<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Shares Down Amid Uncertainty  </HEADLINE>
By DIRK BEVERIDGE, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- The uncertainties gripping Taiwan shook
its stock market today, with many shares falling as far as possible
on fears of a war with China but a few rallying on hopes
President-elect Chen Shui-bian might forge greater economic ties
between the rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The government stepped in and bought shares to help contain the
damage, but warned investors it could not keep buying indefinitely
against a tide of selling.
</P>
<P>
   Taipei shares finished with a loss of 2.6 percent -- bouncing
back from an early drop of 3.2 percent in the first session since
Saturday's vote that will end more than a half-century of
governance by the ruling Nationalist Party.
</P>
<P>
   Shares were able to drop only as much as 3.5 percent under
emergency measures announced Sunday night by Finance Minister Paul
Chiu -- and most companies listed on the Taipei exchange fell by the
maximum from the outset.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's Weighted Price Index lost 227.22 points, closing at
8,536.05.
</P>
<P>
   But the mood was not entirely gloomy. Despite massive red ink in
much of the stock market, shipping companies rallied on Chen's
comments that he would like to see Taiwan and China agree on direct
air and sea links.
</P>
<P>
   People and goods traveling between the two now must pass through
an outside destination -- often Hong Kong -- which costs businesses
time and money.
</P>
<P>
   Shares also dipped in Hong Kong, where the Hang Seng Index was
off by almost 1 percent late Monday morning after falling even
further from the start on war worries.
</P>
<P>
   Indicating Taiwan's political upheaval seemed like a market
threat of similar magnitude to the devastating earthquake in
September that closed share dealings for several days, Chiu decided
to halve the normal 7 percent limit for one-day stock drops for the
next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Chiu did not alter the daily limit of 7 percent increases,
however.
</P>
<P>
   The government also said it would intervene and buy shares if
necessary to try to protect prices and the Taiwan dollar -- and the
central bank moved quickly to stabilize the currency.
</P>
<P>
   Amid heavy foreign exchange dealings -- with investors dumping
the Taiwanese currency and the central bank buying it -- the Taiwan
dollar was off by only a fraction of a percentage point at the rate
of 30.795 to the U.S. dollar early in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Although the government also intervened and bought shares, Vice
Finance Minister Yen Ching-chang appealed for investors to stay
calm and accept the election outcome.
</P>
<P>
   If traders keep selling, Taiwan could not indefinitely keep
buying, Yen warned.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts predicted that after a day or two of serious
drops, investors might sense some good buying opportunities, as
they have so often in the past when Taiwan faced various calamities
and the market overreacted.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's win has stirred concerns of aggravated tensions with
China, which is disturbed by his party's pro-independence stance.
China views Taiwan as a rebel province and says it must reunify
with the mainland at some point.
</P>
<P>
   ''The question is how many days of steep selling we're going to
see,'' said Peter Kurz, the top executive in Taiwan for Wall Street
investment bank Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   The big sellers may have bailed out last week, when Taiwan spent
the equivalent of $3.3 billion to contain a share slide.
</P>
<P>
   China responded to Chen's election by issuing a conciliatory
wait-and-see statement -- which stood in stark contrast to Beijing's
earlier saber-rattling -- and that could help prevent a massacre on
the market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
