<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Arrives in India  </HEADLINE>
By TERENCE HUNT, AP White House Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
   DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) -- President Clinton opened the first trip
of an American president to poverty-ridden Bangladesh on Monday but
scrubbed a showcase visit to a rural village because of security
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   A brilliant sun and humid heat greeted Clinton and Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright as they stepped off Air Force One after
the flight from New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
   Bangladesh, a Muslim nation of 120 million is the most densely
populated country in the world and one of the poorest, with a per
capita income of about $1 a day.
</P>
<P>
   In an article written for the Times of India, Clinton saluted
Bangladesh for ''making great strides lifting citizens out of
poverty, raising the status of women, strengthening democracy,
standing against terrorism and weapons of mass destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   A 21-gun salute boomed as Clinton walked down a red carpet to an
arrival ceremony, where he was greeted by Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina and President Shahabuddin Ahmed. A military band played the
national anthem of the United States and Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people, many of them schoolchildren wearing
different color uniforms and waving American and Bangladeshi flags,
lined Clinton's motorcade route.
</P>
<P>
   The road from the airport to town, about six miles, was cleared
of all traffic and police, troops and paramilitary forces were
posted with automatic weapons every 30 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's first stop was a meeting with the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours before starting the daylong trip to Bangladesh, the
White House canceled a stop at the village of Joypura, about 20
miles from the capital of Dhaka. Presidential spokesman Joe
Lockhart cited concerns raised by security experts and another
official said there were fears about taking the president by
helicopter over a dense, tropical forest where security could not
be guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Clinton was confining his visit to Dhaka and meet with
Joypura villagers there.
</P>
<P>
   Also before his arrival, protesters in New Delhi burned an
effigy of the president. In the northern region of Kashmir, police
beat back separatists seeking to reach New Delhi and draw attention
to their cause.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was accompanied to South Asia by his daughter Chelsea
and his mother-in-law, Dorothy Rodham. Hillary Rodham Clinton
stayed home to campaign for the Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's six-day journey to India, Bangladesh and Pakistan
brought him to one of the poorest regions of the world struggling
with population growth, malnutrition, illiteracy and poor health.
Adding to the suffering, India entered the new century with more
AIDs cases than any other nation -- 4 million people are HIV
positive.
</P>
<P>
   In the capital, the protesters chanted, ''Death to Bill Clinton.
Death to the imperialism of multinationals.'' While most Indians
welcome Clinton's visit, several nationalist and communist groups
protest that he will push American economic interests at India's
expense. In Kashmir, Indian police lobbed tear gas against the
separatists.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will spend most of his time in India -- five cities in
five days -- seeking a new relationship to replace Cold War
suspicions. Bangladesh was a side trip at the start, and the
president will make a short stop in military-ruled Pakistan on his
way home.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials say there is a possibility Clinton will
stop in Geneva to meet Syrian President Hafez al-Assad on March 26,
but the chief of staff, John Podesta, refused comment.
</P>
<P>
   In Bangladesh, Clinton planned to salute its efforts to combat
poverty and build an inclusive democracy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his session with the prime minister, Clinton also
had meetings scheduled with the opposition leader, and a state
dinner. He was expected to offer $97 million in food aid for
Bangladesh and $84 million in grants to support clean-energy
projects in Bangladesh, India and Nepal, White House spokesman Mike
Hammer said.
</P>
<P>
   Searching for foreign policy achievements as his presidency
winds down, Clinton has been frustrated in trying to promote peace
in the Middle East and Northern Ireland. He faces huge obstacles,
as well, in trying to narrow differences between India and
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   They have fought two wars over the last half century over rival
claims for the Himalayan territory of Kashmir. They clashed again
last summer when Pakistan-based fighters seized mountain peaks
inside India. More than 1,000 combatants died before Clinton
persuaded then-Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif of Pakistan to withdraw
the forces.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring world pressure, India and Pakistan both tested nuclear
devices in 1998, dramatically heightening the stakes of their old
feud. Clinton acknowledged the dimensions of the threat when he
described the region as ''perhaps the most dangerous place in the
world today because of tensions over Kashmir and the possession of
nuclear weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's national security adviser, Sandy Berger, said
neither side has deployed nuclear weapons. ''That's an important
step not taken,'' he said. But neither is willing to sign a nuclear
test ban treaty.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton has pledged to press for nuclear restraint, the
administration has sketched modest goals for his trip.
</P>
<P>
   India and the United States are to sign a ''vision statement''
outlining the goals and principles that should guide the
relationship. White House officials say the visit to India is long
overdue, delayed because of political turnover in India and then
the nuclear tests in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
