<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foca Trial To Begin in The Hague  </HEADLINE>
By JEROME SOCOLOVSKY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) -- Some of the rape victims were as
young as 12. Prosecutors say the Bosnian Muslim women were detained
in a local high school, a sports hall and private homes and
sexually assaulted nightly by soldiers and paramilitaries.
</P>
<P>
   The Foca trial, which starts today at the Yugoslav war crimes
tribunal, marks the first time an international court will judge a
case about sexual enslavement. It is part of an attempt by U.N.
prosecutors to make wartime sexual assault one of the most grievous
and punishable crimes under international law.
</P>
<P>
   Radomir Kovac, Dragoljub Kunarac and Zoran Vukovic are charged
with up to 50 counts of rape, torture, enslavement and outrages
upon personal dignity in the Foca case, named after the
southeastern Bosnian city where the crimes allegedly took place.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants, former fighters on the Bosnian Serb side, have
pleaded innocent to the war crimes and crimes against humanity
charges, which carry a maximum sentence of life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, the defendants set up the
''quasi-brothels'' or ''rape factories'' in the summer of 1992
where dozens of women were detained. Nightly, women allegedly were
brutally beaten and forced to have sex with soldiers and
paramilitaries. They were gang-raped, tortured, and often forced to
give birth, prosecutors say.
</P>
<P>
   At least 10 rape victims are expected to testify at the trial
with privacy measures such as screens and voice scrambling. In
court documents, the women are identified with witness codes such
as FWS-48, FWS-50 and FWS-75.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say many victims suffered permanent physical harm in
addition to the lifetime mental torment caused by their sexual
assault.
</P>
<P>
   Although Foca was the most notorious case of systematic rape in
the 1992-95 war, there were reports of rape by all sides in dozens
of camps across Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, a European Community commission estimated 20,000 rape
victims in the conflict. The Bosnian government put the figure at
50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav tribunal was established by the U.N. Security
Council in 1993 after the discovery of Bosnian camps where
prisoners were murdered, raped and tortured. Judges have handed
down sentences of up to 45 years to 14 defendants from all sides of
the war.
</P>
<P>
   The only previous known prosecution of forced prostitution
occurred in 1948 in Batavia, now Jakarta, Indonesia. A Dutch
colonial court tried Japanese military defendants for raping Dutch
women prisoners during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: International Criminal Tribunal for the Former
Yugoslavia: http://www.un.org/icty
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
