<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senegal Opposition Leads Election  </HEADLINE>
By GLENN McKENZIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAKAR, Senegal (AP) -- Excited supporters of opposition
presidential candidate Abdoulaye Wade danced and sang in the
streets of the capital today after unofficial results showed him
leading the incumbent in a run-off election.
</P>
<P>
   But with no official returns announced, a foreign election
observer cautioned it was too early to call a winner.
</P>
<P>
   There was no reaction from President Abdou Diouf's party, which
has ruled for 40 years. However, truckloads of paramilitary police
were quietly deployed overnight around the presidential palace and
other key government installations in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Although at least one foreign election observer said late Sunday
it was too early to say who had won, journalists at Senegal's
popular private radio stations were broadcasting early returns
gathered from individual voting stations in the cities, which
showed Wade leading Diouf.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary official results were not expected until Tuesday or
later.
</P>
<P>
   During the first round of voting on Feb. 27, Diouf won 41
percent with good rural returns, while opponent Wade trailed with
30 percent on the strength of strong urban support.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, however, Wade has won the backing of five of the six
other opposition candidates from the previous round.
</P>
<P>
   Wade told journalists early today that he was not yet claiming
victory, but believed ''strongly that I have won this election.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a day of liberation, a dawn of a new era,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 supporters danced and sang Senegalese pop songs
outside Wade's home in suburban Dakar while thousands of others
honked horns and raced through the streets in cars, motorcycles and
on foot carrying posters and flags.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the campaign headquarters of Diouf's Socialist Party
was nearly abandoned Sunday evening, although a worker said the
party was confident of making up for urban losses in villages and
towns of the interior.
</P>
<P>
   The elections were a test of Senegal's reputation as one of
Africa's most peaceful, democratic states.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of violence, ballot theft and other irregularities
around the country marred Sunday's vote. Several injuries and
dozens of arrests were reported.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Cesar Sibailly, an Ivorian election observer from the
Association of African Jurists, said late Sunday that it was too
early to say who had won -- or whether the results would be fair.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said he and other observers were satisfied that
voting had taken place relatively openly and peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the showdown, Wade accused Diouf of preparing to
fix the elections and warned of a spontaneous revolution by angry
voters if he lost.
</P>
<P>
   After voting in the capital, Wade, 70, who describes himself as
a liberal, told his supporters Sunday not to initiate violence but
to fight back if attacked.
</P>
<P>
   He also warned Senegalese to ''remain vigilant'' for ''serious
election anomalies.''
</P>
<P>
   Although turnout figures were unavailable, there appeared to be
fewer voters in Dakar than during the first round. Some voters had
been unable to return on time from Muslim festivities in other
parts of Senegal.
</P>
<P>
   Diouf's backers say he should be re-elected because under his
leadership Senegal has become one of Africa's most stable nations
with a vibrant trading economy despite few natural resources.
</P>
<P>
   Critics accuse Diouf of fostering a corrupt elite and ignoring
the country's poor since he became president in 1981. In recent
years, unemployment and crime have increased in the coastal
capital.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: CIA World Factbook on Senegal:
http://www.odci.gov/cia/publications/factbook/sg.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
