<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maine Syrup Industry Changing  </HEADLINE>
By ANN S. KIM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOWHEGAN, Maine (AP) -- Working amid the steam and loud hum of
the evaporator is Jeremy Steeves' favorite part of his family's
maple syrup businesses. He constantly checks the levels of the pan,
the temperature and sugar level as watery sap is transformed into
golden syrup.
</P>
<P>
   This is a busy time for maple syrup producers like Steeves in
Somerset County, where an estimated 1 million sugar maples are
tapped in the thick North Woods stretching to the Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's kind of intense because the sap's running. You have to
keep things going,'' he said. ''There's always that urgency.''
</P>
<P>
   Somerset, which produces 90 percent of Maine's maple syrup and
more than any other county in the United States, has
single-handedly propelled Maine's syrup production to new heights.
</P>
<P>
   And maple syrup producers like Steeves hope to boost the profile
of Maine, which ranks third behind Vermont and New York for maple
syrup production in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of people don't even know they make syrup in Maine,''
Steeves said outside the sugar shack at Strawberry Hill Farms.
</P>
<P>
   The market for syrup has grown over the last 15 years as
producers have started selling overseas, particularly in Asia and
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Overall production in North America has grown from around 3.5
million gallons to 6.5 million gallons since the mid-1980s, the
Quebec Maple Syrup Producers Federation says.
</P>
<P>
   In Maine, production has grown from 113,000 gallons in 1993 to
187,000 gallons last year, and so many taps are being added that
some Mainers see the day when they surpass New York's production.
</P>
<P>
   The sweet taste evokes picture-postcard images of sturdy Yankees
hauling buckets of sap and cooking it over wood fires.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is more prosaic. The sap flows in miles of practical
blue plastic tubing that runs from tree to tree. It flows into
larger tubes and pipes before being pumped up to the stainless
steel evaporator.
</P>
<P>
   The fires are fueled by oil, which slashes the costs of chopping
and hauling wood and makes the temperature easier to control.
</P>
<P>
   ''We couldn't do all this business with pails,'' says John
Steeves, Jeremy's father. ''It would be like using a rowboat to go
to England. It's just not practical.''
</P>
<P>
   With about 7,000 taps, Strawberry Hill Farm is considered small
for a commercial operation in a county where some producers have
100,000 taps.
</P>
<P>
   Somerset County had more than 710,000 taps listed in the U.S.
Department of Agriculture's 1997 census, and as much as a quarter
of production may go unreported, said Aubrey Davis, director of the
New England Agricultural Statistics Service in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The county with the most taps in Vermont, Franklin, has about
452,000 and St. Lawrence County in New York has about 152,000.
</P>
<P>
   Even though syrup is big business, the basic idea is the same --
remove enough water from about 40 gallons of sap to turn it into
one gallon of syrup. Some producers put the sap through a reverse
osmosis machine that pushes the water out of the sap. Others, like
the Steeves, boil it.
</P>
<P>
   Before the sap is boiled in an evaporator, it's as thin as water
and just a bit cloudy. With just 2 percent to 4 percent sugar,
there's only the faintest bit of sweetness. As the sap moves
through the machine, water is removed and the color turns to its
familiar amber.
</P>
<P>
   Precision counts because there's a window of only about 30
seconds between the time the water is cooked off and the syrup
turns to sugar, Jeremy Steeves said. And if the syrup burns, it
ruins the custom-made pans, which could take more than six months
to replace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-20-00 0122 </TRAILER>
