<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ridge Again Veep Prospect  </HEADLINE>
By JIM STRADER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) -- After Gov. Tom Ridge led George W. Bush
on an early morning run along the Susquehanna River, the Texas
governor was asked about his Pennsylvania counterpart's fit as a
''running mate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush refused to take the bait, joking that Ridge was simply his
''jogging mate.''
</P>
<P>
   The governors' playfulness last summer was among the first signs
of election season ''veepstakes'' speculation, with Ridge a strong
Republican vice presidential prospect, just as he was in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his friendship with Bush -- and with his father,
former President Bush -- Ridge offers some potential pluses for the
White House ticket, but also a few drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Most attractive would be Ridge's popular leadership in
Pennsylvania, likely to be a major swing state in November, where
he is serving his second and final term as governor.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ridge would make good political sense,'' said Larry Bartels, a
political science professor at Princeton University, who views
Pennsylvania as a fall battleground.
</P>
<P>
   As governor, Ridge has been successful on economic development,
welfare reform and enacting a number of crime bills. He has won
limited changes in education, seeing charter schools and academic
standards approved but failing to gain legislative support for
tuition vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   He also would be an interesting choice because of his views on
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Ridge is Roman Catholic, but he believes in abortion rights -- a
stance that could help Bush move to the political middle after
courting conservative Republicans to defeat Arizona Sen. John
McCain for the presidential nomination. Bush opposes abortion, but
he would allow exceptions in cases of rape, incest or when
continuing the pregnancy would jeopardize a woman's life.
</P>
<P>
   Bartels said the difference of opinion could produce grumbling
among GOP hardliners but that Ridge's selection could broaden the
ticket's appeal by moving it away from the religious right.
</P>
<P>
   Ridge boasts working-class roots, a Harvard degree earned on
scholarship, decorations for combat service in Vietnam, a part-time
career as a prosecutor and 12 years in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   A political moderate, he has demonstrated ability to reach
independents in Pennsylvania, a valuable asset given how those
voters helped boost McCain in the early GOP primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats outnumbered Republicans 54 percent to 41 percent in
the Erie-based congressional district that sent Ridge to Washington
in his last election in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, GOP presidential nominee Bob Dole looked at Ridge as a
possible running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Ridge said he ''raised some reservations'' about joining the
ticket, even as Dole narrowed his list of prospects, but did not
withdraw his name. Dole wound up choosing Jack Kemp.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was that winnowing-out process,'' Ridge said.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, the governor has remained aloof, careful not
to betray too much interest in the No. 2 spot while not quite
discouraging speculation.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's far too early,'' Ridge said. ''It is the politics of June
or July that will dictate the choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Without naming names, he said Bush has a ''very deep bench''
from which to choose, including ''strong and supportive
governors,'' members of Congress and people outside government.
</P>
<P>
   Ridge said he would not automatically say ''Yes'' if Bush popped
the question.
</P>
<P>
   ''There'll be some political matters that have to be weighed,''
he said. ''At the end of the day, it will be as much a personal
decision, a family decision, as a political one. ... I enjoy being
governor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
