<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Says GOP Must Make Peace  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM C. MANN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former President Ford says George W. Bush and
John McCain must heal the wounds of their bitter campaign for the
Republican presidential nomination if the party is to have a chance
of winning back the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The 86-year-old GOP elder statesman said victory also requires
that Bush, who emphasized his conservatism in defeating McCain,
bring the party back toward the center, as Ronald Reagan did in
1980 to defeat President Carter.
</P>
<P>
   In a television interview aired Sunday, Ford also speculated
that McCain, a senator from Arizona, would agree to be Texas Gov.
Bush's running mate if Bush asked properly. McCain has said
repeatedly that he would not run for vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the Republicans are going to win, Bush and McCain have to
get together. And I'm an optimist. I think they will,'' Ford said
on ABC's ''This Week.'' ''And I can be very frank with my
Republican friends: Unless they move back into the middle, and have
a big-tent philosophy, they'll continue to lose the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford said McCain, by attracting hordes of new, largely
independent and less conservative voters to GOP primaries, ''did a
great favor to the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   In winning nine of 13 Republican contests on Super Tuesday,
March 7, and earlier primaries, notably South Carolina's, Bush
emphasized his conservative credentials to appeal to the party's
right. Some analysts contend he portrayed himself as far more
conservative than he is, which could make a more centrist position
in the general election difficult to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on his experience in his nomination campaign against
Reagan in 1976, Ford said he thinks Bush has left himself
sufficient flexibility. Ford narrowly defeated Reagan, then lost
the general election to Jimmy Carter, who then lost to Reagan in
1980.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan ''was to the right of me, but when he came to 1980, he
moved over toward the middle, and his friends on the right ...
didn't abandon him,'' Ford said. I think the Bush supporters could
do the same.''
</P>
<P>
   In prescribing ''reconciliation and a good, strong
partnership,'' the former president said Bush and McCain must
realize ''that politics is a tough, tough arena. And you don't hold
grudges if you want to win the big ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, he said: ''Bush has to be magnanimous. He has to
modify some of his views in order to accommodate the views of
McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the running-mate question, Ford said: ''I suspect that if
Governor Bush asked him on a patriotic, Republican request, Senator
McCain would probably say yes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-20-00 0133 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000320.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York FBI chief, expert in organized crime, retiring  </HEADLINE>
By PAT MILTON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Lewis Schiliro is putting away his FBI badge
after 25 years of helping to dismantle the mob, track terrorists
and steer the FBI into a shrinking world where the next case might
be 3,000 miles away or on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ''We used to chase fugitives over fences. Today, we chase them
through cyberspace,'' the head of the FBI in New York said in an
interview shortly before his retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Schiliro noted it's largely due to FBI Director Louis Freeh,
once his roommate at the FBI academy in Quantico, Va., that the
agency is now fighting terrorism and white-collar crime worldwide
in coordination with foreign police.
</P>
<P>
   ''Agents now travel all over the world ... . For us it was a big
deal if we went into New Jersey,'' Schiliro said.
</P>
<P>
   He is one of the top experts on organized crime -- testifying 11
days at the trial of mob boss John Gotti -- and as an assistant
director of the FBI heads the agency's largest field office, in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh called Schiliro ''the very best of the FBI,'' saying the
agency has benefited from ''his street experience, his judgment and
his unbending reflection of the highest ethical values.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White of the Southern District in New York
also praised Schiliro. ''In his own self-effacing way he has
successfully handled some of the FBI's biggest and most difficult
cases,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Among Schiliro's cases were the World Trade Center bombing, the
crash of TWA Flight 800 and the pursuit of Osama bin Laden and the
terrorists he allegedly led to carry out the deadly bombings of two
U.S. embassies in Africa on Aug. 7, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer whose father was a plumber, Schiliro joined the FBI in
Cleveland in 1975, a time when terrorism seemed a problem only in
faraway lands and organized crime had more power than the mayor in
some parts of New York.
</P>
<P>
   He came to the city just as the FBI was beginning an assault on
organized crime, targeting leaders of New York's five Mafia
families with federal racketeering laws that allowed life sentences
for operating a continuing criminal enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Schiliro discovered that the mob had such a tight grip on the
city that it was impossible to put up a building, open a restaurant
or collect garbage without paying a bribe to the Mafia.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you did not make payoffs to the right unions, your cement
would not be poured or your bricks would not be delivered,'' he
said. ''You would have to become part of the corruption. If you
didn't play ball, you would get hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Schiliro, a reserved man, made his mark against the Mafia more
than a decade ago when he supervised the FBI's work in the famous
Pizza Connection case, in which mobsters delivered drugs along with
pizzas.
</P>
<P>
   With hundreds of successful cases over the last 25 years, the
FBI has largely demystified the mob, relying heavily on electronic
surveillance to convict crime figures with their own words. It also
pierced the wall of silence around the Mafia's hierarchy; now it's
not uncommon for organized crime's ''soldiers'' to snitch on one
another.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of a life sentence without parole is one of the FBI's
most powerful weapons. It was used, for example, to convince
Gambino family underboss Salvatore ''Sammy the Bull'' Gravano to
admit two dozen murders and help put his boss, John Gotti, behind
bars.
</P>
<P>
   Schiliro says that with constant prosecution, the Cosa Nostra
can be reduced to a street gang with little more influence than any
bunch of disorganized thugs.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Mafia is trying to redefine itself, looking for
white-collar partners for illegal Wall Street stock schemes and
tapping Russian organized crime for its expertise in international
racketeering.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have forced them out of their traditional areas,'' said
Schiliro, adding that the mob's power has been reduced in the
construction, carting and garment industries, as well as in trade
unions and the Fulton fish market.
</P>
<P>
   ''They will look for new ways to make money,'' he said. ''That
is why we see them in health care fraud, penny stock trading.
</P>
<P>
   ''Looking back on it, we waged a good battle,'' said Schiliro.
''But we haven't won yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Schiliro, 51, plans to work at MBNA, a major credit card company
based in Wilmington, Del. He said he decided to retire early, at
the end of March, partly for financial reasons; this fall he will
have a daughter entering medical school, a son entering college and
another daughter, an attorney, getting married.
</P>
<P>
   He admits he will miss the job.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been a front row seat to the best show on Broadway,'' he
said. ''I would not change anything in my career. I just wish it
had lasted longer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
