<BODY>
<HEADLINE> How India Strike Disrupted Deal  </HEADLINE>
By FARID HOSSAIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) -- Just ask Data Magfur whether
Bangladesh's repeated political strikes are good for business.
</P>
<P>
   Magfur's chance to start a shoe leather export business was
ruined by one such strike. He is just one of many Bangladeshis who
suffer when transportation and business shuts down as opposition
parties try to cripple the country to force new elections. Business
leaders say the strikes, which can leave foreign investors hunkered
in their hotels for fear of street mobs, are sapping the country's
potential for economic growth and discouraging foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
   There were 30 such strike days last year and five so far this
year. An opposition alliance led by Khaleda Zia is trying to force
out the government of Sheikh Hasina, who used the same tactics
before she was elected in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   American business is interested in investing in Bangladesh,
particularly in its undeveloped natural gas fields, and President
Clinton's visit today will focus attention on the potential of one
of the world's poorest countries.
</P>
<P>
   Magfur, 27, runs his father's pesticide business but had a plan
to start his own leather export company. His prospective German
clients were in Dhaka on Feb. 2 when a strike was called, and they
lost interest quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had an appointment with a German business team at the office
of Dhaka Chamber of Commerce and Industry,'' Magfur told The
Associated Press. ''One of the German businessmen, I was told, was
interested in buying leather products from Bangladesh.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I was both excited and nervous. This was my first business
negotiation on my own,'' he said. ''But all my hopes faded the
moment I read in the newspapers that the opposition had called for
a general strike that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Magfur lives in Uttar, 12 miles from the Motijheel commercial
district where he was to meet the Germans.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I refused to give up,'' he said. ''I hired a rickshaw to
travel all the way to Motijheel. It took me nearly two hours, a
30-minute journey by car.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I reached the chamber's office I was told that the
meeting was canceled. The Germans could not come out of their hotel
because of the strike,'' he said. ''They were leaving the next day.
I became desperate and rescheduled my meeting with them at their
hotel in the evening.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the meeting occurred, he said, the Germans were more
interested in talking about the strike and fears of future
disruptions. ''The Germans wanted to know more about our political
situation than my business proposals,'' said Magfur.
</P>
<P>
   One of the visitors asked Magfur if it was safe to do business
in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hardly had any good answer. I tried to reassure him. But I
guess he was not convinced. The businessmen returned home learning
bad things about our country. That's what I concluded watching
their faces.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he said, the pesticide business is suffering losses
because of the frequent strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Because pesticide is linked to the crop season, ''we can sell it
only six months in a year,'' said Magfur. ''So we need to supply
the chemicals to the farmers when they need them.''
</P>
<P>
   The five strike days in February stopped shipping at an
important time, Magfur said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have already lost some business,'' he said. ''Last year we
lost at least 20 percent of our business because of strikes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
