<DOCNO> APW20000320.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Episcopal bishop takes a turn as a congressional intern  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Thomas Shaw is not your average Capitol Hill
intern.
</P>
<P>
   He's a 54-year-old Episcopal bishop, leading a 90,000-strong
diocese in eastern Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, who draws stares as he hustles around the Capitol in a
long black robe, a heavy crucifix hanging from his neck, is
believed to be the first clergyman to be a congressional intern.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to learn more about the role of religion in government
while working for Rep. Amo Houghton, a Republican from western New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to know how Washington works because I really want the
Episcopal church to have the most effective voice possible,'' Shaw
said, his calm, quiet tones almost drowned out by the clatter in
Houghton's office.
</P>
<P>
   Houghton and Shaw became friends 20 years ago when Houghton was
leading his family's Fortune 500 company, Corning Inc., which makes
glass and ovenware. Houghton, who once considered becoming an
Episcopalian priest, attended retreats in Cambridge, Mass., where
Shaw is a monk.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw eventually presided over the marriage of Houghton and his
wife Priscilla, joking that Houghton was the only Republican for
whom he had asked his congregation to pray.
</P>
<P>
   ''That makes me feel good, because you only pray for sinners,''
Houghton said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   The 74-year-old Houghton said Shaw approached him about coming
to Washington after last year's impeachment battle. He recalled his
reaction as, ''My gosh, that would be a breath of fresh air.''
</P>
<P>
   He allows that Shaw is not treated like a typical intern.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't expect him to open the mail and run errands,'' the
seven-term lawmaker said. ''I want to make sure he sees, hears and
rubs shoulders and is conversant with some of the issues we deal
with every day down here.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's interest in religion and politics isn't new. Early last
year, as the battle over President Clinton's impeachment raged in
Washington and bombs rained down over Kosovo, Shaw called Houghton
and asked how the church should respond.
</P>
<P>
   He ended up holding a vigil and dialogue attended by some 400
people at St. Paul's Cathedral in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ''People were confused,'' Shaw said. ''It's always important for
Christians to come together and pray during times of great
division.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw and Houghton saw Clinton's impeachment as having deeply
religious themes -- sin, forgiveness and redemption. Houghton was
one of only a handful of Republicans who voted against impeachment,
pushing instead for a strongly worded censure.
</P>
<P>
   Houghton praised Shaw as the only church leader he knew who
would hold open discussions on hot-button issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''The church cannot just consider itself doing its job if it has
a solid congregation,'' Houghton said. ''It's got to reach out into
the world and relate.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw started his job Feb. 17, about the time religion took
center stage in the Republican presidential primary, with John
McCain claiming Christian conservatives had too much influence in
the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw said he ''doesn't put a lot of stock'' in the political
rhetoric involved in that debate. But he added he disagrees with
the focus that people in the Christian right place on issues like
prayer in schools.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think fundamentally whether we have prayer every day
in public schools is going to make a big difference in social
change in this country. I do think that if the government and the
churches were to join together to eradicate racism in this country
it would make a huge difference,'' said Shaw, who recently
accompanied Houghton to a civil rights march in Selma, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Also at that march was Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga. Lewis, a civil
rights activist, is co-chairman with Houghton of the Faith and
Politics Institute, a nonpartisan, interfaith group set up to
provide political leaders with opportunities for moral reflection
and spiritual community.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think what Amo is doing in having the bishop here is
tremendously important,'' Lewis said. ''The church needs to know
what's going on here in Washington. He will go home and spread that
word.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw will ends his month-long internship at the end of March and
will return to Boston. Until then, he is absorbing all he can,
especially on two issues dear to him: children living in poverty
and relief for the hungry.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to know what's happening in the world,'' Shaw said.
''That means we have to be out there in the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-20-00 0142 </TRAILER>
