<HEADLINE> 'Brockovich' Holds Court in Movies  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GERMAIN, AP Entertainment Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Add legal heavy-hitter to Julia Roberts' list
of box-office accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ''Erin Brockovich,'' Roberts' drama about a pollution lawsuit,
premiered as the nation's top movie with $28.2 million in its
opening weekend, according to studio estimates Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The sci-fi rescue thriller ''Mission to Mars,'' last weekend's
No. 1 movie, slipped to second place with $10.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   The horror story ''Final Destination'' opened in third place
with $10.2 million. The movie is about a youth whose premonition
about an exploding plane saves himself and other passengers but
prompts the Grim Reaper to stalk them.
</P>
<P>
   ''Erin Brockovich'' is based on the real-life story of a
California legal clerk who leads a crusade against Pacific Gas &AMP;
Electric over tainted water.
</P>
<P>
   The role was a bit of a risk for Roberts. She has made a string
of romantic hits, including last year's ''Notting Hill'' and
''Runaway Bride,'' but has had trouble finding an audience in
dramas such as ''Mary Reilly'' or ''Michael Collins.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Erin Brockovich'' drew critical praise and was marketed
wisely, with movie ads highlighting the humor and sharp tongue of
Roberts' character.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no surprise when Julia Roberts is No. 1 at the box
office, given her track record,'' said Paul Dergarabedian,
president of Exhibitor Relations Co. Inc., which tracks movie
admissions. ''This proves why she's the top female draw, right now,
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing in 2,847 cinemas, the movie averaged an impressive
$9,905 a theater, compared with $3,562 in 3,060 theaters for
''Mission to Mars'' and $3,943 in 2,587 theaters for ''Final
Destination.''
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Steven Soderbergh, the film also minimizes the
courtroom drama and keeps the focus on Roberts, who plays an
impoverished, lowbrow mother of three who cusses constantly and
wears sexy outfits.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's a superstar, and this is what superstars are all
about,'' said Nikki Rocco, head of distribution for Universal,
which released ''Erin Brockovich.'' ''People like her not only in
romantic pictures, but she can take a true story like this and turn
it into pure entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oscars continued to boost business for ''American Beauty,''
which crossed the $100 million mark. It took in $2.9 million for a
total of $102.7 million. That was up nearly $28 million since
''American Beauty'' scored a leading eight Oscar nominations on
Feb. 15, including best picture, actor and actress.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Cider House Rules,'' with a best picture nod and six other
nominations, added $2.4 million this weekend and has grossed $45.7
million, double its take before the Academy Award nominations came
out.
</P>
<P>
   Another best picture nominee, ''The Sixth Sense,'' was expected
to pass ''The Empire Strikes Back'' and become one of the 10
top-grossing movies of all time soon after next Sunday's Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Sixth Sense'' took in $1.2 million over the weekend,
putting its 33-week total at $288.4 million. That was up about $9
million since the Oscar nominations and just $2 million shy of the
gross for ''The Empire Strikes Back.''
</P>
<P>
   Estimated ticket sales for Friday through Sunday at North
American theaters, according to Exhibitor Relations Co. Inc. Final
figures were to be released today.
</P>
<P>
   1. ''Erin Brockovich,'' $28.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   2. ''Mission to Mars,'' $10.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   3. ''Final Destination,'' $10.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   4. ''My Dog Skip,'' $5.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   5. ''The Ninth Gate,'' $3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   6. ''The Whole Nine Yards,'' $3.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   7. ''American Beauty,'' $2.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   8. ''The Cider House Rules,'' $2.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   9. ''Snow Day,'' $2.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   10. ''The Tigger Movie,'' $1.9 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
