<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alabama Town Slowly Dying  </HEADLINE>
By JAY REEVES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   EMELLE, Ala. (AP) -- This tiny town is dying, but not for the
reason many expected.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, Emelle was ground zero in a controversy over the
sprawling hazardous waste landfill just outside the city limits.
</P>
<P>
   Critics said the landfill would poison the entire region if it
leaked, slowly wiping out life. The TV show ''60 Minutes'' paid a
visit, along with legislators, other leaders and activists. A
former state attorney general dubbed the site ''America's pay
toilet.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmental outrage didn't succeed in closing what was then
known as the nation's largest hazardous waste dump, but a state tax
and a series of federal regulations decimated business during the
'90s, wiping out nearly 340 jobs. Most of the trucks that used to
roll north along Alabama 17 to the dump quit coming.
</P>
<P>
   The change has all but killed Emelle, population 63, located in
rural west Alabama just a few miles from the Mississippi state
line.
</P>
<P>
   The only grocer retired a couple of years ago and no one opened
a new store. An old gas station sits empty with a ''For Sale'' sign
in the window. City Hall -- a stucco building paid for with
hazardous waste dumping fees -- is locked and virtually empty.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you run out of gas here, you're out of gas,'' said resident
Rosie Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of business at the Waste Management-owned landfill,
which opened in 1977, was good for the town environmentally,
according to postmaster Janet Hutcherson.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no way to replace the lost jobs, because Emelle
proper doesn't have a single business. Most people work at least 15
miles away in York or Livingston, or even farther away in
Tuscaloosa or Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   ''It hurt a lot of people,'' said Hutcherson.
</P>
<P>
   Landfill manager Rodger Henson has been at the facility since it
was known by its old name, Chemical Waste Management, a now-closed
division of Waste Management. Employment that peaked at 420 is down
to 83.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would have been great to have the business without the
controversy, but that didn't happen,'' said Henson.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak, the landfill took in nearly 800,000 tons of
hazardous waste annually. The site is safe, Henson says; there has
never been a leak.
</P>
<P>
   Former Attorney General Jimmy Evans, who used the ''pay toilet''
nickname, investigated the landfill and tried to get it closed, but
the effort failed.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, only 120,000 tons a year are now buried at the
landfill, a decline of about 85 percent from earlier. Henson
attributes the drop primarily to a $51-a-ton fee that legislators
imposed in 1991 on most waste buried there.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have the highest tax of any facility like ours in the whole
land,'' said Henson.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the tax increase, declining tonnage meant less state
revenue. The landfill generated $35 million in taxes for the state
in the 1991 budget year, but less than $1.5 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law also changed. Companies were required in the early
'90s to reduce the amount of hazardous waste they produced, and
other regulations barred companies from dumping materials that once
were commonly buried at Emelle, such as solvents.
</P>
<P>
   Rosie Bradley has served three terms on the City Council in part
because no one else will run and worries about what will become of
her town. She hopes the landfill holds tight and keeps its deadly
contents away from her children.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jobs or not, we're stuck with that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Environmental Background Information Center:
http://www.ebic.org
</P>
<P>
   Waste Management: http://www.wm.com/corp/frontpage
</P>
</TEXT>
