<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Galilee Awaits Arrival of Pope  </HEADLINE>
By HUGH A. MULLIGAN, AP Special Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
   TABGHA, Israel (AP) -- A few days before Pope John Paul II's
visit, fishermen on the Sea of Galilee dropped off a half dozen
huge catfish at the Franciscan monastery hugging the shore.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't approach the miraculous catch that Peter hauled in
here at the Lord's bidding in the gospel story, but Father Jerome
was delighted, and so was his all-white cat, Bianco.
</P>
<P>
   ''These fishermen don't eat catfish because the Jews deem them
unclean,'' said the friar from Ghana, carving barbecue-size cutlets
with a long knife. ''They are very kind and know we will enjoy
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Father Jerome is custodian of the shrine of the Primacy of
Peter, where in John's gospel the risen Christ cooked a fish
breakfast over a charcoal fire for his disciples and conferred the
leadership of his church on the fisherman who became the first
pope.
</P>
<P>
   Busloads of German pilgrims gathered at the rock called the
''Table of Christ'' where in 1964 photographers with police in wet
pursuit plunged into the lake to capture Paul VI on his knees in
prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Now a third pope, proclaiming the third Christian millennium,
would soon be visiting the holy sites in Galilee, recalling so many
of the teachings and miracles attributed to Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are nervous, but we will be ready,'' another Franciscan,
busy painting the gate at the traditional site of Peter's house in
Capernaum, called down from a stepladder.
</P>
<P>
   A guide in a brown cowled habit told pilgrims from San Francisco
one of those playful irreverent jokes that friars love to
jump-start their audience's attention: ''Here the Lord cured St.
Peter's mother-in-law, then he immediately left home to follow
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Priests in hard hats and Roman collars running around with
clipboards seemed quite nervous at the altar site above the Mount
of Beatitudes where John Paul II was scheduled to celebrate an
outdoor Mass for an estimated 100,000 faithful on Friday. A few
days before, a canvas roof had collapsed, and work fell behind
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   In the gospel story, Christ fled here to escape the crowds
hoping to see him perform a miracle. It was on this lovely
hillside, now blooming with the first approach of spring in the
Holy Land, that he told his disciples the meek would inherit the
earth, the poor the kingdom of heaven, that mourners would be
comforted and the hungry filled.
</P>
<P>
   Hot dog vendor Danny Laghan, who immigrated to Israel 10 years
ago from Woodmere, Long Island, concerned himself with filling
hungry construction workers. ''You bet, I'd like to see the Pope,''
he enthused. ''For free, I'll serve him a real kosher hot dog,
blessed by a higher authority. Others pay seven shekels ($1.75).
He's a good man, this pope, a man of peace. Shalom to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Danny lives with his wife and three children in new housing in
the nearby ancient village of Korazim, which Jesus denounced in
Matthew's gospel for failing to repent after witnessing him cure
the blind and the sick.
</P>
<P>
   All throughout the Holy Land, the past and present seem to meld
into a seamless garment woven millennia ago by ordinary people. In
Nazareth, at the top of a winding narrow lane in the souk, the Arab
market, a whining buzz saw proclaimed the premises of the carpenter
Waleed Daher.
</P>
<P>
   ''I make fine furniture of oak and mahogany for the high society
of Nazareth, whoever has the shekels,'' he boasted with a laugh.
His business is just a few steps from St. Joseph's monastery, built
over the site where tradition holds that Joseph had his carpentry
shop when Jesus was a child.
</P>
<P>
   Waleed complained that there used to be dozens of carpenters in
the souk, making ''blue baby cradles for tourists,'' but rising
rents have driven them out in favor of upscale fashion boutiques.
</P>
<P>
   The noon angelus bell rang out from the Basilica of the
Annunciation, where on Saturday the Pope will celebrate Mass on the
feast day of the Angel Gabriel announcing to Mary that she was to
be the mother of God.
</P>
<P>
   At exactly the same instant, loudspeakers over a nearby mosque
called Muslims to midday prayer, reminding the Christian tourists
that Nazareth in Galilee, the boyhood home of Jesus, is a
predominantly Arab city. Controversy has flared after Israeli
authorities gave permission to build a new mosque almost in front
of what is considered the largest Christian church in the Middle
East and one of the most sacred Christian shrines.
</P>
<P>
   The fireworks crackling in the narrow streets were not for the
papal visit, but for the four-day Muslim festival of Eid al-Adha.
</P>
<P>
   Vatican flags hang from Nazareth's many convents and pilgrim
guesthouses, but the banner across Paul VI Street, Nazareth's main
thoroughfare named for his visit here in 1964, does not welcome
John Paul II. It was left hanging from a strike of municipal
garbage collectors who had not been paid in two months.
</P>
<P>
   ''Business is very bad,'' complained street peddler Saleh
Qumsieh, selling head scarfs, ''just like Mary wore,'' and
''genuine shepherds' flutes.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We ordered T-shirts with the Pope's picture, but none have
arrived yet,'' he said. ''My brother-in-law already is selling them
in the market in Amman. In this country, you need a miracle just to
do business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-20-00 0156 </TRAILER>
