<DOCNO> APW20000320.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mission Celebrates Swallow Return  </HEADLINE>
By ERICA WERNER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN CAPISTRANO, Calif. (AP) -- The famous swallows were few
and far between, but tourists were out in force to hear the mission
bells ring and celebrate the birds' annual return.
</P>
<P>
   Only six of the white-breasted birds swooped through the grounds
of the crumbling Mission San Juan Capistrano on Sunday as an
estimated 20,000 watched the birds wing back from their winter home
in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'd like to see the birds, we want to see the birds. Were
they here yesterday?'' asked John Grottodden, 27, an engineer from
Torrance.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers welcomed the crowds because admission fees and
revenues from T-shirts and snow cones will help fund a
rehabilitation project, underway since 1991 and still $4 million
short of its $10 million goal.
</P>
<P>
   Mission officials blame scaffolding that rings much of the
building and the construction crews that labor there for a scarcity
of swallows in recent years, though they insist the birds can still
be spotted at dawn and dusk.
</P>
<P>
   Mission administrators also blame a southern Orange County
development boom for pushing the swallows out of their natural
habitat.
</P>
<P>
   Officials tried to coax the birds Sunday by scattering ladybugs
on the mission's rose bushes and by making mud puddles -- ''swallow
wallows'' -- for nest-building. They also built fake ceramic nests
to trick the birds into thinking there were friends nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Legend has it that in the early years of the mission, which was
constructed in 1776 and nearly destroyed by an earthquake in 1812,
untold thousands of swallows blackened the skies around St.
Joseph's day.
</P>
<P>
   Officials hope that when the rehabilitation project is complete
two or three years from now, the birds will return in larger
numbers. And they have faith that the birds will never stop coming
back.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a strange phenomenon of nature that they really do head
back to Capistrano,'' said Gerald J. Miller, mission administrator.
''They've been doing it for thousands of years.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: http://www.missionsjc.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-20-00 0212 </TRAILER>
