<DOCNO> APW20000320.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alabama-Birmingham 78, Miss. St. 72  </HEADLINE>
By LANDON HALL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUGENE, Ore. (AP) -- Holly Holland scored 21 points and Deanna
Jackson added 20 as Alabama-Birmingham built a big second-half lead
and held on to upset Mississippi State 78-72 Sunday night in the
West Regional.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th-seeded Lady Blazers (21-12) will play No. 2 Rutgers in
the regional semifinals in Portland next Saturday. UAB had never
won an NCAA women's tournament game before this year.
</P>
<P>
   LaToya Thomas, the nation's top-scoring freshman in the regular
season at nearly 21 points per game, led third-seeded Mississippi
State (24-8) with 26 points, but fouled out with 50 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Bulldogs were bigger and faster, but were hurt by foul
trouble. Second-leading scorer Jennifer Fambrough picked up her
fourth foul just 2:06 into the second half and played a total of 12
minutes, scoring five points.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who scored a career-high 32 in Friday's 80-79 overtime
win over sixth-seeded Oregon, started slowly but used her long arms
to get shots over Thomas in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Her baseline drive, followed by Holland's 3-pointer, finished an
11-0 run and put the Blazers ahead 60-41 with 8:05 to go.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs rallied, getting within 70-65 on a layup by Angela
Harris with a minute left. But the Blazers hit their free throws
and held onto the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Holland matched Thomas with 12 points in the first half as UAB
took a 39-28 lead. Holland also played solid defense and helped
feed Jackson and center Michelle Smith in the low post.
</P>
<P>
   A turnaround jumper by Thomas pulled Mississippi State to 23-21,
but Jackson's sister, Lisa, started an 8-0 run with a short jumper,
two free throws and a 3-pointer to push the lead to 31-21.
</P>
<P>
   Smith added 17 points for UAB, which shot 58 percent from the
field, and Deanna Jackson had 11 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Harris had 17 points for the Lady Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Blazers played in front of more people the past two
games at McArthur Court than they did all season in Birmingham. The
two-session attendance was 10,510, while the Blazers drew 9,085 in
12 home games at Bartow Arena.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
