<DOCNO> APW20000320.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tiger Finds a New Way To Win  </HEADLINE>
By DOUG FERGUSON, AP Golf Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- The thrilling playoff in Hawaii. The
spectacular comeback in Pebble Beach. By those standards, Tiger
Woods' victory in the Bay Hill Invitational was a snoozer.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean it was any less spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   Going head-to-head against the No. 4 player in the world, Woods
put on a clinic Sunday and whipped Davis Love III by four strokes,
matching Woods' largest margin of victory since his 12-stroke romp
in the 1997 Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ''Remember how he used to grade himself? He about an A-minus
right now, every week,'' said Love, who also finished four back in
the Tour Championship. ''I might go next week and shoot 15-under
and win, but he's been doing it week after week after week after
week.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mentally, right now, he's got the advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods has more than that.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a tight swing, he still hits it farther than most -- 36
yards longer than Love on one hole. He has a 2-iron that he rips
off the tee with alarming precision and the distance of most
players' driver. He has control of his distance with his approach
shots. He has a short game to die for.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder he has so many victories, 18 overall in a career that
began just under four years ago, and 10 of those coming since in
the last 10 months. What Woods really wants is another green
jacket, and that will have to wait a couple of week.
</P>
<P>
   But he is certainly headed in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   Woods didn't make a bogey in the final 34 holes under tough,
tricky winds at Bay Hill. He led by at least two strokes from start
to finish and wound up with a 2-under 70, a serviceable score that
turned out to be all he needed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think I'm heading in the right direction for Augusta,''
Woods said. ''Hopefully, my game is peaking towards that.
Hopefully, next week I'll have some signs that I'm actually playing
a little bit better.''
</P>
<P>
   That can't be good news for the rest of the tour.
</P>
<P>
   Woods now has won 10 times in his last 16 PGA Tour events, and
he has won 23.7 percent of his starts since turning pro in August
1996. He also hasn't finished lower than 18th in a stroke-play
event in a year.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a lot of fun to go out there and compete and know that
you have a chance to win the tournament,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   He speaks from experience.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 13th consecutive time on tour, and 15th time around
the world, that Woods had at least a share of the 54-hole lead and
went on to win. It also was the third straight time since November
he faced Love and experienced little pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Woods had a lot to do with that.
</P>
<P>
   ''I figured if I could go out there and stay away from the big
number and just make a lot of pars, that would put a little
pressure on Davis,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   Love started the day two strokes behind and never got any
closer. He birdied the 18th hole for a 2-under 72 and finished
second in Arnold Palmer's tournament for the third time.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Kendall had a 67 and finished third.
</P>
<P>
   The final round was essentially match play between Woods and
Love, and the result was about as resounding as when Woods beat him
5 and 4 in the semifinals of the Match Play Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Two strokes turned into a 5-stroke advantage after just four
holes. Love made bogey from the bunker, another bogey when his
approach bounced into the rocks guarding the water, and what felt
like a bogey when he couldn't make birdie on the par-5 fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just making silly mistakes,'' said Love, who has gone
nearly two years without winning. ''You're not going to beat Tiger
Woods playing like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The only way to beat Woods is to play like him.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a tough lie in the rough on the first hole, his
delicate chip ran over the lip, and he made the 6-footer coming
back for par. And he made no serious blunders after that.
</P>
<P>
   Love's last hope came after birdies on the 10th and 11th cut the
lead to two, but he found the bunker on the 12th hole with a 3-iron
and couldn't get up-and-down to match Woods' birdie.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was my chance,'' Love said. ''And I didn't take advantage
of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods earned $540,000, pushing his season total to over $2.5
million, which is more anyone made all of last year except for him
and David Duval. He goes to The Players Championship this week, his
final event before the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   Woods will be thinking about Augusta. He's been thinking about
the next major ever since the new year started.
</P>
<P>
   It obviously hasn't been that big of distraction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
