<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton's Village Visit Canceled  </HEADLINE>
By PARVEEN AHMED, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) -- Nearly 50 flights were disrupted at the
international airport, the capital's main roads were closed all day
and villagers who planned to show President Clinton around their
town instead had to travel to the capital city to see him.
Clinton's side trip to the village was scrapped out of concern for
his safety.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 12,000 policemen, soldiers and paramilitary troops in
green camouflage stood on rooftops and every 30 feet or so along
the streets where Clinton's motorcade passed.
</P>
<P>
   American and Bangladeshi military jets roared over the capital
Sunday on practice runs, generating sonic booms and a protest from
the Mayor Mohammad Hanif.
</P>
<P>
   ''The parties concerned should not make the people frightened by
such bangs without prior notice,'' the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Bangladeshis found alternate ways into the city
after police declared main roads off-limits except to those with
special security passes. Doctors at Bangabundu Medical University
Hospital on the motorcade route were given passes allowing them to
drive to work.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have taken Sunday and Monday off as I live on the other side
of town and have to go all around the city to get to work,'' said
Arif Ahmed, who works for a bank in the city center. Some companies
told their employees to stay home.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first visit by an American president to this
impoverished, tropical nation, which has had a democratic
government since 1991 after a history of military coups and
assassinations.
</P>
<P>
   Airport authorities said 46 domestic and international flights
would be delayed during Clinton's landing and takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of leftist parties, opposed to U.S. world trade and
economic policies, planned two demonstrations on Monday, neither of
them near Clinton's route. Students marched several times around
the campus of the University of Dhaka, and leftists said they would
gather to protest at a memorial to the Bangla language.
</P>
<P>
   The night before Clinton's arrival, the White House canceled a
major event of his Bangladesh visit, a trip to the village of
Joypura, to view the results of lending to small enterprises
including dairy production and handicrafts.
</P>
<P>
   A helicopter landing pad had been constructed at the edge of the
village and a stage erected near a 100-year-old banyan tree.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential spokesman Joe Lockhart said security experts had
raised concerns about Clinton's visit to the village, 20 miles from
the capital. Another U.S. official said there were fears the secret
Service could not guarantee the president's safety if he flew over
dense, tropical forest en route to the village.
</P>
<P>
   Security officers have not detailed any specific threat to
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 villagers were bused to the capital, instead, to meet
Clinton at the U.S. Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I understand Clinton was also interested in seeing the village
but I don't know why the visit has been canceled,'' said Muhammad
Yunus, founder of Grameen Bank and a lending program that has been
copied around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ''My first reaction was, ''I can't go to the villagers and face
them and tell them Clinton is not coming here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-20-00 0300 </TRAILER>
