<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monday, March 20, 2000 
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Visits Bangladesh Capital
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) -- President Clinton abruptly canceled travel plans
that would have taken him by helicopter to a village in densely crowded,
impoverished Bangladesh and instead delivered encouragement for a young
democracy and a multimillion dollar aid package in the capital city. The first
American president to ever visit this largely Muslim country, Clinton received a
21-gun salute as he and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright arrived to a
red-carpet greeting. Heavy security was obvious, with many soldiers with rifles
standing alongside the airport runway, and closely spaced along the route into
town.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Foca Trial To Begin in The Hague
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) -- The Foca trial, which starts today at the
Yugoslav war crimes tribunal, marks the first time an international court will
judge a case about sexual enslavement. It is part of an attempt by U.N.
prosecutors to make wartime sexual assault one of the most grievous and
punishable crimes under international law. Radomir Kovac, Dragoljub Kunarac and
Zoran Vukovic are charged with up to 50 counts of rape, torture, enslavement and
outrages upon personal dignity in the Foca case, named after the southeastern
Bosnian city where the crimes allegedly took place.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mozambique Hit by Yet More Flooding
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) -- A river in northern Mozambique burst its banks
after a week of torrential rain, adding to the devastation caused by weeks of
floods in other parts of the impoverished southeast African country. The flooded
Messalo River in Gabo Delgado province severed the main road 70 miles from the
Tanzanian border on Sunday, said Silvano Langa, head of the country's national
disaster management agency. "To my knowledge no lives are at immediate risk, but
crops have been lost," he said. No further details of the extent of the damage
were immediately available.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pope Heads to the Holy Land
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) -- In the first papal visit to the Holy Land in 36 years,
John Paul II embarks on a highly personal pilgrimage today that will see him
retrace the footsteps of Jesus from birth, to baptism to crucifixion. The
weeklong journey through Jordan, Israel and the Palestinian territories was born
out of the pope's desire to see Christendom's holiest sites in this millennial
year, though the mission will be freighted with much broader religious and
political significance in this volatile region.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.N. Human Rights Meeting To Begin
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   GENEVA (AP) -- China and Chechnya promise to be two of the toughest
challenges for the 53-nation U.N. Human Rights Commission as it begins its
annual six-week session. The Chechen war and Chinese clampdowns are among issues
that will be drawing dozens of foreign ministers and other top officials from as
far away as Pakistan, Chile and Cuba. U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer and British Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook have joined about 30 cabinet level officials in signing up just for
the first week, which begins Monday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Boeing Workers Approve New Contract
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SEATTLE (AP) -- Ending one of the biggest white-collar walkouts in the
country's history striking Boeing engineers and technical workers approved a new
contract Sunday. Members of the Society of Professional Engineering Employees in
Aerospace planned to return to work at 9 a.m. Monday. Under the three-year
proposals, technicians would get a 4 percent raise in the first year and a 3
percent raise in each of the next two years. Engineers would receive a 3 percent
raise every year of their contract.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
470 Feared Dead in Uganda
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   KANUNGU, Uganda (AP) -- Ugandan police said Sunday it may take days before
they can fully explain Friday's fire involving members of the Movement for the
Restoration of Ten Commandments of God. As many as 470 people were killed in
either a mass suicide or murder. Circumstances surrounding the deaths -- who the
dead were and how the fire was started -- remain foggy. Little was known about
the cult, although it appeared to incorporate Christian beliefs and local
farmers said it was led by a former prostitute.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Flames 3, Oilers 2
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- Jason Wiemer scored midway through the third
period as the Calgary Flames beat the Edmonton Oilers 3-2 Sunday night in a game
that featured five power-play goals. Jarome Iginla and Robyn Regehr also scored
for Calgary, which rallied from a two-goal deficit to end a six-game losing
streak. Roman Hamrlik and Ryan Smyth scored for the Oilers, who are in seventh
place in the Western Conference with 78 points.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS
</SUBHEAD>
