<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 09:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PM-NJ--Trinity-Drug Death, 1st Ld-Writethru,440  </HEADLINE>
sdhfcsy
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Students and staff of Trinity College
were struggling to understand the death of a 22-year-old senior in
what police say was a drug and alcohol binge that left his roommate
from New Jersey critically ill.
</P>
<P>
   Two other roommates have been charged with possession of
narcotics. They were scheduled to be arraigned today in Hartford
Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   A school spokeswoman said she did not believe the tragedy was
indicative of widespread drug use among Trinity students.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not in a reactive mode in response to this and we don't
believe we have a drug problem on campus,'' said Linda Campanella,
Trinity's senior vice president for operations and planning.
</P>
<P>
   But she said the death would certainly spark a dialogue between
students and school officials.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be a lot of dialogue and reflection that comes out
of this. We will try to learn as much as we can from this and act
on that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the dead student, Josh Doroff, of Harrison,
N.Y., and his three roommates were drinking and doing drugs in
their dormitory room Thursday night and Friday morning, celebrating
the end of mid-term exams.
</P>
<P>
   Doroff, a political science and economics major, died Friday
afternoon after being taken to Hartford Hospital by friends. The
other stricken student, Clement ''Nick'' Kaupp III, 22, of Mendham,
N.J., was found later by police, unconscious in the room. The
pre-law student was also taken to Hartford Hospital, where he was
listed in critical condition on life support Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital spokesman James Battaglio said Sunday that Kaupp's
family had asked that no more information be released on his
condition.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the students, all seniors, apparently had mixed
prescription anti-anxiety drugs, sleeping pills and a migraine
medication. In addition, they also were drinking and may have taken
heroin, police said. Police said they were trying to learn where
the students obtained the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Doroff, the son of Frank Doroff, executive vice president of
Bloomingdale's, was buried Sunday in Valhalla, N.Y., after a
graveside service, according to a spokeswoman for Riverside
Memorial Chapels in Mount Vernon, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy on Doroff was inconclusive Sunday, pending further
study of tissue and blood samples, said a spokesman for the state
medical examiner's office in Farmington. The toxicology reports
were expected to take about six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Two other roommates-- William B. Bachman, 21, of South Natick,
Mass., and Joshua B. Eaves, 22, of Downingtown, Pa. -- were arrested
after they were taken to the hospital Friday for observation.
</P>
<P>
   Students are on spring break and classes will not resume until
March 27. A memorial service for Doroff will be held that day at 4
p.m. in the college's chapel. College staff, including counselors,
will be available starting the weekend before classes resume.
</P>
</TEXT>
