<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Rejects ''Racial Balancing'  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE ASSEO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sidestepping a dispute over racial diversity,
the Supreme Court today let stand a ruling that bars race as a
factor when public school students seek to transfer to another
school.
</P>
<P>
   The court, without comment, rejected the appeal of a Maryland
school district that refused to let a white boy transfer to a
mostly white magnet school from his minority-dominated neighborhood
school.
</P>
<P>
   ''School districts may take voluntary, race-conscious action to
avoid creating racial isolation,'' lawyers for the Montgomery
County Public Schools told the justices. A federal appeals court
disgreed and overturned the school district's action.
</P>
<P>
   Today's court action set no legal precedent, but left intact the
appeals court's ruling that said such ''racial balancing'' is
unconstitutional when not needed to remedy past discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court ruling affects all schools in Maryland, North
Carolina, South Carolina, Virginia and West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of public school districts allow children to be
transferred to different schools through school-choice programs,
magnet schools or charter schools that are publicly funded but
involve less government regulation.
</P>
<P>
   A number of schools have been sued over the use of race in
deciding what transfers will be allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Eisenberg and Elinor Merberg wanted their son, Jacob, to
attend a magnet school emphasizing math and science when he started
first grade in 1998 in Montgomery County, a suburb of the nation's
capital.
</P>
<P>
   They sued after school district officials barred the transfer
because it would harm the racial diversity of Jacobs' neighborhood
school, Glen Haven Elementary. It was 24 percent white, 40 percent
black, 25 percent Hispanic and 10 percent Asian at the time. White
enrollment had dropped by 15 percent over the previous four years.
</P>
<P>
   The magnet school, Rosemary Hills Elementary, was 66 percent
white, 16 percent black, 14 percent Hispanic and 4 percent Asian.
</P>
<P>
   Jacob's parents said the school district's decision violated his
constitutional equal-protection rights. A federal judge refused to
order a transfer, but the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals struck
down the school district's policy last October.
</P>
<P>
   If student transfers lead to schools dominated by one race or
another, ''any racial or ethnic imbalance is a product of private
choices and it does not have constitutional implications,'' the
appeals court ruled.
</P>
<P>
   In the appeal acted on today, the school district's lawyers said
studies show that desegregated schools aid black students'
achievement and that children who attend integrated schools are
more likely to choose integrated colleges, neighborhoods and work
places.
</P>
<P>
   If students like Jacob are allowed to transfer, his neighborhood
school ''will not only lose diversity but will become all-minority
in the foreseeable future,'' the appeal contended.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the boy's parents urged the court to reject the
school district's appeal. ''Integration can only be pursued as a
result of a constitutional violation, not for its own sake,'' they
said.
</P>
<P>
   The case is Montgomery County Public Schools vs. Eisenberg,
99-1069.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For the appeals court ruling in Eisenberg v.
Montgomery County Public Schools:
http://www.uscourts.gov./links.html and click on 4th Circuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
