<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Court Considers Drug Case  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE ASSEO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to clarify when
courts can overrule arbitrators who require a company to keep an
employee in a safety-sensitive job despite testing positive for
illegal drug use.
</P>
<P>
   The court said it will hear a West Virginia coal company's
argument that an arbitrator wrongly refused to let it fire a heavy
equipment operator who twice tested positive for marijuana use.
</P>
<P>
   James Smith worked for Eastern Associated Coal Corp. in the
Madison, W.Va., area when in 1996 he applied for a position as a
heavy equipment operator. The job required a drug test, and his
results were positive for marijuana use.
</P>
<P>
   The company fired him, but Smith filed a grievance and an
arbitrator ordered the company to rehire him.
</P>
<P>
   He passed three subsequent drug tests but again tested positive
for marijuana in June 1997. The company fired him, and an
arbitrator again ordered Smith reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   The arbitrator relied on Smith's testimony that a family problem
led to a ''one time lapse'' and that if that were not so, Smith
''will make another misstep with drug use and be caught.'' At that
point he would be fired, the arbitrator said.
</P>
<P>
   Eastern asked a federal judge to overturn the arbitrator's
decision, saying there was a ''well defined and dominant public
policy'' against performing safety-sensitive jobs under the
influence of illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge ruled against Eastern, and the 4th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals upheld that ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Courts ''overwhelmingly defer'' to arbitrators' decisions in
labor disputes, the appeals court said, adding that federal
regulations do not make it illegal to reinstate employees who test
positive for drug use.
</P>
<P>
   In the appeal acted on today, Eastern's lawyers said federal
appeals courts have disagreed over when courts can overturn such
arbitration awards. Workplace safety is a ''national concern'' and
illegal drug use costs American businesses more than $60 billion a
year, the appeal said.
</P>
<P>
   The United Mine Workers union's lawyers agreed there is a public
policy against drug-impaired people performing safety-sensitive
jobs, but added that courts approach such matters on a case-by-case
basis. They asked the court to reject the company's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The case is Eastern Associated Coal Corp. vs. United Mine
Workers of America, 99-1038.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For the appeals court ruling in Eastern Associated
Coal v. United Mine Workers of America:
http://www.uscourts.gov./links.html and click on 4th Circuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
