<HEADLINE> Stocks Mixed; Dow Up 77.95  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in early trading today as
investors waited to see whether the Federal Reserve will raise
interest rates at its meeting on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 77.95 to 10,673.18.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were modestly lower. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index was down 0.56 at 1,463.91, and the Nasdaq
composite index was down 2.45 at 4,795.68.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks were mostly higher today after Lehman Brothers
reported first-quarter earnings well above Wall Street's
expectations. Several other Wall Street firms that are scheduled to
release their earnings this week also rose.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman Brothers rose ~ to 92 5/16, and Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter rose 2 to 90].
</P>
<P>
   Dow component American Express rose 3] to 147.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq, MicroStrategy, a maker of software used in
electronic commerce, plummeted 123[ to 103| after the company
revised its financial results for 1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was relatively calm on the eve of the Fed's meeting.
Many on Wall Street are expecting the Fed to raise interest rates
by a quarter-percentage point, which would be the fifth increase
since last June.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has been raising rates in an effort to slow the economy
just enough to contain inflation. Last week, government economic
data hinted at a very modest slowdown, encouraging investors to
believe that dramatically higher rates won't be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Higher interest rates are generally bad for stocks because they
cut into corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 6-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 126.61 million
shares, compared with 294.96 in Friday's busy session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 3.03 to 571.74.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 1.6 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's Xetra DAX index was up 1.9 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 1.4 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
1.5 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
