<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inmate Loses Supreme Court Appeal  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE ASSEO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today turned down an appeal
by a Louisiana man who won, and then lost, a $1 million award from
jail officials who failed to protect him from gouging out his own
eyes during a psychotic episode.
</P>
<P>
   The court, without comment, turned away James J. Sibley's
argument that a trial jury, not the judge, should decide whether
jail officials were indifferent to his mental condition.
</P>
<P>
   Sibley was arrested on assault and battery charges in November
1989 and taken to the Vermilion Parish Correctional Center in
Abbeville, La.
</P>
<P>
   After he began showing erratic behavior in his jail cell, a
doctor examined him and concluded he should be taken to a mental
health facility. There was no room at the facility, however, and
Sibley was placed on a waiting list.
</P>
<P>
   On his fifth day in jail, Sibley was placed in leg shackles
after he was found kicking the door to his cell. On the sixth day,
15 minutes after a deputy had checked on him, the deputy found
Sibley gouging his eyes out with his fingers.
</P>
<P>
   He was blinded in both eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Sibley filed a civil rights lawsuit against Sheriff
Raywood J. Lemaire and deputies Hubert P. Trahan and Freddie Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   A federal jury ruled against Lemaire and Trahan on the civil
rights claims and against all three men on negligence grounds.
Sibley was awarded $1,050,000 in damages.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1997, following an appeals court ruling in a similar
case, the trial judge ordered a new trial in Sibley's case and
ruled for the deputies on the civil rights claims.
</P>
<P>
   The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals agreed, saying the
officials were entitled to qualified immunity because Sibley did
not show that they acted with ''deliberate indifference.''
</P>
<P>
   In the appeal acted on today, Sibley's lawyer said the issue of
deliberate indifference should have been decided by a jury, not by
the judge.
</P>
<P>
   The case is Sibley vs. Lemaire, 99-1039.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For the appeals court ruling in Sibley v. Lemaire:
http://www.uscourts.gov./links.html and click on 5th Circuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-20-00 1028 </TRAILER>
