<DOCNO> APW20000320.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 10:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Reviews Sexual Predator Label  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD CARELLI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to consider
squelching a convicted rapist's attempt to get out from under his
designation in Washington state as a sexually violent predator who
should stay locked up even after he served his prison sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, granting an appeal by state officials, said they
will review Andre Brigham Young's fight against how Washington's
Sexually Violent Predator Statute applies to him.
</P>
<P>
   Young was convicted of five different rapes over a 31-year
period. A day before he was to complete his prison sentence in 1991
for the last of his convictions, state officials sought to have him
committed as a sexually violent predator.
</P>
<P>
   The state law they relied on served as a model for a Kansas law
the Supreme Court upheld in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In that 5-4 decision, the nation's highest court said such
confinement does not violate the constitutional right to due
process and is not double punishment for the same crime. The
confinement, intended to protect society, is civil -- not punitive,
the court said three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, six states had such laws -- Kansas, Washington,
Arizona, California, Minnesota and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   But ruling in Young's case last May, a three-judge panel of the
9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that he should have a
chance to prove before a federal trial judge that his confinement
is indeed punitive because he is being denied the ''adequate care
and individualized treatment'' the state law calls for.
</P>
<P>
   The May decision ordered a federal trial judge to reconsider
Young's case.
</P>
<P>
   In seeking to derail that reconsideration, the state's lawyers
told the justices that the appeals court's ruling is both
''unworkable in practice'' and unwarranted.
</P>
<P>
   The case is Seling vs. Young, 99-1185.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For the appeals court ruling in Young v. Weston:
http://www.uscourts.gov/links.html and click on 9th Circuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-20-00 1029 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000320.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 10:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Rejects Newspaper's Appeal  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD CARELLI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today rejected an appeal in
which the justices were urged to rule that the public and news
media have a constitutional right to attend civil trials even when
some participants want to exclude them.
</P>
<P>
   The court, without comment, turned away arguments by lawyers for
a North Carolina newspaper, The Charlotte Observer.
</P>
<P>
   It was 20 years ago when the nation's highest court first ruled
that members of the public and news media have a First Amendment
right to attend criminal trials.
</P>
<P>
   Judges may conduct criminal trials, or even portions of them, in
secret only as a last resort to insure fairness and only after
explaining why excluding the public is necessary, the court said in
a landmark 1980 ruling called Richmond Newspapers vs. Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Some lower courts have extended that decision and some Supreme
Court sequels to require access to civil, or non-criminal, trials.
The justices never have, however.
</P>
<P>
   The justices last decided an open-court case in 1993, when they
unanimously struck down a Puerto Rico rule that excluded the public
from preliminary hearings for defendants in felony criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
   The North Carolina dispute stems from a doctor's lawsuit against
the operator of two Charlotte hospitals. A. Ron Virmani said
Presbyterian Health Services Corp.'s decision to deny him
privileges at the two hospitals violated its by-laws.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital company in 1996 asked the presiding judge to close
the pretrial hearing held on its request to have the lawsuit
dismissed. The company based its request on a state law that
requires closure of court proceedings and records in cases
involving hospital peer reviews.
</P>
<P>
   John Hechinger, a reporter for the Observer, was in the
courtroom when the request for closing the proceedings was made. He
objected and asked that his lawyer be allowed to oppose the
hospital company's request.
</P>
<P>
   The judge rejected Hechinger's request and had him removed from
the courtroom. The hearing was conducted in secret.
</P>
<P>
   The Observer's owner, Knight Publishing Co., challenged the
judge's action, and a state appeals court ruled that he had made a
mistake. The appeals court ordered that a transcript of the hearing
and all documents introduced at it be made available.
</P>
<P>
   After the hospital company appealed, the North Carolina Supreme
Court overruled the appeals court last June. The state's highest
court upheld the state law requiring closure of court proceedings
and records in cases involving hospital peer reviews.
</P>
<P>
   In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for the Observer said the
justices ''should not permit the state's sweeping closure rule to
stand.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There are powerful and persuasive reasons, well grounded in
both history and function, for applying the right of access to
civil cases,'' the appeal said. ''Public access to civil
proceedings is a concept at the heart of our judicial tradition
that serves the vital social functions of ensuring the
accountability of our legal institutions and facilitating an
informed citizenry.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeal was supported in a friend-of-the-court brief
submitted by the Reporters Committee for Freedom of the Press,
American Society of Newspaper Editors and Society of Professional
Journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Novant Health Southern Piedmont Region, which
acquired Presbyterian Health Services after the dispute began,
urged the court to reject the Observer's appeal. They said the
state court's ruling was based on ''the public's compelling
interest in the confidentiality of peer review records.''
</P>
<P>
   The case is Knight Publishing Co. vs. Novant Health Southern
Piedmont Region, 99-1011.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For the state court ruling in Virmani v.
Presbyterian Health Services Corp.: http://www.courts.net and click
on North Carolina.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
