Gold(final) -    $285.60    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Mon.
</P>
<P>
   Feds To Phase Out MTBE Gas Additive
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration has decided to
phase out MTBE as a gasoline additive on grounds it poses a risk to
public health or the environment, government sources said. MTBE, a
leading oxygenate and octane booster, reduces emissions of smog,
but it has been linked to groundwater pollution in California and
elsewhere. Carol Browner, administrator of the Environmental
Protection Agency, was to announce this afternoon that her agency
will seek to ''significantly reduce or eliminate'' use of MTBEs
under the Toxic Substance Control Act, according to a government
official. The agency also will ask Congress for changes in the
Clean Air Act that will encourage use of ethanol, an additive from
corn, in place of MTBE, another source said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Employees Returning To Work
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- One of the biggest white-collar walkouts in the
country's history has ended with Boeing Co. engineers and technical
workers returning to work today after a 40-day walkout. During that
time, Boeing missed at least 15 airplane deliveries, and work on
some government contracts suffered during the walkout of about
15,000 to 17,000 workers. In its annual report to federal
regulators, filed last week, Boeing said the strike would hurt
financial performance in the first quarter, which ends March 31,
and could affect the second quarter as well. Boeing shares were
down 1 this morning at 37.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler Adds PT Cruiser Plant
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Citing strong demand for its Chrysler PT Cruiser,
DaimlerChrysler AG will begin building the retro-styled wagons at a
second factory. DaimlerChrysler said today it would build PT
Cruisers at its Eurostar plant in Graz, Austria, next year. The
plant has the capacity to build 50,000 PT Cruisers a year. The
company also is ramping up production at its plant in Toluca,
Mexico, which has the capacity to build 180,000 vehicles a year.
The first PT Cruisers were scheduled to arrive in dealerships this
month. It already has waiting lists and markups over the sticker
price of $17,000 to $20,000 at some dealers. DaimlerChrysler shares
were down 2 1/16 at 65 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   Dutch Airline KLM To Cut 2,700 Jobs
</P>
<P>
   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- KLM Royal Dutch Airlines NV plans
to shed 2,700 jobs, or 7.9 percent of its work force, as part of a
restructuring plan to cut costs and return to profitability. The
measures announced today are intended to offset rising fuel costs,
declining capacity and cheaper air fares which resulted in an
operating loss of $30 million in the latest quarter. The national
carrier will eliminate the jobs over the next 12 months though a
combination of forced job cuts and attrition.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan Intervenes in Stock Plunge
</P>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Political uncertainties shook Taiwanese
stocks today, with most falling as far as they could on fears of a
war with China. The government intervened and bought shares to help
contain the damage brought on by opposition candidate Chen
Shui-bian's election, but officials warned they could not keep
buying indefinitely if traders keep selling. Prices finished with a
loss of 2.6 percent, and 394 of the 589 companies on the Taipei
stock market dropped the maximum amount. But the mood was not
entirely gloomy. Shipping companies rallied on Chen's comments that
he would like to see Taiwan and China agree on direct air and sea
links.
</P>
<P>
   3 European Stock Markets To Merge
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Stock exchanges in Paris, Amsterdam and Brussels
announced today that they would merge to form Euronext, the largest
single stock exchange in continental Europe. ''It is not a link. It
is not an alliance. It's a merger, a full merger,'' Jean-Francois
Theodore, head of the Paris exchange and the chairman and chief
executive of Euronext, told a news conference in London. Euronext
hopes to complete its merger by September or October, he said. The
combined exchanges will continue to operate trading floors in
France, the Netherlands and Belgium, and each will be listing the
stocks of its partners.
</P>
<P>
   National Commerce Buying CCB
</P>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. (AP) -- National Commerce Bancorporation is buying
CCB Financial Corp. for $1.94 billion in stock in a merger of
Southern banking companies. The company created under the deal will
have about $15 billion in assets and will keep the name National
Commerce Bancorporation. Its corporate headquarters will be in
Memphis, while its operations base will be in Durham, where CCB
Financial is located. CCB Financial shareholders are set to receive
2.45 shares of NCBC common stock for each of CCB's 40.3 million
shares, valued at $48.23 each as of Friday's close. The merger,
approved by the companies' boards of directors, requires regulatory
and shareholder approvals and is expected to close in the third
quarter. This morning, CCB stock was up 1 3/16 at 39} and National
Commerce was down 2 11/16 at 17.
</P>
<P>
   Siemens, Mannesmann Join Forces
</P>
<P>
   DUESSELDORF, Germany (AP) -- Electronics company Siemens AG is
planning to form an automotive technology venture with German
engineering and telecommunications firm Mannesmann AG, the
companies announced today. The venture will be the world's largest
supplier of high tech electronics systems for cars and trucks, with
sales of roughly $6.79 billion and 50,000 employees worldwide. Each
company will hold 50 percent of the joint venture, which brings
together Siemens' automotive branch and Mannesmann's automotive
unit, VDO Kienzle GmbH. The new entity, which will take the name
Atecs Siemens Automotive AG, will begin operation July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Supreme Court Considers Drug Case
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to clarify when
courts can overrule arbitrators on the issue of illegal drug use.
The court said it will hear Eastern Associated Coal Corp.'s
argument that an arbitrator wrongly refused to let it fire a worker
who twice tested positive for marijuana use. James Smith already
worked for West Virginia company when he applied for a position as
a heavy equipment operator. The job required a drug test, and his
results were positive for marijuana use. The company fired him, but
an arbitrator ordered the company to rehire him. Smith tested
positive for marijuana again a year later. The company fired him,
and an arbitrator again sent him back. The arbitrator relied on
testimony that a family problem led to a ''one time lapse.''
</P>
