<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Rejects Overtime for Trainers  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE ASSEO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Eight Texas high school sports trainers who
want overtime pay for the long hours they spend treating student
athletes' injuries lost a Supreme Court appeal today.
</P>
<P>
   The court, without comment, rejected an appeal in which the
trainers argued that their duties should not be considered
professional work exempt from the federal overtime pay law.
</P>
<P>
   The trainers work an average 60-hour week at the San Antonio
Independent School District. They work to prevent and treat student
athletes' injuries, attend practices and games, and help students
undergo rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   The trainers sued the school district in 1996, contending they
were entitled under the federal Fair Labor Standards Act to time
and one-half pay when they work more than 40 hours a week.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge ruled that seven of the eight trainers should
not be considered professionals and therefore were entitled to
overtime pay.
</P>
<P>
   Employees can be considered professionals if their work requires
advanced knowledge gained through specialized instruction, and if
they consistently must exercise their own judgment on the job.
</P>
<P>
   The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reversed the judge and
ruled for the school district. Trainers in Texas must have a
university degree as well as specialized training in subjects such
as human anatomy and physiology, and they exercise their own
judgment, the appeals court said.
</P>
<P>
   The 5th Circuit court said it was not required to defer to a
Labor Department opinion letter that said Kansas athletic trainers
should not be considered professionals.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal acted on today said the appeals court should have
deferred to the Labor Department letter even though it was not a
formal department rule.
</P>
<P>
   The case is Owsley vs. San Antonio Independent School District,
99-1205.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For the appeals court ruling in Owsley v. San
Antonio Independent School District:
http://www.uscourts.gov./links.html and click on 5th Circuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
