<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rains Drench Soybean, Grain Prices  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices plummeted in
early dealings today on the Chicago Board of Trade after
heavier-than-expected weekend rains soaked growing regions in much
of the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   After a week-long rally that followed U.S. government warnings
of drought, soybeans dove more than 2 percent immediately after
trading opened today. That erased Friday's gains, which were based
largely on expectations that the Midwest would see a mostly dry
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rain fell in key soybean growing areas of Illinois and
Indiana over the weekend. More showers falling today in the eastern
Midwest -- including outside the Board of Trade building in downtown
Chicago -- added to pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Corn prices took a beating for the same reason, with
expectations for more rain later in the week contributing to the
selling mood.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat also tumbled, pressured by the weekend precipitation in
much of the Midwest and the Delta. The storm system expected to
cross the winter wheat belt later in the week helped push prices
lower.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for May delivery fell 6 cents to $2.66\ a bushel; May corn
fell 6 cents to $2.34} a bushel; May oats fell 1{ cents to $1.20{ a
bushel; May soybeans fell 13 cents to $5.24{ a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef futures were higher in early trading on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, while pork futures were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   April live cattle rose .55 cent to 72.47 cents a pound; May
feeder cattle rose .33 cent to 83.55 cents a pound; June lean hogs
rose .45 cent to 70.80 cents a pound; May pork bellies fell .17
cent to 93.15 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
