<DOCNO> APW20000320.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 11:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court To Clarigy Mail-Fraud Charges  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE ASSEO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to clarify
whether people can be charged with federal mail fraud for lying
when applying for a state license, such as a permit to operate
video poker games.
</P>
<P>
   The court said it will hear a New Orleans lawyer's argument that
the mail-fraud law does not apply to state licenses that have not
yet been issued.
</P>
<P>
   Carl W. Cleveland and Fred H. Goodson of Slidell, La., were
charged in 1996 with mail fraud, racketeering and other offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors said the two lent money to Goodson's adult
children to operate a video poker business, but that applications
for state licenses concealed the fact that Cleveland and Goodson
were the business' true owners. Prosecutors said the men concealed
their ownership to avoid state assessment of their suitability.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland and Goodson each were convicted of two counts of mail
fraud as well as money laundering, racketeering and other charges.
Both were sentenced to 10 years and one month in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The mail-fraud charges were based on the state's mailings of the
video poker license and subsequent renewals.
</P>
<P>
   The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the convictions
last July. The court noted it previously had ruled that state
licenses are considered ''property'' under the mail fraud law,
which bars people from using the mail to fraudulently obtain
property.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to hear Cleveland's appeal. His
lawyers said other federal appeals courts have ruled that a state
license not yet issued is not considered property under the federal
law.
</P>
<P>
   The 5th Circuit court's ruling would mean that ''virtually any
alleged misrepresentation in applying for such licenses can be the
basis for federal felony charges,'' Cleveland's appeal said.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department lawyers had urged the court to reject the
appeal, saying Louisiana had a property interest in the video poker
licenses and is entitled to control the source of that money.
</P>
<P>
   The case is Cleveland vs. U.S., 99-804.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For the appeals court ruling in U.S. v. Cleveland:
http://www.uscourts.gov./links.html and click on 5th Circuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-20-00 1108 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
