<HEADLINE> Dow Up 90.98; Nasdaq Down 43.81  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks rose today, but the broader
market held back as nervous investors waited to see whether the
Federal Reserve will raise interest rates at its meeting on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In morning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 90.98 at 10,686.21.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was down 0.82 at 1,463.65, and the Nasdaq composite index was
down 43.81 at 4,754.32.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow was led higher by its technology components.
Hewlett-Packard rose 5 to 142 13/16, and Intel rose 5 7/16 to 135
5/16.
</P>
<P>
   American Express rose 1[ to 144}, but other financial stocks
were mixed. Lehman Brothers reported first-quarter earnings well
above Wall Street's expectations but its shares slipped [ to 91
5/16. Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, scheduled to report earnings
later this week, rose 1\ to 89|.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq, MicroStrategy, a maker of software used in
electronic commerce, lost more than half of its value. Shares
plummeted 127 13/16 to 98 15/16 after the company revised its
financial results for 1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was relatively calm on the eve of the Fed's meeting.
Many on Wall Street are expecting the Fed to raise interest rates
by a quarter-percentage point, which would be the fifth increase
since last June. Higher interest rates generally send stocks lower
because they cut into corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has been raising rates in an effort to slow the economy
just enough to contain inflation. Last week, government economic
data hinted at a very modest slowdown, encouraging investors to
believe that dramatically higher rates won't be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   John H. Shaughnessy, chief investment strategist at Advest Inc.,
said that while he expects a rate increase Tuesday, he believes Fed
Chairman Alan Greenspan won't act aggressively for the remainder of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Greenspan does not want to break the back of the best
economic recovery this nation has enjoyed in its history,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 283.34 million
shares, compared with 508.75 in Friday's busy session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 8.90 to 565.87.
</P>
</TEXT>
