<HEADLINE> Report: Fiat Eying Volvo and Scania  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Fiat's Giovanni Agnelli says the Italian automaker,
which last week announced an alliance with General Motors Corp., is
eyeing AB Volvo and Scania AB after regulators blocked the proposed
merger of those two truck makers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't know the terms that led the antitrust to reject the
operation. We need to see if they could also be applied to us,''
Agnelli, who is honorary chairman of Fiat, was quoted Sunday as
saying by Milan daily Corriere della Sera.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the European Commission rejected Volvo's planned $6.9
billion merger with rival Swedish truck and bus maker Scania as
anticompetitive.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, which is the executive arm of the 15-member
European Union, said the merger ''would have caused serious
competition concerns by creating dominant positions'' in several
sectors, including the heavy truck and bus markets in Sweden,
Denmark, Norway, Finland and Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed merger, announced in August, would have created the
world's second-largest truck and bus maker, behind DaimlerChrysler.
</P>
<P>
   Volvo, based in Goteborg, owns 45.5 percent of Scania and will
retain its stake for now, according to a statement issued before
the commission made its decision public.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not Scandinavian, that's for sure,'' Agnelli told the
Milan newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, Fiat and its truck unit Iveco would
most likely bid solely for Scania.
</P>
<P>
   GM and Fiat SpA announced a $2.4 billion alliance last week
aimed at cutting costs by sharing parts and people.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Fiat will swap 20 percent of its Fiat Auto
subsidiary for about 5.1 percent of GM's common stock -- making the
Italian company GM's largest shareholder. Fiat and GM will form
joint ventures in engine building and purchasing that could
eventually involve thousands of workers on two continents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
