<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 11:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN: Poor Nutrition Court Hurt Kids  </HEADLINE>
By SUE LEEMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Poor nutrition could stunt and handicap 1 billion
children in the next 20 years unless a more focused campaign is
launched to improve feeding, according to a report for the United
Nations published Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The report, by the independent Commission on the Nutrition
Challenges of the 21st Century, said about a quarter of children in
developing countries -- some 30 million a year -- suffer retarded
growth even before they are born, in the wombs of their
malnourished mothers.
</P>
<P>
   Early undernutrition, followed by weight gain as those in
developing countries adopt Western lifestyles and consumption
patterns, can lead to a virulent form of obesity, which later in
life causes millions in the developing world to develop diabetes,
heart disease, and some cancers, the report concluded.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have completely failed to recognize the extraordinary
interlinkage'' between underweight children and cancers and other
chronic disease in later life, commission chairman Professor Philip
James told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''The malnutrition of mothers and children is programming a
whole generation and setting it back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But James said the problem is ''entirely preventable.''
</P>
<P>
   The report cited as an example Thailand, where a relatively
low-cost program of monitoring, education and feeding cut the
proportion of underweight preschool children from 50 percent in
1982 to about 10 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   A Costa Rican nutrition program targeted at preschool children
and pregnant and nursing women cut the proportion of undernourished
children under 5 from 45 percent in 1978 to 2 percent today, the
report noted.
</P>
<P>
   James said it was cause for concern that 30 million children a
year are born under the recommended minimum birthweight of 5.5
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Some 200 million children around the world are stunted or
handicapped in some way due to poor nutrition, and many more are
''sub-optimal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite programs to cut deficiencies in vitamin A, as many as
250 million preschool children still have mild deficiencies of this
vital nutrient, James added.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 243 million adults are severely undernourished, and
the commission said in India alone, more than 80 percent of
pregnant women suffer from anemia.
</P>
<P>
   Some 250 million people have escalating obesity and resultant
chronic diseases, including diabetes, which U.N. studies show
afflicts one fifth of those who have been undernourished in the
womb, James said.
</P>
<P>
   The report labeled South Asia the worst-affected region,
followed by sub-Saharan Africa, the Middle East and North Africa,
and Latin America and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, made up of academics and health officials from
seven countries, reports to a U.N. subcommittee on nutrition. Its
goal is to eradicate malnutrition by 2020.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-20-00 1157 </TRAILER>
