<HEADLINE> Administration: Overhaul World Bank  </HEADLINE>
By MARTIN CRUTSINGER, AP Economics Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration put forward today a
package of proposals to overhaul lending activities at the World
Bank and other regional development banks, hoping the effort will
blunt a congressional drive for even more radical changes.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said that the World Bank and
regional banks such as the Asian Development Bank should refocus
their efforts on providing loans to projects that would help
alleviate poverty in the world's poorest nations but which are not
likely to attract support from commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the Council on Foreign Relations in New York,
Summers said that when loans are made to developing countries that
can attract private capital, such as China and Brazil, those loans
should carry higher interest rates than the World Bank charges for
loans to the poorest nations that don't have access to private
capital markets.
</P>
<P>
   Summers' package of proposals also included recommendations for
the World Bank to put more emphasis on providing support for
medical vaccines to improve health conditions and on projects that
would protect the environment.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's proposals for reform at the development
banks followed a similar set of proposals Summers put forward in a
speech in London in December aimed at promoting change at the
182-national International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's proposals for both the IMF and the World
Bank do not go nearly as far as a blue ribbon advisory commission
appointed by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   That panel, chaired by economist Allan Meltzer of Carnegie
Mellon University, called for limiting the IMF to providing
short-term emergency loans to countries facing balance of payments
crises.
</P>
<P>
   The Meltzer commission also called on the World Bank to focus on
the use of grants to the world's poorest nations rather than loans,
and halt two-thirds of the lending it now does to better-off
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
   While conservative Republicans in Congress embraced the Meltzer
report, Democrats in the House and Senate attacked its proposals as
too extreme.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's reform recommendations are an effort to put
forward a more moderate set of proposals which the White House
hopes will shape the upcoming debate in Congress and at the
upcoming spring meetings of the IMF and World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The United States does not have the power to impose changes on
the IMF and the other multinational lending institutions, but the
size of U.S. voting shares in all of the organizations gives
America a powerful voice in arguing for changes.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 182-nation IMF and its sister lending agency,
the World Bank, both of which are headquartered in Washington, the
regional development banks include the Inter-American Development
Bank, the Asian Development Bank and the African Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Summers said in all the debate, the world should not lose sight
of the important role played by the development banks in promoting
global prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ''The strengthening of the world's economic and financial
institutions and the management of global integration are central
policy challenges of our time,'' Summers said in his speech, copies
of which were released in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ''The work of the World Bank and the regional development banks
is probably more important now than it has ever been,'' Summers
said. ''As the president has often observed, today the United
States has as much to fear from states that are too weak as states
that are too strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Summers said that every dollar that the United States
contributed to the World Bank and the other development banks
spurred $45 in lending programs.
</P>
<P>
   But Summers said it was important that the money be used in ways
that would promote the largest amount of poverty reduction in
countries willing to put in place necessary economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ''The international community cannot want reform and stability
more than a country's own government and people do,'' Summers said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-20-00 1325 </TRAILER>
