<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Visibility Key for Oscar Nominees  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GERMAIN, AP Entertainment Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Warren Beatty flirted with a presidential run
but decided against it. His wife, Annette Bening, is hot on the
campaign trail, though.
</P>
<P>
   Bening is running for best actress at Sunday's Academy Awards
for her role as a shrill, adulterous real-estate saleswoman in the
Oscar front-runner ''American Beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   Her visibility in Hollywood trade ads and public appearances has
helped pump up Bening's Oscar prospects against those of Hilary
Swank, the critics' darling and the Golden Globe winner for ''Boys
Don't Cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Bening ''has been at the opening of every Hollywood car wash and
Dairy Queen,'' joked Thomas O'Neil, an Oscar analyst who is writing
a book about movie awards. ''She has been absolutely everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Magazine covers, talk shows, Hollywood trade conventions, other
awards ceremonies such as the Screen Actors Guild and Directors
Guild -- all are virtual requirements for nominees hoping to go home
with an Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   Studios pump as much as $2 million into a movie's Oscar
campaign. They buy dozens of glitzy Oscar ads in Variety and The
Hollywood Reporter, set up screenings, provide video copies of
films to Academy voters and make stars available for interviews and
other appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have to admit that last year, Gwyneth Paltrow was
everywhere,'' said USA Films' Steve Flynn of 1998's best-actress
winner for ''Shakespeare in Love.'' ''It was very aggressive and a
smart thing for her to do, and I think it paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   Flynn's best-actress candidate last year, Cate Blanchett in
''Elizabeth,'' was overseas shooting a picture, and ''her
unavailability definitely hampered my opportunities to keep her
visible'' for Academy consideration, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Big Oscar campaigns can put smaller films at a disadvantage.
Even so, movies with relatively modest Oscar budgets managed to
garner acting nominations this year, including Swank in ''Boys
Don't Cry,'' Janet McTeer in ''Tumbleweeds,'' Richard Farnsworth in
''The Straight Story'' and Sean Penn and Samantha Morton in ''Sweet
and Lowdown.''
</P>
<P>
   The real question is whether any of them can actually win
without an expensive Oscar campaign.
</P>
<P>
   While Oscar campaigning dates back to the 1920s and '30s, some
critics say it has become too gaudy, cheapening the awards.
</P>
<P>
   ''The whole notion of campaigning runs counter to what the
process really is about, which is our members making subjective
evaluations of filmmaking,'' said Ric Robertson, the Academy's
executive administrator.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1990s, the Academy instituted rules to prevent
studios from bestowing lush video packages and other gifts on Oscar
voters. Academy officials would like to tone the campaigns down
further but do not see any legal way to restrict such things as
trade ads, Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   Just how pervasive are those ads?
</P>
<P>
   ''There's so many you don't even pay attention to them anymore.
It's like a perfume ad in Vogue,'' said Alexander Payne, director
of ''Election.'' He is nominated for adapted screenplay with
co-writer Jim Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Like last year with DreamWorks' ''Saving Private Ryan'' and
Miramax's ''Shakespeare in Love,'' the two studios are going
head-to-head for best picture, DreamWorks with ''American Beauty''
and Miramax with ''The Cider House Rules.''
</P>
<P>
   The two have the biggest buzz factor and have been the most
visible in trade ads, though other studios have been quick to shell
out Oscar marketing money, Disney for ''The Insider'' and ''The
Sixth Sense,'' Warner Bros. for ''The Green Mile.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike last year, DreamWorks declined to discuss its Oscar
campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to trust the Academy,'' said DreamWorks
spokeswoman Vivian Mayer.
</P>
<P>
   Other studios, including Disney, Paramount and Universal, also
refused to talk about Oscar strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Miramax, the Disney-owned independent distributor
that has turned awards campaigning into a science, said Oscar
marketing does not unduly influence the Academy.
</P>
<P>
   Trade ads simply encourage Academy members to see a particular
movie, then serve to ''remind people about the emotional reaction
they had to the movie after they had seen it,'' said Mark Gill,
Miramax West Coast president.
</P>
<P>
   Henri Bollinger, an Academy member and Hollywood publicist since
the 1950s who worked on Humphrey Bogart's winning Oscar campaign
for ''The African Queen'' in 1951, said awards marketing is just
part of the business.
</P>
<P>
   ''People seem to forget that the Oscars themselves were created
as a marketing tool for the industry,'' Bollinger said. ''I readily
admit I have been influenced by these ads to go and see a film. But
I don't ever remember casting a vote for a film because of its
Oscar campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.oscars.org
</P>
</TEXT>
