<HEADLINE> European Shares Rise  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- European stocks finished mostly higher on Monday,
fueled by investors turning to technology and telecom shares.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of shares in European companies rose
3.65 points, or 0.9 percent, to 397.39, while the technology
subindex outperformed all others, rising 4.5 percent. The TechMARK
100 index rose 0.7 percent. Equant, STMicroelectronics, France
Telecom, Deutsche Telekom, Vodafone and Pearson led heavyweight
gainers.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks companies in
countries that joined the single currency, was up 4.28 points at
452.60. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index was up 63.0 points at
5,052.1.
</P>
<P>
   ''The reason why people were buying these stocks is still there;
their growth rates are higher than the rest of the market,'' said
Khuram Chaudhry, an analyst at Merrill Lynch
</P>
<P>
   But while technology stocks outperformed, Internet service
providers fell back as investors hone their strategies in the
fledging new economy.
</P>
<P>
   World Online lost after an initial public offering Friday failed
to live up to expectations, while Terra Networks, Freeserve and
United Pan-Europe Communications all fell Monday. The
Brussels-based technology index Easdaq lost 2.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   London's FTSE-100 Share Index rose 1.0 percent, to 6,624.5.
Frankfurt's Xetra DAX Index rose 2.1 percent to 7,872.38, led by
Siemens, which rose 15.25 euros, or 9.5 percent, to 175.24 euros.
SAP rose 68.80 euros, or 9.5 percent, at 969.80 euros, while
Deutsche Telekom gained 4.80 euros, or 5.6 percent, to 91.30 euros.
</P>
<P>
   The Paris CAC-40 Index was up 0.8 percent to 6,352.51,
Amsterdam's AEX Index was down 0.1 percent to 671.65, and Belgium's
Bel-20 Index rose 0.6 percent to 2,852.02 after the three exchanges
confirmed they plan to merge.
</P>
