<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supporters of stadium point to more reasons for stadium  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Selling naming rights for the proposed
University of Connecticut football stadium in East Hartford could
fetch between $1 million and $3 million, but there may be a few
sticking points before any deals can be made.
</P>
<P>
   The 40,000-seat stadium, proposed for a 75-acres parcel of land
donated by United Technologies Corp., would cost taxpayers about
$90 million as part of the Adriaen's Landing riverfront development
project. The plan still needs legislative approval, and supporters
say selling the name of a stadium to a corporation could help cover
some of the cost.
</P>
<P>
   ''The value of naming-rights deals has exploded in the last five
years, and as far as we can tell, there's no end to it,'' said Dean
Bonham, a Denver-based consultant who has worked on many big
corporate stadium deals.
</P>
<P>
   In two big professional sports deals, Bonham said, American
Airlines paid $195 million for a Dallas hockey and basketball
arena, and Federal Express paid $205 million for the Washington
Redskins football stadium name. College stadiums are also hot, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Senate President Pro Tempore Kevin Sullivan said tax laws
may prevent an outright sale of naming rights because the stadium
would belong to the public, financed by tax-free bonds. To get
around that, the state could receive a ''gift'' from a corporate
donor and bestow an honor on the company, in the form of the
stadium's name, Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   Plans to sell naming rights can also be foiled if UTC insists on
the location name, Bonham said.
</P>
<P>
   Hosting soccer games at the stadium could also bring in more
cash by expanding its use beyond the handful of home UConn football
games.
</P>
<P>
   Planners are designing the stadium to meet specifications for
college, professional and international-level play.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nobody is going to have a better stadium for soccer,'' said R.
Bartley Halloran, chairman of the Capital City Economic Development
Authority, which is developing the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Halloran said there are no agreements, but the stadium could
hold men's and women's soccer for UConn, as well as the University
of Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, he said, an expansion of major league soccer into
Hartford is not out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   But David Askinas, associate commissioner of the United Soccer
Leagues in Tampa, Fla, called such hopefulness ''a great leap of
faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Askinas said the proposed stadium might be too large for many
soccer uses. NCAA soccer draws far smaller crowds, even at the
highest levels, he said; UConn, averaging 2,400 fans per game,
attracts some of the biggest crowds. And the NCAA Final Four, in
December, is always held in a warm-weather state, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The point, said Halloran and Richard Gray, the governor's point
man on Adriaen's Landing, is that soccer would be just one more
possibility, with no guarantees of added use. The plan before
lawmakers anticipates only UConn football.
</P>
<P>
   ''The key from the planning standpoint is to design as much
flexibility as possible into the stadium,'' Gray said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
