<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No contest plea does not mean admission of guilt, despiteconviction  </HEADLINE>
By STEVE FEICA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP)-- A conviction for stealing does not
necessarily mean somebody is a thief, the state Supreme Court said
in ruling that a Groton town worker fired for embezzlement be
returned to his job.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-2 decision released Friday involved the case of David
Warren, who sold dumping permits to residents at the town landfill.
He was fired in April 1997 after pleading nolo contendre, or no
contest, to a larceny charge.
</P>
<P>
   Warren was accused of pocketing money for the permits and was
arrested in November 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The plea agreement was recorded as a conviction for larceny in
the sixth degree, a misdemeanor involving the theft of $250 or
less.
</P>
<P>
   Warren was fined $85 plus $15 in court costs. He opted for the
plea deal to save at least $5,000 in legal fees, according to court
documents.
</P>
<P>
   Warren's union, United Steelworkers of America, took the case to
arbitration and won Warren's reinstatement. The arbitrator had
ruled there was no independent evidence that Warren had stolen
anything, and said he should return to work.
</P>
<P>
   The arbitrator noted that ''Warren neither had pleaded guilty to
the crime charged nor had he been found guilty after a trial,''
according to court documents.
</P>
<P>
   The town appealed to a lower court which threw out the
arbitrator's decision. The case eventually made its way to the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   In writing for the majority, Justice Joette Katz said ''There is
.. no factual foundation whatsoever for the assertion that Warren
embezzled even one penny from his employer.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz wrote that the no contest plea was not necessarily an
admission of guilt, but rather a matter of convenience.
</P>
<P>
   ''The arbitrator made a factual finding, which is binding on
this court, that Warren had pleaded nolo contendre, because, for
financial reasons, he had deemed such a plea a more convenient and
cleaner way to resolve the charges against him,'' Katz wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice Francis M. McDonald and Justice David M. Borden
filed dissents.
</P>
<P>
   Both said there is no distinction between a conviction from a
plea of no contest and a conviction after a guilty plea or trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
