<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Lets Jail Ban Playboy  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD CARELLI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court turned a cold shoulder to
free-speech and pro-nudity claims Monday by refusing to let an
Arizona jail's inmates get Playboy magazines delivered to their
cells.
</P>
<P>
   The justices rejected a challenge to the jail's ban on all
depictions of frontal nudity. The appeal, turned away without
comment, contended the ban violates inmates' rights.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, the Maricopa County sheriff's office has prohibited
jail inmates from possessing ''sexually explicit material,'' which
it defines as anything that shows male or female frontal nudity.
</P>
<P>
   The county runs one of the nation's largest jail systems,
housing up to 6,500 inmates at facilities in the Phoenix area.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Mauro challenged the ban in 1995 after officials denied
his request that his subscription to Playboy be directed to the
cell where he was being held while awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro later was convicted of fraud and is an inmate at the
Arizona State Prison in Florence. His case against Maricopa County
and Sheriff Joseph Arpaio had remained alive, however, because he
was seeking monetary damages.
</P>
<P>
   The jail's ban covers publications and inmates' own artwork and
is said to be aimed at preventing inmate fights and harassment of
female jail employees.
</P>
<P>
   A federal trial judge upheld the ban but a three-judge federal
appeals court panel struck it down. The three-judge panel said the
prohibition was too sweeping and would include ''such magazines as
National Geographic, medical journals, artistic works and countless
other materials.''
</P>
<P>
   An 11-judge panel of the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
reversed the three-judge panel last August by a 7-4 vote. The
majority of that court concluded the county's policy fell within
guidelines provided by a 1987 Supreme Court decision on jailhouse
censorship because the ban is ''reasonably related to legitimate
penological interests.''
</P>
<P>
   In his appeal, Mauro's lawyers noted that a Sports Illustrated
swimsuit issue and Victoria's Secret catalog are allowed, but
Michelangelo's ''David'' or concentration camp photographs are
banned.
</P>
<P>
   The county's lawyers urged the justices to reject the appeal
because it ''fails to offer any evidence that other inmates have
been denied artistic or scientific publications under the policy.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For the appeals court ruling in Arpaio v. Mauro:
http://www.uscourts.gov/links.html and click on 9th Circuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
