<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate race in N.J. features contrasting personalities, heavyspending  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   EWING, N.J. (AP) -- When Sen. Frank Lautenberg announced last
year that he would retire at the end of his term, former Gov. Jim
Florio saw it as an opportunity to revive his political career.
Wall Street banker Jon S. Corzine saw it as an opportunity to begin
one.
</P>
<P>
   The two are now squared off in a Democratic Senate primary
battle that promises to be one of the most bitterly contested and
expensive of the 2000 political season. Though they share liberal
positions on many key issues, their personalities and campaign
styles are a study in contrasts.
</P>
<P>
   Florio, the one-time congressman and one-term governor whose
political career was derailed seven years ago by a series of
unpopular tax increases and an upstart Republican named Christie
Whitman, remains as forceful and self-assured as ever at 62. It's
an image that befits his background as the son of a Brooklyn
shipyard worker, former Navy boxer and lawyer by training.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, 53, also touts his working-class roots as the son of an
Illinois farmer. But there the personal similarities end. Bearded,
soft-spoken, professorial in dress and manner, Corzine made a
fortune on Wall Street. He stepped down as chairman of Goldman
Sachs after taking the investment bank public.
</P>
<P>
   He is cheerful and approachable but has been criticized as a
dull, colorless campaigner and a boring speaker. He acknowledges
his campaign style remains a work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am still not Huey Long in this process, but I think we have
made strides. I am a lot more comfortable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With a bankroll estimated at more than $300 million, Corzine is
prepared to invest heavily in his political future.
</P>
<P>
   He has already spent some $4 million to lay the groundwork for
his campaign and help Democratic candidates in state races. An ad
campaign launched this week to bolster his minimal name recognition
will spend $888,000 on television ads in the expensive Philadelphia
and New York media markets over seven days.
</P>
<P>
   The big spending has opened the door for Florio and his
supporters to renew their charges that Corzine is trying to buy a
Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are having Wall Street, generically, come and acquire a
party in the way that they acquire a company,'' Florio fumes.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine has a lot of ground to gain between now and the June 6
primary. Three recent polls indicate his name is known to only
about one in five New Jersey Democrats and have him trailing Florio
2-to-1.
</P>
<P>
   But Corzine has won endorsements from several key county
organizations and party leaders, including Lautenberg.
</P>
<P>
   ''Democrats warm up to Jon Corzine very quickly,'' said Tom
Byrne, a Democratic Party activist who flirted with a Senate
candidacy himself before Corzine arrived on the scene. Byrne is the
son of former Gov. Brendan Byrne.
</P>
<P>
   Byrne questions Florio's electability, citing the baggage he
carries from his ill-starred gubernatorial term.
</P>
<P>
   ''It goes way beyond the income tax to the point where many
Democrats who have worked with him over the years do not want to do
so anymore,'' Byrne said.
</P>
<P>
   The clash of personalities and the furor over spending mask
considerable similarities on the issues. Corzine favors
government-paid health coverage for everyone, tough gun control and
federal programs to provide access to a college education for
anyone who wants it.
</P>
<P>
   He rejects the liberal label -- politely. ''I use the term
progressive,'' he said. ''The fact is that the federal government
has been much more successful that our political process has
allowed it to be painted.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio's platform is tailored to appeal to the party's
traditional working-class constituency: health insurance for
working families and a strong Social Security system for their
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   The winner will face the winner of a Republican scramble created
when Whitman, who had planned to run, changed her mind and withdrew
in September. GOP candidates include Rep. Bob Franks, state Sen.
William Gormley, Essex County Executive Jim Treffinger and Ramapo
College professor Murray Sabrin.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
