</P>
<P>
   Lehman Beats Analysts' Expectations
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc. said today its
first-quarter earnings surged 156 percent to $541 million, a figure
well above analysts' predictions. Lehman attributed its strong
results to record revenues in the company's investment banking and
securities trading businesses. Lehman earned $3.69 a share, 59
cents above high-end expectations, for the three months ended Feb.
29. During the first quarter of 1999, the firm reported net income
of $211 million, or $1.57 a share, as Wall Street recovered from a
global financial crisis brought on by economic strife in Asia and
Russia. Shares of Lehman, the fourth largest U.S. securities firm,
were down 2 7/16 this afternoon at 89.
</P>
<P>
   Feds Phasing Out MTBE Gas Additive
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration announced today it
will ban MTBE as a gasoline additive on grounds it poses a risk to
public health and the environment. MTBE, a leading oxygenate and
octane booster used in one-third of the gasoline sold in the United
States, reduces emissions of smog, but it has been linked to
groundwater pollution. Carol Browner, administrator of the
Environmental Protection Agency, said her agency will seek to
eliminate use of MTBEs under the Toxic Substance Control Act. She
said the ban, expected to take up to three years to implement,
would have little effect on consumer costs.
</P>
<P>
   China Oil Imports Expected To Rise
</P>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- China's long-term level of oil imports will
outstrip by three times the country's own forecast, the
International Energy Agency said today. The figures suggest that
China will become a far more influential player in the global oil
market and in the oil-rich Middle East, the agency said. ''China's
economic growth has outstripped its own energy resources,'' said
William Ramsey, deputy director of the IEA. Separately, IEA
Director Robert Priddle urged OPEC countries to release
''substantial'' extra oil supplies to help reduce soaring prices at
the pump.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Workers Back on the Job
</P>
<P>
   RENTON, Wash. (AP) -- Boeing Co. white-collar workers celebrated
the determination and solidarity that led to their new contract
when they returned to work today -- 40 days after walking off the
job. The strike by 15,000 to 17,000 members of the Society of
Professional Engineering Employees in Aerospace affected Seattle
and Portland area Boeing plants, causing the company to miss at
least 15 airplane deliveries. Boeing has said the strike would hurt
financial performance in the first quarter, which ends March 31,
and could affect the second quarter as well. Boeing stock was down
~ at 37[.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Suggests World Bank Reforms
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration put forward today a
package of proposals to overhaul lending activities at the World
Bank and other regional development banks. Treasury Secretary
Lawrence Summers said that the organizations should refocus their
efforts on providing loans for projects in the world's poorest
nations that are not likely to attract support from commercial
banks. In a speech in New York, Summers said that when loans are
made to developing countries that can attract private capital, such
as China and Brazil, those loans should carry higher interest rates
than loans to the nations that don't have access to private capital
markets.
</P>
<P>
   3 European Stock Markets To Merge
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The planned merger of stock exchanges in France,
Belgium and the Netherlands marks an important step forward in
efforts to forge a pan-European exchange that could compete more
effectively with Wall Street, analysts said. The new exchange,
called Euronext, would be the largest single stock market in
continental Europe and would make it easier and cheaper for
investors to trade shares in companies listed jointly on their
respective exchanges. The combined exchanges would continue to
operate trading floors in all three countries, and each would list
the stocks of its partners. Market capitalization of the listed
companies would be $2.3 trillion. Euronext, to be incorporated as a
Dutch company, hopes to complete its merger within the next seven
months.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation Rate Rises in EU Nations
</P>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The inflation rate in the 11 euro-zone
countries was 2.0 percent in February, up from 1.9 percent in
January and 0.8 percent a year ago. Also, the European Union
statistical office Eurostat said that annual inflation in the 15 EU
nations rose to 1.9 percent in February from 1.8 percent in
January. In February 1999, EU inflation stood at 1.0 percent. The
rise is significant because the European Central Bank has set 2.0
percent as its target ceiling for inflation in the euro zone. The
highest annual inflation - a year-on-year rise of 4.6 percent - was
recorded in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler Adds PT Cruiser Plant
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Citing strong demand for its Chrysler PT Cruiser,
DaimlerChrysler AG will begin building the retro-styled wagons at a
second factory. DaimlerChrysler said today it would build PT
Cruisers at its Eurostar plant in Graz, Austria, next year. The
plant has the capacity to build 50,000 PT Cruisers a year. The
company also is ramping up production at its plant in Toluca,
Mexico, which has the capacity to build 180,000 vehicles a year.
The first PT Cruisers were scheduled to arrive in dealerships this
month. It already has waiting lists and markups over the sticker
price of $17,000 to $20,000 at some dealers. DaimlerChrysler shares
were down 2 13/16 at 64 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   Fiat May Go After Scania Stake
</P>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Fiat's Giovanni Agnelli says the Italian automaker,
which last week announced an alliance with General Motors Corp., is
eyeing AB Volvo and Scania AB after regulators blocked the proposed
merger of those two truck makers. The European Commission had
rejected Volvo's planned $6.9 billion merger with its Swedish rival
truck and bus maker Scania as anticompetitive. According to a
report in the Milan daily Corriere della Sera, Fiat and its truck
unit Iveco would most likely bid solely for Scania.
</P>
