<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Family seeks investigation of inmate's death  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- A Plainfield man hung himself in jail two
days after he lost a bid to withdraw his guilty plea to killing his
mother-in-law, state officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at East Jersey State Prison found Mark Masters hanging
by a bedsheet in his cell at 5:30 a.m. Sunday, Department of
Corrections spokesman Chris Carden said. Carden said he did not
know when guards had last seen Masters alive.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Mitzner, Masters' attorney, said Monday family members
spoke to Masters on Saturday night and said Masters was in good
spirits and understood that his loss in court on Friday was not the
end of his appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was apparently fearful for his life because he had had an
altercation with sheriff's officers,'' Mitzner said.
</P>
<P>
   Carden said the Corrections Department would investigate the
death as it does every inmate death, but said Monday, ''There's no
indication of foul play.''
</P>
<P>
   Masters, a 37-year-old former handyman, had been serving a
30-year sentence since 1993 for strangling his 74-year-old
mother-in-law, Mary Mason, and cutting off her hands with an ax on
March 4, 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Masters surrendered to police at the Plainfield home he shared
with his wife, mother-in-law and stepdaughter after a 19-hour
standoff with police that ended when he shot himself in the chest.
</P>
<P>
   Masters pleaded guilty to manslaughter, but later asked to
withdraw his plea, saying he had proof that his wife at the time,
Minka Barany, killed her mother.
</P>
<P>
   Masters appealed to state Superior Court Judge Ross Anzaldi for
an evidentiary hearing on Friday, presenting an affidavit from
stepdaughter Dominique Barany, who said Minka Barany confessed to
her months after the killing.
</P>
<P>
   ''She told me that she killed her mother and that it was all her
fault that her mother was dead,'' said Dominique Barany, who was 13
at the time of the killing, in an affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   Masters told Mitzner he entered a guilty plea because Minka
Barany told him she would kill her daughter if he didn't take the
blame.
</P>
<P>
   Masters became violent in court on Friday, biting Union County
Sheriff's Officer Scott Jones in the left arm and requiring several
more to restrain him, Sheriff Ralph G. Froehlich said.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff's officers only handled his transfer from the
courthouse to the Union County Jail and had no contact with him at
East Jersey State Prison, Froehlich said.
</P>
</TEXT>
