<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Drops 162; Dow Rises 51  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq composite index fell sharply today as
profit-taking investors once again moved money out of technology
stocks and into old-fashioned industrial shares.
</P>
<P>
   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the
Nasdaq composite index was down 162.76 at 4,635.37.
</P>
<P>
   Broader indicators were mixed. The Dow Jones industrial average
was up 51.19 at 10,646.42, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index
was down 10.24 at 1,454.23.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow and the Nasdaq diverged as investors drew money out of
lesser-known names in the software and biotechnology groups and
poured it into computer makers and more established technology
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow was led higher by Hewlett-Packard, up 8| to 146 7/16,
and Intel, up 6| to 136{.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq, MicroStrategy, a maker of software used in
electronic commerce, lost more than half its value. Shares
plummeted 127 21/64 to 99 27/64 after the company revised its
financial results for 1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The stock, which had soared 2000 percent in the past 12 months
to a high of 333 on March 10, almost singlehandedly caused the
decline in the Russell 2000 index of smaller companies. With its
big run-up, MicroStrategy had become one of the Russell's largest
companies in terms of market capitalization.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 was down 20.50 at 554.27.
</P>
<P>
   Biotechnology companies also contributed to the Nasdaq's
weakness as investors took profits from the sector's big run early
this year. The Nasdaq's Biotechnology Index more than doubled
between Dec. 1 and March 7, leaving those companies vulnerable to
profit-taking. President Clinton's announcement last week that he
wants to make some genetic research openly available -- rather than
bought and sold by biotech companies -- has unsettled many
investors, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Biogen fell 5} to 79[ and Amgen fell 4 51/64 to 58 21/64.
</P>
<P>
   While those stocks fell, investors sought out blue-chip
including United Technologies, up 1] to 56; AT&AMP;T, up 2{ to 55
11/16; and DuPont, up 1| to 54 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   ''Portfolio managers have been recognizing value in some of the
old industrial stocks,'' said Chris Wolfe, equity market strategist
at J.P. Morgan's private client group. A protracted decline at the
start of the year left many blue-chip companies at bargain prices
before the Dow began bouncing back last week.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of Dow components continued to struggle. Boeing
slipped [ to 37 1/16 even after the company's engineers and
technical workers agreed to end a 40-day walkout.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was relatively calm on the eve of the Fed's meeting.
Many on Wall Street are expecting the Fed to raise interest rates
by a quarter-percentage point, the fifth increase since last June.
Higher interest rates generally send stocks lower because they cut
into corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has been raising rates in an effort to slow the economy
just enough to contain inflation. Last week, government economic
data hinted at a very modest slowdown, encouraging investors to
believe that dramatically higher rates won't be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   John H. Shaughnessy, chief investment strategist at Advest Inc.,
said that while he expects a rate increase Tuesday, he believes Fed
Chairman Alan Greenspan won't act aggressively for the remainder of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Greenspan does not want to break the back of the best
economic recovery this nation has enjoyed in its history,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 734.74 million
shares, compared with 1.07 billion at the same time in Friday's
busy session.
</P>
</TEXT>
