<HEADLINE> Grain, Soybean Prices Plummet  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures plummeted Monday on the
Chicago Board of Trade after a wet weekend in the Midwest tempered
concerns of a crop-wrecking drought this spring and summer.
</P>
<P>
   Soybean prices gave back all the gains they posted in a strong
rally last Friday, tumbling on heavier-than-expected rainfall in
key growing areas. The big runup in prices late last week had been
predicated partly on forecasts for a dry weekend, which were proven
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Corn fell for the same reasons, also pressured by new forecasts
for rain in the Midwest later this week which should reduce drought
worries.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat prices were another victim of the weather-driven
commodities markets. Wheat sank immediately due to the weekend
rains in the central United States, and were pushed lower by the
forecasts for precipitation in the winter wheat belt later in the
week.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for May delivery fell 6 cents to $2.66\ a bushel; May corn
fell 5 cents to $2.35} a bushel; May oats fell { cent to $1.21{ a
bushel; May soybeans fell 11} cents to $5.25} a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while
pork futures were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   April live cattle rose .28 cent to 72.20 cents a pound; May
feeder cattle rose .45 cent to 83.40 cents a pound; June lean hogs
rose .08 cent to 71 cents a pound; May pork bellies fell .65 cent
to 92.72 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
