<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Researchers: Chip Helps Man Walk  </HEADLINE>
By CONSTANT BRAND, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Ten years after a car crash paralyzed
him from the waist down, an implanted computer chip is helping Marc
Merger regain the ability to walk.
</P>
<P>
   The 39-year-old financial consultant from France is the first
patient to undergo the implant procedure, which was developed by a
consortium of European researchers to help people who have lost the
use of their legs.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, surgeons implanted 15 electrodes on nerves and
muscles in Merger's legs, connecting them with wires to a computer
chip embedded in his abdomen. The procedure had to be repeated in
February after problems arose.
</P>
<P>
   Merger was able to stand up by himself in early March, and he
took his first steps last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are a whole lot of people like me who need this,''
Merger said during a news conference at European Union headquarters
Monday. ''It's hard to imagine not being able to walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Professor Pierre Rabischong of Montpellier University in France,
a project coordinator, said the implanted chip allows Merger to
create artificial muscle movement.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are trying to reproduce what happens in the brain ... with
electrodes to nerves and muscles,'' said Rabischong. ''We are not
working miracles here, but allowing patients to stand up using
their own muscles.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, scientists hope patients will be able to control
their movements by pressing buttons on a walking cane now under
development that will act as a remote control. For now, scientists
transmit instructions to the chip via computer. The signals are
transmitted to the electrodes in the legs and converted into muscle
movement.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are by no means at the end of the road. A lot of work is
still required,'' Rabischong said.
</P>
<P>
   Merger was living proof of that Monday. A demonstration of him
walking at EU headquarters had to be postponed because a computer
glitch failed to communicate commands to the computer chip, meaning
he could not walk.
</P>
<P>
   Gabrielle Tronconi, 23, is one of six people due to receive
implants later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope I will be able to reduce my disability and to be able
to do more things than I can do right now,'' the 23-year-old
Italian said. ''I hope to walk because of the research
developments,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rabischong said that there are more than 300,000 people in
Europe with paralysis of the lower limbs. Their average age is 31,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union and six governments -- France, the
Netherlands, Germany, Denmark, Italy, and Britain -- have been
working on developing the technology since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Previous electronic systems have allowed paralyzed people to
stand and walk with a walker, sometimes for more than a mile, said
Naomi Kleitman, director of education at the Miami Project to Cure
Paralysis at the University of Miami School of Medicine. Those
systems use electrodes taped on the skin.
</P>
<P>
   Systems that implant computer-controlled electrodes have tested
in the lab for many years as well, she said. They may allow more
sophisticated control over leg nerves and muscles, although there
has been some problems with long-term maintenance of the implanted
electrodes, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kleitman said she couldn't comment directly on the European
system without knowing more details.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-20-00 1552 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000320.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Richardson Pursues Cheaper Oil  </HEADLINE>
By H. JOSEF HEBERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bill Richardson's itch to travel is no secret.
As a congressman, U.N. ambassador and now secretary of energy, he
may have logged as many miles journeying as anyone in President
Clinton's Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   He's on the road again this week, this time in search of greater
oil production and lower fuel prices. The outcome may determine
whether the Hispanic former lawmaker remains on the list of
often-mentioned potential vice presidential running mates on the
Democratic ticket with Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Trotting the globe on a moment's notice, Richardson gained
notoriety as a congressman with a string of unorthodox freelance
diplomatic missions that won freedom for American hostages in North
Korea, Iraq and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is the point man in Clinton's ''quiet diplomacy'' aimed
at convincing members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries to open their spigots and push back prices that -- if not
contained -- could drive the world economy into a recession.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC is to decide March 27 on new production levels.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it looks good for (oil) production increases,''
Richardson said in an interview before departing for Africa and
then on to Europe for meetings with energy ministers from Nigeria,
Algeria, the United Arab Emirates and others.
</P>
<P>
   He packs what he considers his lucky charm: a travel-worn,
rumpled blue blazer that became a trademark in the mid-1990s rescue
missions.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll have it with me,'' he said, adding after a pause, ''I'm
going to need it.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, 52, the most visible Hispanic in Clinton's
administration and a New Mexico congressman for 14 years, must
wonder sometimes about his luck since leaving the U.N. post to
become energy secretary 15 months ago. The Energy Department
usually doesn't garner a lot of headlines. When he moved there,
some thought he might disappear from the limelight despite his
acknowledged political ambitions and folksy style.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he has found himself enmeshed in almost continuous
damage control.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it was the uproar over security problems and alleged
espionage at the department's nuclear weapons labs. Richardson
scrambled from one congressional hearing to another and onto
weekend television news programs to stay one step ahead of critics.
</P>
<P>
   This year, it is oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes could not be higher, both economically and
politically, as Republicans view the specter of $2-a-gallon
gasoline this summer as fodder for attacks against the
administration and Vice President Gore's presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   Public unrest at the gas pumps comes at an untimely moment for
Richardson as well. As the administration's most prominent
Hispanic, he frequently has been discussed as a possible No. 2 on a
Gore presidential ticket. But if negotiations with OPEC fail and
the gasoline price run-up is not abated, Richardson could be
blamed.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson witnessed the grassroots force of the issue last
weekend in California, where he met with Saudi Arabia's oil
minister. People recognized him, he said, and they wanted to know
what was being done to bring gasoline prices down.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe our (approach) of quiet diplomacy has been working,
so we're continuing it,'' he said. Without offering specifics, he
said he hopes for ''sizable production increases in a timely
fashion,'' predicting that would prompt prices to start falling by
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Administration sources say Richardson privately has expressed
concern that talk of U.S. use of its emergency oil reserve or
threats against oil producing countries could anger some OPEC
members and jeopardize any increase in production.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Richardson has sought to convince the OPEC ministers
that it is in their interest to pump more oil.
</P>
<P>
   During his trips to the Persian Gulf last month, he and his
staff swamped the Saudi and Kuwaiti ministers with charts and
statistics showing the dramatic shortfall in oil inventories, the
expected demand and the possibility that $30 dollar-a-barrel oil
might send not only America's economy but also the world's into a
tailspin.
</P>
<P>
   It is an argument he intends to repeat in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to stress the importance of sufficient increases in
a timely fashion,'' said Richardson. ''I'm not pressuring. ... The
OPEC ministers, all who I talked to, recognize that high oil prices
have become a problem and what is needed is stable prices.''
------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Energy Department site: http://www.doe.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-20-00 1554 </TRAILER>
