<DOCNO> APW20000320.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Party Admits Financial Woes  </HEADLINE>
By DIRK BEVERIDGE, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- President-elect Chen Shui-bian, whose
party acknowledges it's a novice in financial affairs and lacks a
ready pool of talent to draw on, faces a tough challenge in trying
to run Taiwan's complex economy.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan has one of Asia's most stellar economies -- it rode out
the financial crisis of the late 1990s virtually unscathed, largely
because of the island's huge success in creating a world-leading
semiconductor industry.
</P>
<P>
   But after Chen's opposition Democratic Progressive Party rocked
the political structure of Taiwan with his election win Saturday,
his young and inexperienced party now has to deal with issues that
were handled by the Nationalists for more than 50 years, since
Taiwan and China were politically separated.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to crucial economic issues -- naming a team to run
the Finance Ministry, for example -- Chen has no ready pool of
talent to draw on.
</P>
<P>
   ''The financial expertise of the DPP is not good, or not enough
in the quantity sense,'' Chen's executive campaign manager, Chiou
I-jen, told reporters Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''This doesn't mean we're worried about Taiwan's financial
performance,'' Chiou added.
</P>
<P>
   The healthy economy should chug along well enough to withstand
any minor bumps along the way as the DPP deals with its economic
learning curve, Chiou said.
</P>
<P>
   The DPP has made enormous gains in local and legislative
politics in its 13-year history, but Chen's victory will give the
party its first leadership opportunities at the national level.
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices plunged Monday on Chen's victory, and panicky
Taiwanese dumped their currency in favor of the U.S. dollar. As it
often has, the Taiwanese government moved to limit the decline by
purchasing shares and propping up the Taiwan dollar.
</P>
<P>
   But the government warned investors that they will have to live
with the outcome of Saturday's election. Vice Finance Minister Yen
Ching-chang told traders that if they keep selling, Taiwan cannot
indefinitely keep buying.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the shares of a few companies rallied on hopes that Chen
will lift bans on direct air and shipping links with China.
</P>
<P>
   Chen, who takes office on May 20, on Monday reaffirmed he wants
to improve trade ties with the huge, developing market in China,
which is just 80 miles across the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
   China has been apprehensive about Chen since his party favors
formal independence for Taiwan, while Beijing has sought
reunification.
</P>
<P>
   In Taiwan, politics and business have long been closely linked,
and Chen's administration will end up in charge of a number of big
state-owned industries -- such as utilities, the telephone company,
banks, oil refineries -- that have been controlled for decades by
the Nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   Even the big air carrier, China Airlines, is run by a board of
trustees appointed mostly by the Nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   Taking over such enterprises is no task for beginners.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan also has hundreds of small businesses owned by the
Nationalist Party, and there could be disputes over whether some
property was obtained illegally.
</P>
<P>
   Chiou, the campaign manager, said the DPP worries that the
Nationalists might try to walk away with some of their assets for
fear the new government will challenge their ownership.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now, we can't get any concrete information,'' about some
Nationalist holdings, Chiou said.
</P>
<P>
   Chiou said Chen's team will ''wait and watch'' and hopes to meet
soon to discuss the workings of Taiwan's business world with
President Lee Teng-hui and the party's investment manager, Liu
Tai-ying.
</P>
<P>
   Some concerns may turn out to be exaggerated, but change is
clearly on the way and it won't necessarily be smooth.
</P>
<P>
   ''Chen is going to break some of the business behavior patterns
of the past,'' said Peter Kurz, the top executive in Taiwan for
Wall Street investment bank Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   ''The basic modus operandi of how you do business here in Taiwan
is going to change,'' Kurz added. ''Chen is going to be a reformer,
and some of the cozy ties between business and government from the
past will change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-20-00 1556 </TRAILER>
