<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Postpones Germany Trip  </HEADLINE>
White House postpones Germany trip.
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- President Clinton has postponed a May
visit to Germany for talks with world leaders because British Prime
Minister Tony Blair is unable to attend, a White House spokesman
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're trying to reschedule. No new date has been set,'' said
Mike Hammer of the National Security Council staff, accompanying
Clinton on a six-day visit to South Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was to have spent May 1-2 in Aachen, Germany, for a
conference with Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, Italian Prime
Minister Massimo D'Alema and Blair. Clinton also was to have
received a prestigious award, the International Charlemagne Prize.
Hammer said the May dates conflict with Blair's schedule.
</P>
<P>
   One possibility is that a stop in Germany will be tagged on when
Clinton visits Portugal for a June 5 summit with European Union
leaders. That trip also may include stops in Nigeria and Moscow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
