<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia's Putin Flies Into Chechnya  </HEADLINE>
By ELMIRA KOZHAYEVA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Playing up his image as a tough leader,
acting President Vladimir Putin flew into Chechnya in a fighter jet
on Monday and said he was ready to hold talks with rebels.
</P>
<P>
   After briefly inspecting parts of the devastated Chechen capital
on a dramatic pre-election visit, Putin signaled that Moscow was
willing to discuss the republic's future if the rebels give up
their weapons and abandon armed struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are ready with those people -- even with those people -- to
start talks,'' Putin said in Khankala, a suburb of Grozny. ''They
have this choice.''
</P>
<P>
   He stopped short of calling for peace talks with the rebels,
repeating Moscow's demands that they surrender their weapons in
return for amnesty. The Russian government has said some top rebel
leaders would face criminal charges even if they surrender.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's visit appeared tied to presidential elections Sunday, in
which he holds a commanding lead. He came to Grozny in the back of
a two-man Sukhoi 27 fighter jet, wearing a leather flight jacket
over a business suit.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Putin sounded a conciliatory note with his
remarks on possible talks about the future of Chechnya. Many
Russians approve of his handling of the war, but the government has
shown signs of wanting to wrap it up.
</P>
<P>
   While the rebels have been driven into the mountains, they have
not given up fighting despite repeated Russian claims that the
insurgents have been defeated.
</P>
<P>
   But Putin also warned that Moscow is ready to continue the war,
saying the rebels would be blockaded in the mountains and hunted
down by special forces troops. ''They will be eliminated,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   It was Putin's first visit to Grozny since Russian troops
captured it early last month after bombarding the city for months
with artillery and air strikes. It was not known if Putin visited
Grozny before.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian assault has left the city a wasteland of shattered
buildings, and some officials had proposed abandoning it. But Putin
said Monday that ''Grozny will be slowly restored.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin inspected a unit of paratroopers scheduled to be pulled
out of Chechnya and honored soldiers with medals and other awards.
</P>
<P>
   The advances against the rebels have allowed Russia to begin
scaling down its military operation and Putin said ''there is no
sense in keeping surplus troops in the republic.''
</P>
<P>
   But he cautioned that an extended military presence could be
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ''We still have a lot of problems and it is clear that this
demands significant forces,'' Putin said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, a news report said a Russian pilot taken hostage in
October had been freed in Komsomolskoye, a Chechen town captured by
Russian forces after two weeks of heavy shelling.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Alexander Zhukov was seized when his jet went down in
Chechnya during a mission.
</P>
<P>
   Federal forces raised the Russian flag over Komsomolskoye on
Monday, claiming control of it after fighting with small pockets of
rebels earlier in the day. About 75 rebels surrendered there
Monday, Russian news media reported.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, the Interfax news agency reported that a Chechen
field commander, Salautdin Timirbulatov, had been captured by
Russian troops. Russian television stations later broadcast a
videotape purportedly showing him executing a prisoner of war from
the previous Chechnya conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of hostages have been taken in Chechnya since the
republic won de facto independence from Russia at the end of a
1994-96 war. Moscow has said that one of the reasons behind its
current campaign to retake Chechnya is to stop the kidnappings and
restore order to the rebel republic.
</P>
<P>
   Russian ground troops entered Chechnya in late September,
preceded by weeks of air raids. The offensive began after rebels
invaded the neighboring Russian region of Dagestan last summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
