<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strollers, Pull Toys Recalled  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- About 44,000 jogging strollers were recalled
Monday because their brakes may fail, causing runners to lose
control and endanger children riding in them, the Consumer Product
Safety Commission said.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally 4,900 wooden pull toys were recalled because a part
may fall off and cause a choking hazard to small children.
</P>
<P>
   The CPSC said the stroller recall involved the single and double
models of the InSTEP and Healthrider jogging stroller, manufactured
by Minnesota-based InSTEP LLC.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers, including Burlington Coat Factory, J.C. Penney and
Target sold the strollers nationwide between December 1998 and July
1999.
</P>
<P>
   The commission said the recall involved seven models, ZS100,
ZD200, ZS100WS, ZD200WS, ZS100HR, PR100 and PR200, which consumers
should stop using immediately and contact the company for a repair
kit. No injuries have been reported, the panel said.
</P>
<P>
   The pull toy recall involves ''The Wooden Pull Along Bead
Coaster'' manufactured by Maxim Enterprise Inc. of Middleboro,
Mass. sold nationwide by Zany Brainy stores from November 1999
until last month.
</P>
<P>
   ''Wheels can break off and the bead can detach from the pull
string, posing small parts choking hazards to young children,'' the
commission said.
</P>
<P>
   In one incident a detached bead was found in a child's mouth,
but no injuries have been reported.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers should return the toys to the store for a $15 refund.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.zanybrainy.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.instep.net
</P>
<P>
   http://www.cpsc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
