<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Drops 187; Dow Ends Up 85  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq composite index fell sharply today as
investors once again moved money out of newer technology stocks and
into shares of more established computer makers and old-fashioned
industrial companies.
</P>
<P>
   According to preliminary calculations, the Nasdaq composite
index was down 187.62 at 4,610.51.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up 85.01 at 10,680.24.
Broader indicators were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow and the Nasdaq diverged as investors drew money out of
lesser-known names in the software and biotechnology groups and
poured it into the largest, most dominant technology companies.
Hewlett-Packard, Intel and IBM led the Dow's advance.
</P>
<P>
   ''Given the very high prices of many of these stocks, people who
want to be heavily invested in technology are believing that maybe
they should stick with the tried and true,'' said Richard A.
Dickson, a technical analyst at Scott &AMP; Stringfellow Inc. in
Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors combined to derail the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   MicroStrategy, a maker of software used in electronic commerce,
lost more than half its value after the company revised its
financial results for 1998 and 1999. The change came after
MicroStrategy altered the way it recognizes revenue to comply with
current requirements of the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The stock, which had soared 2000 percent in the past 12 months
to a high of 333 on March 10, almost singlehandedly caused the
decline in the Russell 2000 index of smaller companies.
MicroStrategy's woes also hastened investors' move toward more
established technology companies, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Their problems really rattled investors,'' Dickson said. ''If
you're investing in IBM, you know they're not going to hit you with
this kind of accounting surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet retailers were mostly lower after Barron's magazine
reported this weekend that dozens of prominent companies are
strapped for cash and may go out of business unless they're
acquired or receive major new investments. Amazon.com and eToys
fell.
</P>
<P>
   Biotechnology companies also contributed to the Nasdaq's
weakness as investors took profits from the sector's big run early
this year. The Amex Biotechnology Index more than doubled between
Dec. 1 and March 7, leaving those companies vulnerable to
profit-taking. Also, President Clinton's announcement last week
that he wants to make some genetic research openly available --
rather than bought and sold by biotech companies -- has unsettled
many investors, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Biogen and Amgen fell.
</P>
<P>
   While those stocks fell, investors sought out blue-chip stocks
including United Technologies, AT&AMP;T and DuPont.
</P>
<P>
   ''Portfolio managers have been recognizing value in some of the
old industrial stocks,'' said Chris Wolfe, equity market strategist
at J.P. Morgan's private client group. ''There's not a lot of money
coming out of the market, but money is being channeled from the new
economy to the old.''
</P>
<P>
   A protracted decline at the start of the year left many
blue-chip companies at bargain prices before the Dow began bouncing
back last week.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was relatively calm on the eve of the Fed's meeting.
Many on Wall Street are expecting the Fed to raise interest rates
by a quarter-percentage point, the fifth increase since last June.
Higher interest rates generally send stocks lower because they cut
into corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has been raising rates in an effort to slow the economy
just enough to contain inflation. Last week, government economic
data hinted at a very modest slowdown, encouraging investors to
believe that dramatically higher rates won't be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   According to preliminary calculations, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
fell 7.84 to 1,456.63.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by an 8-to-7 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,584 down, 1,378 up and 490
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume totaled 912.91 million shares as of 4 p.m., vs. 1.29
billion in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 25.56 to
549.21.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
