<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greenspan Predicts Fed Rate Hike  </HEADLINE>
By MARTIN CRUTSINGER, AP Economics Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan has
bluntly signaled that the central bank will keep raising interest
rates until the economy's red-hot growth slows to a more moderate
pace.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are predicting that the next increase, the fifth rate
boost since last June, will occur Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is essentially a foregone conclusion,'' said William
Cheney, chief economist at John Hancock in Boston. ''Greenspan has
laid out the logic that demand is growing too fast, spurred by
stock prices, and it is unsustainable.''
</P>
<P>
   The central bank's interest-rate-setting Federal Open Market
Committee will announce its decision around 2:15 EST Tuesday,
following one of their eight regularly scheduled meetings for the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Since last June, the Fed has raised rates four times in
quarter-point steps, boosting the federal funds rate -- the interest
banks charge each other -- to 5.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial banks in turn have increased their prime lending rate
in lockstep with the Fed's moves, pushing the benchmark for
millions of consumer and business loans to 8.75 percent, its
highest level since late 1995.
</P>
<P>
   So far, all of the Fed's efforts have done little to slow an
economy that has continued to surge ahead, powered by robust
consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's gross domestic product grew by a torrid 6.9 percent
rate in the final three months of last year and many economists
believe growth in the current January-March quarter will come in
around 5 percent, far above the 3.5 percent rate the Fed would like
to see at this stage of the expansion that began in March 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan has warned in recent speeches that the strong consumer
demand, which he said was being powered by the boom in wealth
created by the stock market, cannot continue to outstrip supply
without triggering serious inflation problems.
</P>
<P>
   To some, Greenspan's warning seemed to indicate the Fed was
aiming its interest rate increases squarely at the high-flying
stock market, prompting some in Congress to question what business
the Fed has in trying to jack up interest rates in order to make
stock prices fall.
</P>
<P>
   But other economists believe Greenspan's comments were
misinterpreted, saying his real point was that strong demand, from
whatever source, must calm down to keep inflation under control.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Fed is in a no-win situation right now,'' said Diane
Swonk, chief economist at Bank One in Chicago, who said the central
bank is trying to raise rates enough now to slow growth before
inflation gets out of hand, when they would be forced to slam on
the brakes even harder.
</P>
<P>
   ''If inflation was already out of control, everybody would be up
in arms and say, 'Why isn't the Fed tightening more?''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the underlying rate of inflation, after taking out the
big boost in energy prices, has remained benign. Core consumer
prices rose just 1.9 percent last year, the best performance in 34
years.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market has been on a wild ride this year, with the Dow
Jones industrial average posting huge declines from late January
until last week, when it roared back to life with a 666 point gain
for the week.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said the Fed might be considering a half-point
rate hike Tuesday if not for the fact that they don't want to be
seen adding to market volatility.
</P>
<P>
   After Tuesday, many economists are looking for at least two more
rate increases, at the May 16 meeting and the June 28 meeting,
pushing the funds rate up to 6.5 percent, the highest level since
January 1991, when President Bush was in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   After that, many analysts believe the central bank will wait to
see how the economy reacts during the summer and fall presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed may be able to stay on hold for the rest of the year if
the economy slows, something that will be helped not only by higher
interest rates but rising energy prices, which means consumers will
be spending more at the gas pumps and less in department stores.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think the economy will slow in the second half of the year,
in part because of higher interest rates and higher oil prices,''
said David Wyss, economist at Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI. ''The Fed
wanted to move early in the year before the campaign gets under
way.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Federal Reserve site: http://www.federalreserve.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
