<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Party Nominates First Woman  </HEADLINE>
By BURT HERMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Germany's conservatives nominated the first woman
and first former East German to head a major political party on
Monday, a step hailed as a milestone in the country's
reunification.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Merkel's nomination as Christian Democrat Party
chairwoman follows a devastating campaign financing scandal that
had left the country's dominant postwar party nearly on its
deathbed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I find it unbelievable that I could be nominated with the full
unified support of the party to the chairmanship,'' Merkel said.
''This is a piece of German unification that until some time ago I
could never have imagined living through.''
</P>
<P>
   Merkel, 45, will face no challengers at a convention in April
where she is expected to be confirmed as party head, following in
the footsteps of such prominent German politicians as Konrad
Adenauer and Helmut Kohl. She will replace Wolfgang Schaeuble, who
was pressured to resign last month over his handling of the
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Under Schaeuble's leadership, the party faced one damaging
revelation after another in the wake of Kohl's admission in
December that he accepted up to $1 million from donors he has
refused to name.
</P>
<P>
   Even Schaeuble was forced to admit he had accepted $50,000 in
cash from a key figure in the scandal -- contradicting his own
earlier statements to parliament that he had never met that person.
</P>
<P>
   Merkel's rapid rise in the party has led to speculation she
could become Germany's first woman chancellor candidate, although
she told reporters Monday that no decision would be made this year
on who would run in the 2002 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys show Merkel's popularity has surged, making her the
second highest-rated politician, behind the Christian Democratic
Saxony state governor Kurt Biedenkopf and ahead of the public's
previous political darling, Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer.
</P>
<P>
   Schaeuble said Merkel's nomination was secured by the
''unusually large'' endorsements she received at local party
gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a great step in German unity to have an East German woman
as chairwoman of a major German party,'' said Biedenkopf.
</P>
<P>
   Merkel has brushed aside suggestions she is too liberal to lead
the party, saying Monday she has no plans to shift the party's
political direction and pledging to follow the Christian Democrats'
charter. She also said being a woman would not influence her
political priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will not carry out the work expected of me in a
gender-specific way,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the first senior party members to distance herself from
the scandal-tarnished Kohl, Merkel said she could still distinguish
the former chancellor's positive achievements.
</P>
<P>
   ''Kohl was essential to German unity, and to European
unification -- that is and remains his achievement,'' Merkel said.
''We know today that also many things happened during this time,
but I am of the opinion that we must separate one thing from the
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in the western city of Hamburg in 1954, Merkel was only a
couple months old when her father, a Lutheran pastor, was assigned
to a parish in a small town in East Germany. The holder of a
doctorate in physics, she eventually worked as a chemist in a
scientific academy in East Berlin -- but her ties to the church kept
her from her desired career as a Russian and physics teacher.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the year the Berlin Wall fell, she became involved with
the burgeoning democracy movement rooted in East German churches.
Merkel joined the Christian Democrats just two months before German
reunification on Oct. 3, 1990.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
