<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill would bar Con Ed from charging outage costs to customers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A bill in the state Assembly would bar
Consolidated Edison from imposing on customers the cost of the
outage at its Indian Point 2 nuclear power plant, Assembly Speaker
Sheldon Silver said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is important that the ratepayers not pay for the failures
of Con Ed,'' Silver, a Manhattan Democrat, said.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly bill would prohibit the state Public Service
Commission from allowing the utility to apply the cost of
replacement power while Indian Point 2 is out of service --
estimated at $600,000 a day -- to the utility's rate base or
otherwise passing through the charge to customers.
</P>
<P>
   Con Ed's president, Michael Evans, said earlier this month that
the utility intended to pass along most of the costs of the Feb. 15
outage to ratepayers. A utility spokesman estimated that would add
about $2 a month to the typical electric bill of a residential
customer.
</P>
<P>
   A leak in a tube at the plant carrying radioactive water
resulted in the release of a minute amount of radioactive steam
into the atmosphere. There was no measurable effect on the
environment and no one was injured, but it resulted in the first
alert in the 26-year history of the Westchester County plant.
</P>
<P>
   Silver said the utility was aware of the possibility of the
failure and could have avoided the outage by replacing steam
generators sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a group of Democratic state legislators filed a
''prudency petition'' with the Public Service Commission calling on
the agency to refuse to let Con Ed pass the cost of the outage on
to customers.
</P>
<P>
   Con Ed Joseph Petta said utility officials had not seen Silver's
bill as of Monday and had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   He said officials expect to know more about when Indian Point 2
can be restarted based on an evaluation of the damage to the plant
which will be completed within two weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
