<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SUNY chancellor getting extra $90,000 housing allowance for stayingat home  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- State University of New York Chancellor
Robert King is getting paid an extra $90,000 a year for staying in
his Albany-area home instead of living in the SUNY-provided
chancellor's residence, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The previously unrevealed housing allowance is in addition to
his $250,000-a-year salary that SUNY officials announced in
December when King was hired.
</P>
<P>
   The salary and housing allowance added together mean that King,
who has no previous academic experience, received a 130 percent
raise when he left his job as Gov. George Pataki's state budget
director to lead SUNY.
</P>
<P>
   King is a close friend of the governor and the two have known
each other since King joined the state Assembly in 1987. Pataki had
arrived in the Assembly two years earlier. As head of Pataki's
budget office, King was known as a fiscal hawk.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know why you would need a housing allowance if you
have a taxpayer supported residence and are largely based in
Albany,'' said Blair Horner of the New York Public Interest
Research Group, who cautioned that his group had not done a
comparison of similar university systems. ''I don't know what the
justification is.''
</P>
<P>
   King was in Chicago on Monday at an education conference and not
available for comment, SUNY spokesman E.J. McMahon said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it is clearly outrageous that salary (supplement) was
not revealed,'' Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The reality is he has no experience in the field,'' the
Assembly Democrat told Albany's WROW-AM radio. ''I don't know why
we have to pay top dollar to someone at this point who may be
learning on the job.''
</P>
<P>
   King isn't the only state official not using his official
residence in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki only rarely stays at the Executive Mansion, preferring to
stay most nights at his posh Victorian home in Garrison, Putnam
County. The governor does not get an extra housing allowance,
Pataki spokesman Michael McKeon said.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki controls the SUNY system through his appointments to the
SUNY Board of Trustees. The trustees selected King as chancellor
and approved the housing supplement.
</P>
<P>
   The state education commissioner used to have an official
residence in Albany but it was sold in 1995, officials said.
Education Commissioner Richard Mills does not get a housing
allowance, spokesman Thomas Dunn said.
</P>
<P>
   During their search for a chancellor, SUNY officials were told
by their search consultant, Korn/Ferry International, that the
chancellor's residence -- a penthouse suite in SUNY's baronial
central headquarters in downtown Albany -- probably would not be
suitable for a candidate with a family, McMahon said.
</P>
<P>
   King, who is married and has children has a house in Clifton
Park, told SUNY officials he didn't want to live in the
chancellor's residence, McMahon added.
</P>
<P>
   He said King plans on using the housing allowance to buy a new
house closer to his office at SUNY central.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Post first reported the SUNY housing allowance in
its Monday editions.
</P>
<P>
   SUNY had not revealed the housing allowance previously, McMahon
said, because it wasn't in the resolution that the SUNY trustees
approved for King's hiring and no one asked about it.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nobody was deliberately trying to hide the compensation,'' the
SUNY spokesman said. ''It simply wasn't revealed ... but it wasn't
hidden.''
</P>
<P>
   King's predecessor, John Ryan, also was paid $250,000 a year by
SUNY and lived in the chancellor's residence. He did not get the
housing allowance.
</P>
<P>
   The 52-year-old King, as budget director, made $147,490 a year.
</P>
<P>
   McMahon said that in setting up the supplement for King, SUNY
officials were influenced in part by the fact that City University
of New York Chancellor Matthew Goldstein -- who had been hired in
July -- got a $250,000-a-year salary and a $90,000-a-year housing
allowance.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the thoughts that went into the size of the housing
allowance for our chancellor was the size of the housing allowance
for the CUNY chancellor,'' McMahon said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They wanted to be competitive with academic peer institutions,
and first and foremost, right under their nose, is CUNY,'' McMahon
said. ''And CUNY's got that package.''
</P>
<P>
   There are differences between the SUNY and CUNY situations. CUNY
no longer had an official residence available when Goldstein took
the job. Also, housing costs are considerably less in the Albany
area than in New York City where CUNY is located.
</P>
<P>
   Without a chancellor in residence, the SUNY residence will be
used for visiting dignitaries and official university activities
like luncheons, McMahon said.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein and King are the two highest paid state employees,
even without the housing allowances, according to records
maintained by the state comptroller's office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-20-00 1648 </TRAILER>
