<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Treasury Dept. Posts Budget Deficit  </HEADLINE>
By JEANNINE AVERSA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Treasury posted a budget deficit of $41.7
billion in February, a month that typically records the lowest
revenues and the largest deficits. The government remains on track
to produce a surplus for the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Department's deficit for February, released Monday,
was smaller than the $42.3 billion deficit posted in February 1999.
It also was smaller than the $43.1 billion deficit many analysts
expected and the $44.4 billion deficit projected by the
Congressional Budget Office.
</P>
<P>
   February normally is among the months with the lowest revenues
and the largest deficits, because there generally are fewer tax
payments flowing into Treasury's coffers and more tax refunds being
paid out, budget experts said. But with Leap Year, the government
had one more collection day in February, thus helping to boost
revenues higher than those of February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue for February 2000 totaled $108.7 billion, while
expenditures came to $150.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   For the first five months of fiscal 2000, which began Oct. 1,
the government is running a deficit of $188 million. Revenue during
that period totaled $741.8 billion, while spending came to $741.9
billion.
</P>
<P>
   If a surplus materializes as expected for fiscal year 2000,
which ends Sept. 30, it would be the first time the government
reported three consecutive years of surplus since 1947, 1948 and
1949.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is predicting a $166.69 billion
surplus for fiscal 2000, while the CBO sees a $179 billion surplus.
</P>
<P>
   For fiscal year 1999, the government reported a record surplus
of $124.4 billion. The 1999 surplus followed a $69.2 billion
surplus in 1998, the first time the government finished in the
black since 1969, and the back-to-back annual surpluses were the
first since 1956 and 1957 under President Eisenhower.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, prompted by coffers brimming with government
surpluses, the Treasury said Monday it anticipates buying back some
more of the national debt during the second half of April.
Additional details were unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury has bought back over the last couple of weeks $2
billion of the debt and paid sellers around $613 million in
premiums to cash in their bonds early. Treasury Secretary Lawrence
Summers said in January the government would buy back as much as
$30 billion in debt this year.
</P>
<P>
   The government did not revise January's surplus of $62.15
billion.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the biggest spending categories were Social
Security, $35.96 billion; programs of the Health and Human Services
Department, $30.81 billion; military spending, $21.18 billion; and
interest on the public debt, $20.78 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The government collected $45.7 billion in individual income tax
payments last month compared with $42.8 billion for February 1999.
It received $1.78 billion in corporate tax payments, up from $1.18
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Treasury Site: http://www.ustreas.gov/
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Budget Office site: http://www.cbo.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
