<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli-Palestinian Talks To Resume  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID, AP Diplomatic Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Buoyed by two major Israeli concessions, the
Clinton administration is reopening negotiations between Israel and
the Palestinian Authority. Next weekend, President Clinton tries
personal diplomacy with Syrian President Hafez Assad in a parallel
bid for a second Mideast accord.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's national security adviser attributes the stepped-up
U.S. role to dynamics abroad, not to any effort to build a larger
legacy for Clinton in his final year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Time is not the friend of peace in the Middle East,'' said
Sandy Berger, traveling with Clinton in South Asia. ''Any sense of
urgency comes from their clocks and not our clocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Announcing he would meet Sunday with Assad in Geneva, Clinton
said in Dhaka, Bangladesh, ''I don't want to unduly raise
expectations, but I think this is an appropriate thing for me to do
to try to get this back on track.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate reaction to the announcement in Damascus.
</P>
<P>
   The government-run Tishrin newspaper, in an editorial that ran
before Clinton's announcement, said, ''The rulers of Tel Aviv have
not given up their expansionist greediness for the Arab lands and
their peace claims lack credibility and responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials hoped the Geneva meeting would produce a
resumption of the Israel-Syrian negotiations broken off in
mid-January.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli-Palestinian talks begin Tuesday without Clinton, who
has interceded in previous sessions, in the seclusion of
Washington's Bolling Air Force Base. They will focus on terms of a
final settlement now that Israel has designated the land it is
turning over to Yasser Arafat that would expand Palestinian control
of the West Bank to 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   American hosts anticipate about a week of talks. The two
delegations will be put up in townhouses on a quiet street on the
base and meet in a comfortable separate building.
</P>
<P>
   The two concessions by Israel are its decisions to put a Jewish
settlement under the effective security control of the Palestinians
for the first time -- a possible omen -- and to give the Palestinians
land on the outskirts of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Peace talks between Israel and Syria deadlocked after a round in
January between Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian
Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharra. Assad has not participated
directly since the talks resumed in December, following a
three-year lapse.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking for Barak, Gadi Baltiansky said Israelis hope the
Clinton-Assad meeting will lead to renewed negotiations, but he
added that ''can only take place when the circumstances are
suitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger said Clinton would not introduce any specific proposal
when he sees Assad, nor did he expect immediate results. And yet,
Berger said, ''there are some things best discussed face to face,
leader to leader.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be Clinton's third meeting with Assad. Syria's listing
by the State Department as a sponsor of terrorism bars most U.S.
economic support but has not kept the president from seeing the
Syrian leader.
</P>
<P>
   At the Israeli-Palestinian talks, Clinton's stand-in is Dennis
B. Ross, longtime American mediator, who is bound to reflect the
policy of this and past U.S. administrations that Israel should
give up territory to the Arabs in exchange for promises of peace.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli Cabinet approved a pullback from an additional 6.1
percent of the West Bank on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It puts a tiny gated Jewish settlement called Negohot, about an
hour's drive from the capital, under the effective security control
of the Palestinian Authority in that the two dozen families who
live there may be subjected to Palestinian checks entering and
leaving their community.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat lays claim to virtually all of the West Bank, where tens
of thousands of Jews live.
</P>
<P>
   In another significant concession by Barak's government, Israel
will give the Palestinians three suburbs near, but not abutting,
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   In the talks opening Tuesday over lunch at the air base,
Palestinian negotiators will be pressing for part of Jerusalem and
for a state.
</P>
<P>
   The American hosts, as they do frequently in such negotiations,
barred reporters from the base.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said Ross and his
mediating team intended to ''be helpful,'' but may not participate
in all meetings. The teams will be led by senior negotiators Oded
Eran for Israel and Yasser Abed Rabbo and Saeb Erekat for the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ''The U.S. has long believed that the Palestinian issue
represents the core of the Arab-Israeli conflict,'' the State
Department said in a statement on Friday. ''A solution that meets
the needs of both Israelis and Palestinians is essential if there
is to be a comprehensive peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. aim is an overall accord by mid-September, four months
before Clinton's term ends. A settlement, and also possibly an
agreement between Israel and Syria in which Israel gives up the
strategic Golan Heights, are key goals for Clinton is his final
year.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: AP White House Correspondent Terence Hunt
contributed to this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-20-00 1701 </TRAILER>
