<HEADLINE> 6 Men Arrested in Iran Shooting  </HEADLINE>
By AFSHIN VALINEJAD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- Six men have been arrested in the shooting
of reformist Saeed Hajjarian, Iran's security agency announced
Monday. The agency offered no information on the suspects' motives.
</P>
<P>
   One of the suspects has confessed to shooting Hajjarian in the
face on March 12, according to the Supreme National Security
Council, the nation's top security body.
</P>
<P>
   Hajjarian 46, a city councilman and confidant of President
Mohammad Khatami, regained consciousness Sunday after one week in a
coma.
</P>
<P>
   No other information on the suspects was released, and there was
no indication of their political affiliations.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-reform newspapers and Hajjarian's allies have blamed the
attack on hard-liners who oppose Khatami's cultural, social and
political reforms. The hard-liners have used vigilante groups and
members of the security forces in the past to attack or intimidate
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Abassali Alizadeh, head of the Tehran judiciary, commended the
''serious efforts'' of the Interior and Intelligence ministries and
police in apprehending the suspects, according to a report by the
Islamic Republic News Agency, IRNA.
</P>
<P>
   ''These people who were trying to disturb the security of the
country have been arrested,'' Alizadeh said. ''It is a New Year's
present for the people of Iran.'' Monday is Nowruz, or the Persian
new year.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Iranian Intelligence Minister Ali Yunesi said
police were investigating several possible suspects in the
shooting, including the Mujahedeen Khalq, an exiled dissident
group.
</P>
<P>
   Hajjarian has been ''on the hit-list of the terrorist Mujahedeen
Khalq organization since March 1999,'' IRNA quoted Yunesi as
saying. The minister stopped short of accusing the group of
carrying out the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Mujahedeen Khalq, which seeks the violent overthrow of
Iran's Islamic government, dismissed Yunesi's comments on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammad-Reza Zafarqandi, a member of the medical team treating
Hajjarian, said his patient's condition was improving daily after
he underwent two operations, according to the IRNA report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
