<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls Against Yen, Euro  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar edged lower against most major
currencies Monday in listless foreign exchange trading on the eve
of a Federal Reserve policy-making meeting, which is widely
expected to result in another increase in U.S. interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar dipped to 106.36 Japanese yen in late New York
dealings from 106.37 yen late Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar also fell against the euro, which traded at 97.34
cents, up from 97.15 cents late Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Many currency traders expect inflation fighters at the Fed to
boost interest rates by a quarter percentage point Tuesday in a bid
to keep the economy from overheating. It would be the fifth
increase since June.
</P>
<P>
   The European Central Bank raised rates one-quarter point last
week and its leader issued new inflation warnings Monday.
</P>
<P>
   European Central Bank President Wim Duisenberg told reporters in
Brussels that he expects ''continued price pressures being
exerted'' in Europe, and said the ECB had underestimated the impact
of rising oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   ''The level of oil prices has lasted longer and at a higher
level than anticipated. This has caused us to think the future
level of inflation will come closer to 2 percent than anticipated
earlier,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar fell to 1.6561 Swiss francs from 1.6590 and to 1.4694
Canadian dollars from 1.4726 Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The British pound fell to $1.5699 from $1.5758.
</P>
<P>
   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate.
Based on Friday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 2.0093 German
marks, down from 2.0134; 6.7388 French francs, down from 6.7527;
and 1,989.18 Italian lire, down from 1,993.16.
</P>
</TEXT>
