<HEADLINE> 3 Israelis Hurt in Drive-By Attack  </HEADLINE>
By NASSER SHIYOUKHI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- A gunman opened fire on a car full of Israelis,
wounding three, in a drive-by attack in the West Bank on Monday,
the car's driver said, a day before the arrival of Pope John Paul
II and the resumption of Israel-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   The shots came from a car near Tarkumia, west of the West Bank
city of Hebron. One of the Israelis was seriously wounded, another
moderately and the third lightly. Seven people were in the
Israelis' vehicle, its driver Yoram Sharabi, told Israel radio.
</P>
<P>
   Sharabi said the seven were entertainers performing for Israeli
soldiers. He said a car parked at the side of the road waited for
his vehicle to pass, then overtook it as a gunman inside opened
fire.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, drive-by shootings have been attributed to Hamas, a
Palestinian extremist group opposed to peace with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's attack came as Israel prepared to hand over another
portion of the West Bank to the Palestinians, under terms of an
interim accord signed last September. The Palestinians are to
receive control of another 6.1 percent of the West Bank on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Israel and the Palestinians are to resume talks on
a peace treaty, which broke off in early February. The talks are to
take place at Bolling Air Force Base outside Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian extremists opposed to peace with Israel have often
tried to time attacks to coincide with events in the peace process.
In 1996, a series of suicide attacks on Israeli civilian buses
caused dozens of casualties and halted the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II is to arrive in Israel on Tuesday. Visiting
Jordan on Monday, he noted the need for Middle East peacemaking,
calling the conflicts in the region ''grave and urgent.''
</P>
<P>
   The drive-by shooting took place not far from the ''safe
passage,'' an Israeli highway Palestinians are allowed to use to
drive between the West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
