<HEADLINE> Pentagon Finishes Military Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon's inspector general Monday gave
Defense Secretary William Cohen his report on how the military's
'don't ask, don't tell'' policy on homosexuality is being carried
out, Pentagon sources said.
</P>
<P>
   But the results of the three-month study will not be released
until Cohen reviews it, said Defense Department spokeswoman Susan
Hansen.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen had ordered the review -- based partly on a survey of
military personnel and on spot checks on bases and installations --
after President Clinton complained in December that the policy was
not working as intended.
</P>
<P>
   Under the military's policy on homosexuality, instituted in
1994, the military is not supposed to ask service members about
their sexual orientation, unless there is evidence of homosexual
conduct. Still, soldiers who say they are gay may be discharged.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has said the policy was never supposed to
facilitate rooting out people who are gay or allow for harassment,
both of which have occurred under the policy.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen announced new guidelines in August that would require all
troops to undergo periodic anti-harassment training and assign
investigations of homosexual activity to more senior leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said the new review also would help the
Pentagon better gauge whether the August guidelines were being
followed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
