</P>
<P>
   Analysts Expect Fed Rate Hike
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan has
bluntly signaled that the central bank will keep raising interest
rates until economic growth slows to a more moderate pace, leaving
analysts to predict another rate hike will occur tomorrow. The
central bank's interest-rate-setting Federal Open Market Committee
will announce its decision around 2:15 EST. ''It is essentially a
foregone conclusion,'' said William Cheney, chief economist at John
Hancock in Boston. ''Greenspan has laid out the logic that demand
is growing too fast, spurred by stock prices, and it is
unsustainable.'' Since last June, the Fed has raised rates four
times in quarter-point steps, boosting the federal funds rate -- the
interest banks charge each other -- to 5.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman Beats Analysts' Expectations
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc. said today its
first-quarter earnings surged 156 percent to $541 million, a figure
well above analysts' predictions. Lehman attributed its strong
results to record revenues in the company's investment banking and
securities trading businesses. Lehman earned $3.69 a share, 59
cents above high-end expectations, for the three months ended Feb.
29. During the first quarter of 1999, the firm reported net income
of $211 million, or $1.57 a share, as Wall Street recovered from a
global financial crisis brought on by economic strife in Asia and
Russia. Shares of Lehman, the fourth largest U.S. securities firm,
were down 3| at 87 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   HP, Xerox Settle Patent Suits
</P>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) -- Hewlett-Packard Co. and Xerox Corp.
have settled all pending patent-infringement suits, the companies
announced today. Both companies said they settled their differences
to avoid the costs, time and distractions of lengthy legal battles.
The agreement means all outstanding litigation, including six
patent suits filed between May 1998 and June 1999, have been
dismissed. Xerox had filed complaints involving Hewlett-Packard's
products using inkjet, color balancing and resolution enhancement
technologies. Hewlett-Packard's suits involved Xerox products using
touchscreen controls, inkjet and image enhancement technologies.
Hewlett-Packard shares were up 5 at 144, and Xerox was up 3/16 at
26.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways Urges Alternative Plans
</P>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- US Airways is warning its customers to
prepare for a possible strike Saturday by its flight attendants,
urging them to prepare alternative arrangements. The flight
attendants' union has said it would target random routes with
impromptu walkouts to cause maximum chaos. In response, the airline
has said it would shut down rather than subject passengers to
unpredictable travel. With a strike deadline of 12:01 a.m. EST
Saturday, US Airways flight attendants are back at the bargaining
table in a final attempt to resolve a three-year contract dispute
with the nation's sixth largest airline. The talks are being
supervised by Ernest DuBester, chairman of the National Mediation
Board.
</P>
<P>
   Feds Phasing Out MTBE Gas Additive
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration announced today it
will ban MTBE as a gasoline additive on grounds it poses a risk to
public health and the environment. MTBE, a leading oxygenate and
octane booster used in one-third of the gasoline sold in the United
States, reduces emissions of smog, but it has been linked to
groundwater pollution. Carol Browner, administrator of the
Environmental Protection Agency, said her agency will seek to
eliminate use of MTBEs under the Toxic Substance Control Act. She
said the ban, expected to take up to three years to implement,
would have little effect on consumer costs.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Dept. Posts Budget Deficit
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Treasury Department posted a budget
deficit of $41.7 billion in February, a month that typically
records the lowest revenues and the largest deficits. Revenue for
February 2000 totaled $108.7 billion, while expenditures came to
$150.4 billion. The deficit was smaller than the $43.1 billion
deficit many analysts expected and the $44.4 billion deficit
projected by the Congressional Budget Office. The government
remains on track to produce a surplus for the year. If a surplus
materializes as expected for fiscal year 2000, which ends Sept. 30,
it would be the first time the government reported three
consecutive years of surplus since 1947, 1948 and 1949.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Suggests World Bank Reforms
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration put forward today a
package of proposals to overhaul lending activities at the World
Bank and other regional development banks. Treasury Secretary
Lawrence Summers said that the organizations should refocus their
efforts on providing loans for projects in the world's poorest
nations that are not likely to attract support from commercial
banks. In a speech in New York, Summers said that when loans are
made to developing countries that can attract private capital, such
as China and Brazil, those loans should carry higher interest rates
than loans to the nations that don't have access to private capital
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq To Add MSN Service to PCs
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. and Compaq Computer Corp. plan
to hard-wire The Microsoft Network Internet service into the Compaq
Presario line of personal computers. Microsoft will also offer
rebates of up to $400 to Compaq customers who sign up for three
years of MSN service with the purchase of a new Presario computer.
Compaq will also combine its Compaq.net online service with MSN,
the company said in a statement. MSN sign-up will also be combined
with Compaq's registration process for new PCs, speeding up the
process of getting Internet access. The new Presario computers
featuring MSN access will be available this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon Speeding Up Deliveries
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Amazon.com unveiled an alliance today with
Kozmo.com, a quick delivery service that will bring a selection of
Amazon's books, music and toys to shoppers in less than an hour.
Amazon.com said it invested $60 million in Kozmo.com, a New
York-based e-retailer that sells and rents videos and DVDs, as well
as sells games, magazines, books and a small selection of food.
Kozmo.com's 60-minute delivery service is available in six cities --
New York, Boston, Washington, Seattle, San Francisco and Los
Angeles. It delivers all its goods by messenger and does not charge
a fee for delivery. Amazon.com is exploring partnerships with other
quick-delivery merchants.
</P>
