<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Critics, victims applaud EPA's decision to ban oxyfuels  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HAMMONTON, N.J. (AP) -- Andrea Hartley knows well the problems
with MTBE -- the breathing difficulties, the dizziness, the
headaches. The ailments, which she blames on the controversial
gasoline additive drove her to move to another state and later buy
a diesel-powered car.
</P>
<P>
   To Hartley and others, Monday's announcement that the federal
government would ban the use of MTBE was a breath of fresh air. But
she wants Congress to go a step further by banning all oxygenated
fuels.
</P>
<P>
   ''They've already subjected us to a major lab experiment over
the last 10 years,'' Hartley said.
</P>
<P>
   MTBE, a leading oxygenate and octane booster, is short for
methyl tertiary butyl ether. It is contained in about one-third of
the gasoline sold in America, according to official estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Developed in response to the Clean Air Act of 1990, it was added
to automobile fuel to reduce smog. But critics believe the cure may
have been worse than the illness.
</P>
<P>
   Hartley, of Hammonton, blames it for dizziness, headaches,
irritated nasal passages, loss of balance and other health
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are things that have come upon me, to a large degree,
since it was instituted in New Jersey,'' said Hartley, 40, a
freelance writer and mother of two.
</P>
<P>
   Her problems began in 1991. When her doctors were unable to
diagnose a specific reason for some of her ailments, Hartley began
wondering if the air she was breathing was to blame. When she
complained to the U.S. Environmental Protection Agencies and
others, they told her they'd heard similar complaints from people
exposed to MTBE.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after that, she began driving to Delaware -- where
MTBE-added gas wasn't in use -- to fill the tank of her 1987 Dodge
Caravan. That provided some relief, but it didn't last. Gas
stations there began carrying MTBE-added gas.
</P>
<P>
   Next, she began traveling from her home (she lived then in
Magnolia) to Lancaster, Pa., where she could fill up with gas that
didn't contain the oxygenated additive. She lived there for six
months, then moved back to New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Still plagued by the problems, she traded her van in for a
diesel-burning 1981 Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was like being liberated. I was able to go out again,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Many people had similar respiratory problems. But they weren't
the only ones pointing the finger at MTBE.
</P>
<P>
   The additive also found its way into groundwater supplies.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey-American Water Co., the state's largest water
utility, last month asked federal officials to stop its use after
detecting low levels of it in wells.
</P>
<P>
   The company found MTBE traces ranging from 0.5 parts per billion
to 4.5 parts per billion in six of the company's 200 wells
statewide. Among them were wells in Atlantic, Burlington and Morris
counties.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Browner, administrator of the Environmental Protection
Agency, said Monday her agency will ask Congress to eliminate a
section of the 1990 Clean Air Act that requires gasoline in areas
with serious air pollution to contain at least 2 percent oxygen by
weight.
</P>
<P>
   Browner's announcement Monday came four days after U.S. Rep.
Rodney Frelinghuysen grilled her about MTBE before the House
Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''I told Carol Browner (that) Congress is working on legislation
to ban MTBE,'' Frelinghuysen said Monday. ''In the meantime, I said
to Ms. Browner the EPA has the authority to prohibit its use now.
So I simply asked her, 'Why aren't you doing anything? Does the EPA
think MTBE is not a serious enough problem?'''
</P>
<P>
   The administration wants to replace the oxygenate standard,
which led to the use of MTBE, with a requirement that a small
percentage of all motor fuels be made from renewable sources, such
as grain.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're always pleased to see steps taken to phase out MTBE,''
said Barry Dorfman, of Maple Shade, who is director of special
projects for Oxybusters, a grassroots organization that formed in
response to MTBE-related problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''But from what I understand about the Toxic Substances Control
Act, that could take years to finally go through after all the
legal challenges that are likely to be made. I'm just not sure how
effective it will be,'' said Dorfman.
</P>
<P>
   He calls the MTBE experience ''the greatest environmental
calamity in the history of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It never even cleaned the air. Asthma rates have been
skyrocketing as its use has increased,'' Dorfman said.
</P>
<P>
   What will replace MTBE? The head of the New Jersey Farm Bureau
had a corny idea -- use more ethanol, which is made from corn.
</P>
<P>
   ''Producing ethanol fuels from New Jersey corn is a natural
complement to the state's investment in purchasing farmland to
preserve open space,'' executive director Peter Furey told the
state Assembly Environment Committee in Trenton. ''While producing
a clean, safe alternative to MTBE ... we provide an opportunity for
farmers to produce a value-added crop and provide the market
diversification they need to do business in one of the most
expensive states in the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 12.4 million gallons of ethanol were sold in New
Jersey, compared with the 3.7 billion gallons of MTBE used by
refineries.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, U.S. Rep. Bob Franks told the panel Congress should
investigate the dangers of MTBE and fund programs to clean drinking
water contaminated by it. He also called for the National
Institutes of Health to make ''the first full study'' on the effect
of MTBE on human health.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
