<HEADLINE> Wartime Pope The Subject of Debate  </HEADLINE>
By KARIN LAUB, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- His detractors say Pope Pius XII did not
condemn the Holocaust because he wanted to protect the Catholic
Church at any price. His admirers say his diplomatic silence during
World War II helped save thousands of Jewish lives.
</P>
<P>
   Among a small group of experts, Pius' wartime record has been
the subject of fierce debate for years. Now, the Holy Land visit of
the current pope, John Paul II, is prompting a wider scrutiny of
Pius XII, who has been considered by the Vatican for beatification
-- to the great dismay of Jewish leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Coinciding with John Paul's arrival in Israel on Tuesday, the
Yad Vashem Holocaust Memorial in Israel has published ''The
Holocaust and the Christian World,'' a 271-page collection of
essays and historical documents that examine the role of the
churches and church leaders, including Pius XII, during the Nazi
genocide.
</P>
<P>
   The cover photo shows high-ranking German Catholic clergymen
giving the Nazi salute, the right arm stretched out, as they stand
next to Nazi propaganda chief Josef Goebbels.
</P>
<P>
   In a chapter on the Vatican and Pius XII, historians, priests
and rabbis came to widely divergent conclusions about the pope who,
according to a recent biography by Briton John Cornwell, ''Hitler's
Pope,'' harbored a secret antipathy toward Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Historian Michael R. Marrus wrote that as fascism spread across
Europe, the Catholic Church remained aloof and rarely spoke out
against the persecution of Jews -- a continuation of its traditional
policy of political neutrality.
</P>
<P>
   The top priority of the pope was the survival of the church, not
saving lives, though individual nuns and priests took personal
risks to save Jews, wrote Marrus of the University of Toronto.
''Seeing the institutional church as a supreme value in its own
right, those in charge of its fortunes tended unhesitatingly to put
these ahead of the victims of Nazims,'' Marrus wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1943, with Rome under Nazi occupation, the Nazis
began rounding up Jews ''virtually on the doorstep of the Papal
Palace,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   However, others said there was considerable evidence that behind
the official stance of neutrality, Pius and other top church
officials tried to stop deportations of Jews or hide those being
persecuted.
</P>
<P>
   Eugene Fisher, an interfaith activist at the National Conference
of Catholic Bishops in Washington, D.C., said 80 percent of Italy's
Jews were saved, hidden largely in the monasteries and convents of
Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of Pius also pointed to Nazi reprisals against
Catholics of Jewish origin in the Netherlands in 1942, a response
to the vocal condemnation by Catholic bishops there against the
deportation of Dutch Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II is one of the strongest backers of his wartime
predecessor, much to the consternation of Jewish leaders, including
Israel's chief rabbi, Meir Israel Lau, who has close personal ties
with the pontiff and has praised him as one of the best friends the
Jewish people have ever had.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi David Rosen, an interfaith activist with strong ties to
the Vatican, said the pope's continued defense of Pius was a
''serious tactical error,'' but that during the pope's Holy Land
trip it was best not to talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope and trust that the pope is wise enough not to use this
occasion, his trip to Israel, to raise the issue of Pius XII,''
Rosen said Monday. ''I know that many in the Jewish community are
wise enough not to raise this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Ilena Steinfeldt, an editor of the Yad Vashem collection of
essays, said the book was not meant to indict the Catholic Church,
but to raise questions.
</P>
<P>
   For a more informed debate, the Vatican should grant free access
to World War II-era documents in its archives, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a general feeling that not enough was done (to stop
the genocide),'' Steinfeldt said. ''Still, we are not interested in
a declaration of guilt, but a real reckoning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
