<HEADLINE> Heating Cos. Battle For Customers  </HEADLINE>
By STEVE LEBLANC, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Memories of budget-busting heating oil price
increases during January's numbing cold wave are fueling an
advertising war in the Northeast in which natural gas providers are
trying to gain ground from oil companies.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, home heating oil prices soared to nearly $1.80
per gallon during January's record-setting cold snap, a dollar more
than last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know that the gas companies will use this past season's
price hike to try to convert our customers. We are trying to battle
that,'' said Michael Ferrante, president of the Mass Oilheat
Council Inc., representing 300 retail and wholesale oil
distributors.
</P>
<P>
   The group is one of a half-dozen in the Northeast running radio
advertisements urging customers to stick with oil, despite last
winter's skyrocketing prices.
</P>
<P>
   But natural gas distributors hoping to capitalize on consumer
fears already have begun to woo oil customers with their own ad
blitz.
</P>
<P>
   The push is paying off, according to Tom Kiley, president of the
New England Gas Association.
</P>
<P>
   Kiley said he believes consumers are looking at January oil
bills and asking, ''if this happens now, can it happen again?''
</P>
<P>
   The number of people switching from oil to gas since January has
more than doubled compared to last year, according to Michael
Durand, a spokesman for ComGas which serves the Cambridge,
Worcester and Framingham areas of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've had some pretty amazing statistics so far,'' Durand
said. ''Usually people wait until it's warmer before switching.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the January spike, oil is typically less expensive than
gas, according to Ferrante. In nine of the past 10 years oil prices
have been lower, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The oil price spike is being blamed on a supply squeeze as
international oil producers reduced production of crude oil over
the past year. The oil ads are meant to ''rebuild consumer
confidence,'' Ferrante said. Similar ads are running in
Connecticut, New Jersey, New York, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, and
the Baltimore-Washington, D.C. region.
</P>
<P>
   Kiley said some of the oil ads go too far, including one he said
implies gas companies could not provide heat to all their
residential customers.
</P>
<P>
   But even Kiley concedes oil is historically cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't quarrel with ads that say oil has been less expensive
than gas in recent years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike MacDonnell, 35, a sprinkler fitter from Braintree, Mass.,
is the kind of homeowner both groups are trying to lure. MacDonnell
heats his house with oil, but uses gas in a three-family house he
owns.
</P>
<P>
   MacDonnell said he prefers oil.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every year I had gas, the price went up every winter
regardless of what's going on with the economy,'' said MacDonnell,
who added he will keep gas in his other property. ''I don't think
it's worth the expense to switch either way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
