<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State panels would address minority concerns  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Two bills before the state Assembly and
Senate would create commissions to study the roles and concerns of
New Jersey's minority population.
</P>
<P>
   Each measure passed committee review Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill, sponsored by Sen. Wayne R. Bryant, D-Camden,
would create a 10-member commission of volunteers to advise the
governor and Legislature on issues in the African-American
community.
</P>
<P>
   The commission would offer its advice on any impact of possible
legislation on African-Americans. And, if approved by the full
Senate, it would host statewide events for that community.
</P>
<P>
   The lower house proposal, sponsored by Assembly Speaker Jack
Collins, R-Salem, and Joseph V. Doria, D-Hudson, seeks a commission
to study the social and economic status of minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's first-year duties, as outlined in the bill,
would be to collect information and hold hearings on all existing
economic programs for minorities. In its second year, the
commission would use the information to create a database of those
opportunities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
