<HEADLINE> Bonds Rise a Bit in Light Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Bonds rose slightly in light trading Monday in
advance of a Federal Reserve meeting Tuesday that is widely
expected to result in a fifth increase in short-term interest rates
since June.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond nudged up 1/32
point, or 31 cents per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves
in the opposite direction, continued to hover around Friday's late
level of 6.00 percent. The last close below 6 percent was on Sept.
24, 1999, when the long-term bond yielded 5.96 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds have rallied in recent weeks as the federal government
bought back $2 billion in long-term debt. The Treasury Department
has said it plans to buy back up to $30 billion in debt this year,
and traders are expecting much of those repurchases to go through.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, while Fed rate increases to cool off the economy
have been sending short-term rates rising, the central bank's
efforts to head off a resurgence in inflation are seen as aiding
long-term bonds. Rising inflation makes long-term fixed-income
investments less attractive.
</P>
<P>
   In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities
were down 1/32, and intermediate maturities were unchanged to up
3/32 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information
service.
</P>
<P>
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 5.96 percent as the
discount rose 0.07 percentage point to 5.78 percent. Six-month
yields were 6.15 percent, as the discount rose 0.02 percentage
point to 5.88 percent. One-year yields were 6.21 percent as the
discount rose by 0.02 percentage point from Friday to 5.86 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the
discount is the interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, fell to 5.68} percent from 5.75 percent Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds rose 5/32 point to 94 5/16. The average
yield to maturity fell to 6.06 percent from 6.07 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
