<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Impending Twinkie shortage looms from Maine to metro New York  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID SHARP, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Maine (AP) -- The Teamsters' stranglehold on shipments
of Wonder Bread, Twinkies and other Interstate Bakeries Corp.
products reached all the way down the northeastern corridor to
Philadelphia on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A Philadelphia bakery was shut down after pickets appeared
Monday, and Teamsters planned to set up pickets in Buffalo, N.Y.,
as well. A New York City bakery also was shut down over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a wave that's going to go right across the country,''
said Richard Volpe, director for the union in the United States and
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The strike began Wednesday with 1,400 Teamsters in New England
who were upset because Interstate Bakeries declined to abide by
arbitration rulings surrounding the company's only New England
plant in Biddeford.
</P>
<P>
   But the impact grew as fellow Teamsters refused to cross the
picket lines set up in other states by the New England drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The Biddeford plant made J.J. Nissen, Wonder Bread, Hostess and
Drake's Cakes products. On Friday, a bakery in Wayne, N.J., closed
and that was followed by the closing of the New York City plant on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Those plants, along with the plants in Philadelphia and Buffalo,
employ close to 3,000 members of the Bakers Union, Volpe said.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies quickly boosted production of bread, which has a
two-day shelf life. The supply of products like Hostess Twinkies
and Drake's Cakes also was becoming scarce across the New England.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's Supermarkets Inc., which owns 168 stores in New England,
posted signs in its stores on Saturday to explain that certain
baked products were not available because of the strike, said
spokesman Bernie Rogan.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of Hostess products and Drake's Cakes, Shaw's customers
are seeing more Little Debbie and Entenmann's cakes, in addition to
more Shaw's baked goods, Rogan said from his office in East
Bridgewater, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ''So far, we have not had any customers who have become
indignant over the lack of Twinkies. I think people basically
understand,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The strike has been peaceful for the most part, although a
picket was struck Thursday by a truck operated by a management
driver in Biddeford.
</P>
<P>
   The union has accused the company of refusing to honor
arbitration rulings on work rules and to let a fired trucker return
to work.
</P>
<P>
   One of the major sticking points has been the company's
requirement that drivers deliver more than one brand of Interstate
products at a time. The Teamsters say the practice violates work
rules designed to protect drivers who get paid different amounts
for each brand.
</P>
<P>
   The company maintains it was shut out of the arbitration
process, and it has asked a judge to clarify the process, said Mark
Dirkes, senior vice president for marketing in Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the financial impact on the company and lost wages,
there were no talks scheduled. Both the Teamsters and the company
said the other had to make the first move toward resolving the
stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   David Nelson, an analyst from CS First Boston in New York, said
the strike doesn't threaten Interstate Bakeries but that it will
dim the company's near-term prospects, especially when coupled with
growing gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the strike and rising gas prices, Nelson downgraded
his earnings estimates for Interstate Bakeries.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whenever you have to shut down a plant, that causes
complications and the loss of business,'' Nelson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-20-00 1826 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
