<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Killed in Drive-By Attack  </HEADLINE>
By NASSER SHIYOUKHI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israeli soldiers opened fire on a Palestinian
car at a checkpoint Monday, killing a woman and wounding her
husband, after a drive-by attack against Israelis nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings came a day before the arrival of Pope John Paul II
and two new steps in the peace process: a transfer of West Bank
territory to the Palestinians and the resumption of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers shot at the car at a roadblock near the Israeli
settlement of Tsurif, Palestinian security officials said. The
slain woman's husband suffered a gunshot in the back and was in
stable condition, said hospital officials in the nearby town of
Hebron.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear why the soldiers opened fire. The Israeli
military had no immediate information about the incident.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli roadblock was set up after a gunman fired at an
Israeli vehicle in a drive-by attack nearby earlier Monday. Three
of the seven Israelis in the car were wounded in that shooting, one
seriously, driver Yoram Sharabi told Israel radio.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, drive-by shootings have been attributed to Hamas, a
Palestinian extremist group opposed to peace with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's shootings came as Israel prepared to hand over another
portion of the West Bank to the Palestinians, under terms of an
interim accord signed last September. The Palestinians are to
receive control of another 6.1 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and Palestinian officials signed the maps late Monday.
Signing for the Palestinians, West Bank police commander Haj Ismail
Jabber said the handover would ''help push forward the peace
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Transfer of the territory, including villages near Ramallah,
Hebron and Bethlehem, was set for Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Israel and the Palestinians are to resume talks on
a peace treaty that broke off in early February. The talks are to
take place at Bolling Air Force Base outside Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Israel released 10 Palestinian security prisoners Monday as a
goodwill gesture ahead of the Washington talks. Five prisoners were
freed Sunday. The prisoners served time for killing suspected
Palestinian collaborators with Israel or injuring Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian extremists opposed to peace with Israel have often
tried to time attacks to coincide with events in the peace process.
In 1996, a series of suicide attacks on Israeli civilian buses
caused dozens of casualties and halted the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II is to arrive in Israel on Tuesday. Visiting
Jordan on Monday, he noted the need for Middle East peacemaking,
calling the conflicts in the region ''grave and urgent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-20-00 1826 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
