<HEADLINE> Accused coach admits sexually abusing teens  </HEADLINE>
AP Photo NYSYR101
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- A former youth hockey coach who admitted
having sexual contact with three teen-age boys was sentenced Monday
to 2 1/3 to seven years in state prison.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Gilbert, 36, of Brampton, Ontario, pleaded guilty earlier
this month in Onondaga County Court to three separate charges
related to three victims.
</P>
<P>
   After Gilbert completes his state prison sentence in New York,
he will be returned to Canada to face criminal charges there in
connection with his contact with one of the victims on that side of
the border.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert pleaded guilty to a felony charge of sodomy, admitting
he engaged in deviant sex with a 13-year-old Canadian boy between
July 1 and Aug. 31, 1998, while the boy was staying at his former
home in Baldwinsville.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian boy told authorities that he had more than 100
sexual encounters with Gilbert during a relationship that started
when he was 11. Most of the incidents occurred at Gilbert's
apartment in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor charge of sexual abuse
related to sexual contact with a 16-year-old boy in North Syracuse
last October.
</P>
<P>
   He also pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor charge of attempted
endangerment of a child, admitting he tried to engage in sexual
contact with a 15-year-old at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert was a volunteer assistant coach in the Lysander Youth
Hockey Association in Onondaga County for three seasons before
moving to Canada in September 1999. His teams included primarily
boys, ranging in age from 11 to 16.
</P>
<P>
   However, Gilbert never coached any of the boys he admitted
victimizing, said Chief Assistant District Attorney Rick Trunfio.
</P>
</TEXT>
