<DOCNO> APW20000320.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court: Race No Factor in Transers  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE ASSEO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court refused to allow a Maryland
school district to consider race in deciding whether to let
students transfer to another school, brushing aside a plea to
resolve how far administrators can go to promote diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Without comment, the justices on Monday sanctioned a lower court
ruling against the Montgomery County, Md., school district, which
had barred a white boy from transferring from his
minority-dominated neighborhood school to a mostly white magnet
school. In doing so, it declined a request by the National School
Boards Association to defend educators' leeway to foster diversity
in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Although the action by the justices was not a ruling, it did
leave intact the lower court position that such ''racial
balancing'' is unconstitutional when not needed to remedy past
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The Montgomery County Public Schools' lawyer, Patricia A.
Brannan, said she was disappointed the justices will not hear the
district's argument that it is trying to avoid creating ''racial
isolation'' in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very important when children are very young ... that
giving them that interracial exposure and culture makes a very
strong impression in terms of being able to deal with people
different from themselves,'' Brannan said.
</P>
<P>
   Schools can use race-neutral methods to pursue diversity,
countered Jeffrey D. Eisenberg of Silver Spring, Md., who sought to
send his son Jacob to a magnet school. ''I consider myself to
support diversity. I thought the use of racial bars was too
unfair,'' Eisenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Petersen Jennison, the Eisenbergs' lawyer, said: ''I
don't think they (the justices) want to touch, at this point, the
issue of whether diversity is a compelling governmental interest.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court will have another chance to address the issue
when it considers whether to hear a similar case from Arlington
County, Va. In that case, the same 4th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals that decided the Maryland case said the Arlington County
public schools could not consider race in deciding which children
could attend an alternative kindergarten. Both Montgomery and
Arlington counties are suburbs of the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court rulings affect all schools in Maryland, North
Carolina, South Carolina, Virginia and West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of public school districts allow children to
transfer to different schools through school-choice programs,
magnet schools or charter schools that are publicly funded but
involve less government regulation. Many have been sued over the
use of race in deciding which transfers will be allowed.
</P>
<P>
   In supporting Montgomery County, the school boards association
said that racial diversity in public schools is a lawful goal
because ''K-12 schools hold a special mission of instilling
citizenship and good character.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Montgomery County case, Jacob's parents -- Eisenberg and
Elinor Merberg -- wanted him to attend a magnet school emphasizing
math and science when he started first grade in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   They sued after school district officials barred the transfer
because it would harm the racial diversity of Jacob's neighborhood
school, Glen Haven Elementary. It was 24 percent white, 40 percent
black, 25 percent Hispanic and 10 percent Asian at the time. White
enrollment had dropped by 15 percent over the previous four years.
</P>
<P>
   The magnet school, Rosemary Hills Elementary, was 66 percent
white, 16 percent black, 14 percent Hispanic and 4 percent Asian.
</P>
<P>
   Jacob's parents said the school district's decision violated his
constitutional equal-protection rights. A federal judge refused to
order a transfer, but the 4th Circuit court struck down the school
district's policy last October.
</P>
<P>
   If student transfers lead to schools dominated by one race or
another, ''any racial or ethnic imbalance is a product of private
choices and it does not have constitutional implications,'' the
appeals court ruled.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For the appeals court ruling in Eisenberg v.
Montgomery County Public Schools:
http://www.uscourts.gov./links.html and click on 4th Circuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-20-00 1833 </TRAILER>
