<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Irabu Pleased To Be An Expo  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUPITER, Fla. (AP) -- Standing on the mound of a practice field
behind Roger Dean Stadium, Hideki Irabu was almost as far from the
Bronx as he possibly could be.
</P>
<P>
   And happy to be a Montreal Expo.
</P>
<P>
   Dealt to Montreal on Dec. 22 after falling out of favor with
Yankees owner George Steinbrenner and manager Joe Torre, the
30-year-old Japanese right-hander admitted he didn't know much
about the team he had been traded to.
</P>
<P>
   What he did know about the Expos, though, interested him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew they had some good young players that know how to play
baseball,'' Irabu said through interpreter Go Ikeda after pitching
four innings in a minor league game Tuesday. ''There's a lot of
potential here.''
</P>
<P>
   With his new teammates enjoying an off-day and just a handful of
spectators on hand on to see the game on one of the back diamonds
of the complex the Expos share with St. Louis, Irabu kept to his
five-day pitching schedule. He allowed one run and three hits to
players in the Cardinals' minor league camp.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu has fared just as well against major league competition so
far this spring, going 3-0 with a 1.50 ERA in three starts,
including five shutout innings against Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   With 12 strikeouts and just one walk in his those three games,
Irabu has proven to be everything new owner Jeffrey Loria -- a New
Yorker who grew up rooting for the Yankees -- could have wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's working as hard as we want him to,'' Montreal pitching
coach Bobby Cuellar said. ''He's a pleasure. He understands and he
fits in with everybody and everything we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he had 64 starts with the Yankees -- including 28 in
1998 and 27 last season, Irabu only made one postseason appearance
for New York, the team he had dreamed about playing for as a child.
</P>
<P>
   And that appearance -- his final one for the Yankees -- was a
13-hit, eight-run debacle while pitching 4 2-3 innings of relief
against Boston in Game 3 of the AL championship series.
</P>
<P>
   After having been called a ''fat ... toad'' by Steinbrenner
earlier in the season and cast aside on the road to two World
Series championships, Irabu is looking forward to being able to
repay the confidence that Expos manager Felipe Alou has shown him.
</P>
<P>
   Though verbal communication is impeded by the language barrier,
Cuellar says that the team is careful to ensure that Irabu always
feels comfortable about making sure that he understands what is
going on, and that he is understood, too.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we have a manager here who's really involved a lot in
that,'' Cuellar said. ''We're not smarter than anybody else but
(Alou) has a way of handling people that come from everywhere else.
We're confident that things will be fine.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've made it known -- through his translator -- to him that if
something's wrong, we want to know. If he has any problems or if
there's something we're doing and he doesn't understand it, we want
to know. We have to keep those lines of communication open and
we're doing that every day. He's like any other pitcher we've
got.''
</P>
<P>
   On a staff includes 20-somethings Dustin Hermanson, Javier
Vazquez, Mike Thurman and Carl Pavano, Irabu is by far Montreal's
most experienced starter.
</P>
<P>
   And though he'll no longer have Mariano Rivera around to close
out his starts, Irabu is impressed with the quality of the Montreal
relievers, including former teammate Graeme Lloyd and NL saves
leader Ugueth Urbina.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a very strong bullpen,'' Irabu said. ''They have a lot
of experience with Graeme, Steve Kline, Anthony Telford and
Urbina.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
