<HEADLINE> Diplomat, Man Charged in Visa Fraud  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- A U.S. diplomat and a man from Guyana have been
charged in what federal officials described as a scheme to sell
visas to enter the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas P. Carroll, 32, of Chicago and Halim Kahn, 36, of
Georgetown, Guyana, were arrested Friday on charges of conspiracy
to commit bribery and visa fraud, federal prosecutors said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney's office in Chicago said that it also seized
$535,000 and 10 gold bars from safe deposit boxes controlled by
Carroll, a State Department Foreign Service officer, in the Chicago
area.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors did not say how many visas had been sold by the two
men. But they said that at the time of their arrests they were
planning to sell an additional 250 visas for at least $1 million in
bribes.
</P>
<P>
   For 12 months starting in March 1998, Carroll was the officer in
the embassy in charge of issuing visas to Guyanese and other
foreign nationals.
</P>
</TEXT>
