<DOCNO> APW20000320.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iridium Set To Flicker Out  </HEADLINE>
By BRUCE MEYERSON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Those who plan to succeed where Iridium failed
say they've got better satellite technology, better phones and
better prices. Now they need to address Iridium LLC's biggest
problem.
</P>
<P>
   That means finding enough people who really need mobile phones
that work anywhere in the world. How else can a company hope to pay
for a multibillion dollar satellite system like the one Iridium is
about to destroy in the Earth's atmosphere?
</P>
<P>
   Globalstar Telecommunications LP, the second company to launch a
space-based wireless phone service, is salivating now that its
bankrupt predecessor is about to flicker out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Iridium told a bankruptcy court on Friday that it
wants to pull its satellites from orbit because it can't find new
investors, Globalstar began offering a trade-in on Iridium phones
that were soon to be worthless.
</P>
<P>
   But if Globalstar were to grab every one of Iridium's 55,000
subscribers, it would still be hard to say Globalstar will ever
find enough customers to produce a profit for its investors, led by
Loral Space and Communications.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Wall Street's take on Globalstar has only worsened as
Iridium's fortunes took turn after turn for the worse in recent
months. Since the start of the year, Globalstar's shares have lost
two-thirds of their value. And as Iridium's saga turned hopeless
over the past two weeks, at least two major brokerages lowered
their ratings on Globalstar.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred by these humbling experiences, pedigree names
continue to stake their reputations on the satellite concept,
including Boeing and none other than Craig McCaw, the wireless
pioneer.
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt the global market looks just as ripe as it did
when Motorola Corp. conceived of Iridium more than a decade ago.
More than 3 billion people have never made a phone call, wireless
or wired, and satellites may provide an easier way to connect those
people than installing cables.
</P>
<P>
   However, it's unclear whether many of those people can afford to
pay the type of rates the satellite companies need to recoup their
investment. Likewise, while just 10 percent of the planet is
covered by land-based cellular networks, most of the people who can
afford mobile phones live in that small swath of the world where
regular wireless service is available.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can only compete in areas where there's no cellular
service, and the number of users who can afford (satellite phone
prices) is uncertain,'' said John Coates, the satellite industry
analyst for Salmon Smith Barney. ''The concept still makes sense,
but you can't generate profits if the price of service is 10 times
greater than cellular.''
</P>
<P>
   While Globalstar has tried to differentiate itself with prices
well below even the reduced prices instituted by Iridium last
summer, it's not so clear that ordinary consumers and business
people will be willing to pay more than a dollar per minute for
wireless calling when regular cellular minutes are now tallied in
dimes and quarters.
</P>
<P>
   If everyday consumers and business travelers won't pay for it,
that leaves a rather limited pool of specialized markets such as
the military, oil rigs, ships at sea and mountain climbers.
</P>
<P>
   ''The price of wireless is coming down significantly, and the
satellite providers are suggesting they can take the price back
upstream,'' said Gary Miller, chief executive of Aragon Consulting
Group, a St. Louis-based research firm. ''They have a faulty
business model that would have early adopters fund the growth of
the satellite system and be the front engine to pull the mass
consumer in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-20-00 1845 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000320.0177 </DOCNO>
