<HEADLINE> Jets Sign Shane Burton  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. (AP) -- The New York Jets signed their first
unrestricted free agent of the offseason, defensive tackle Shane
Burton, who agreed to a one-year deal Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Burton, entering his fifth pro season, can earn as much as
$700,000 through incentives for the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel there is a tremendous upside for Shane, who was hurt
for much of last year with a shoulder injury and did not play much
with the Bears,'' agent Drew Rosenhaus said. ''He wanted to play
for Bill Parcells and Al Groh and Mike Nolan and Ray Hamilton. The
Jets have an exciting scheme, and besides that, (linebacker) Marvin
Jones, who is my client, told me the Jets need more big people.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton is 6-foot-6, 305 pounds. The Jets are expected to use a
3-4 alignment, but need some versatility up front, where they tend
to rotate linemen.
</P>
<P>
   ''As an NFL veteran, Shane Burton has displayed the toughness
and experience that should be attributes for him in competing for a
spot on the defensive line,'' Jets coach Groh said.
</P>
<P>
   A fifth-round pick in the 1996 draft out of Tennessee, Burton
played his first three seasons with the Miami Dolphins. He was
waived by Miami in training camp last summer and signed by Chicago.
He appeared in 15 games, but played sparingly and had only 14
tackles and three sacks.
</P>
<P>
   Burton also will be used on special teams. He has blocked four
field goals in his career.
</P>
</TEXT>
