<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Infielder Hayes Released by Mets  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. (AP) -- Infielder Charlie Hayes, told he
wouldn't make the New York Mets' opening day roster, was released
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes played in 11 spring training games, hitting .386
(10-for-26) with two doubles, one home run, and seven RBIs. Hayes,
34, had signed as a free agent Jan. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the important thing for me now is to be with my
family,'' Hayes said. ''I talked to (Mets GM Steve) Phillips and
Bobby (Valentine) and they pretty much told me I wasn't going to
make the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said several clubs have expressed interest in Hayes and
the 11-year major league veteran will remain at the Mets' training
complex for a few days to ponder any offers.
</P>
<P>
   ''It didn't appear that Charlie was going to make our team, so
we decided to give him his release so he might have a chance to
catch on with another team,'' Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes has played for the Giants, Phillies, Yankees, Rockies and
Pirates, and was a member of the Yankees 1996 World Series
championship team. Hayes has a .264 career average with 232
doubles, 135 home runs and 690 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ''We tried to be honest with Charlie,'' Valentine said. ''He
wanted to be seen and we let other teams see him. He was hitting
the ball well. I think he can still play. His effort for us was
very good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
