<HEADLINE> Sosa Sits Out Game With Bad Knee  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, Ariz. (AP) -- Next time, Sammy Sosa will run over the
catcher.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Cubs' star sat out Monday's game and will skip
Tuesday's road trip because of a banged-up knee he got in a
home-plate collision with Colorado Rockies catcher Scott Servais.
The injury isn't serious.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's swollen a little bit, but it's nothing we need to worry
about,'' said Sosa, who looked like his normal self, cracking jokes
in the clubhouse and cranking up his radio. ''Nothing big.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's right knee hit Servais' shin guard when they collided
Sunday. He had a few cuts and scrapes, and his knee was still
slightly swollen Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   He said he'd play if this was the regular season. But since it's
spring training, Chicago Cubs manager Don Baylor decided to give
him some time off.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I play him on it today, it's going to be sore,'' Baylor
said. ''We can't have him limping when we go in to start the
season. So one day of treatment and rest will probably help him a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa has been one of the most durable Cubs the past three
seasons. He played in 162 games last year and in 1997, and appeared
in 159 games in 1998, when he hit 66 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ''In one or two days, my knee will be great,'' Sosa said. ''I'll
be ready to play 162 games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
