<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Urged To Reduce Poverty  </HEADLINE>
By MARTIN CRUTSINGER, AP Economics Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The World Bank should refocus its efforts
toward reducing poverty in the world's poorest countries, the
Clinton administration said Monday as it offered a package of
changes aimed at blunting a congressional effort for an even more
radical overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said the World Bank and
regional development banks working in Asia, Africa and Latin
America should be more selective in the kinds of loans they make.
They should emphasize poverty reduction, Summers said, while
leaving financing of commercial projects to the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Summers said the development banks should reward countries that
best use foreign loans to alleviate poverty, rather than lending
only to countries that face the direst financial circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ''We recognize that there will inevitably be a tension between
helping the countries most in need and helping those who will use
multilateral development bank resources well,'' Summers said. ''But
... increasingly we need to shift the balance in favor of providing
support to countries where donors can have confidence that
assistance will be well used.''
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the Council on Foreign Relations in New York,
Summers said that when loans are made to poor countries that can
attract private capital, such as China and Brazil, those loans
should carry higher interest rates than the World Bank charges for
loans to the poorest nations that lack access to private capital
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Summers' package of proposals also included recommendations for
the development banks to emphasize loans for vaccines to fight
health problems of the Third World and projects that would protect
the environment.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's reform proposals for the development banks
followed a similar set of recommendations by Summers in December to
overhaul the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, the administration's proposals do not go nearly
so far as those of an advisory commission appointed by Congress.
That panel, chaired by economist Allan Meltzer of Carnegie Mellon
University, recommended limiting the IMF to providing short-term
emergency loans to countries facing balance-of-payments crises.
</P>
<P>
   The Meltzer panel also wanted the World Bank to eliminate the
two-thirds of its lending that goes to countries such as China and
Brazil, which have access to global capital markets.
</P>
<P>
   The administration hopes its more modest reform package will
shape the upcoming debate in Congress and at the spring meetings of
the IMF and World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to questions from the audience, Summers said groups
that support the aims of the IMF and the World Bank to fight
poverty need to build a grass-roots constituency in the United
States to air their views in Congress. Conservative Republican
members are supporting the more radical cutbacks favored by the
Meltzer commission.
</P>
<P>
   ''Until that constituency (to battle global poverty) is larger,
this will be a very difficult fight,'' Summers said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States does not have the power to impose changes on
the IMF and the other multinational lending institutions, but the
size of U.S. voting shares in all of the organizations gives
America a powerful voice for arguing change.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 182-nation IMF and its sister lending agency,
the World Bank, both of which are headquartered in Washington, the
regional development banks are the Inter-American Development Bank,
the Asian Development Bank and the African Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Summers said in all the debate, the world should not lose sight
of the important role played by the development banks in promoting
global prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ''The work of the World Bank and the regional development banks
is probably more important now than it has ever been,'' Summers
said. ''As the president has often observed, today the United
States has as much to fear from states that are too weak as states
that are too strong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
