<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minn. Secures 12,000 Season Tickets  </HEADLINE>
By ARNIE STAPLETON, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- The Minnesota Wild has met NHL guidelines
for expansion clubs by securing 12,000 season tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a great day in Minnesota Wild history,'' club CEO Jac
Sperling said Monday, seven months before the team begins play in
the new 18,600-seat Saint Paul Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL requires that expansion clubs reach the 12,000 season
ticket mark by April 15.
</P>
<P>
   ''This validates the NHL's return to Minnesota and we look
forward to building a championship team for our fans,'' Wild
president Tod Leiweke said.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL awarded teams to St. Paul and Columbus, Ohio, in its
latest round of expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota lost the North Stars to Dallas in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Sperling said it was ''a daunting task'' to secure 12,000 season
tickets, including suites and club level seats at the new arena,
which will be completed in September just before the Wild's
inaugural season.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've had an unbelievably high conversion rate of over 90
percent,'' Sperling said.
</P>
<P>
   The league average for the last five expansion teams -- San Jose,
Anaheim, Florida, Nashville and Atlanta -- was a 69 percent
conversion rate, team spokesman Bill Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   At a ceremony Monday, Gordie Howe presented the 12,000th Wild
season ticket holder, Dennis Pladson, 56, of South Saint Paul, with
a team jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ''People are so important to the game of hockey,'' Howe said.
''It's tough playing to half a house, and believe me, I've been
there before.''
</P>
<P>
   At a reception, Howe's wife, Colleen, surprised the team by
announcing the couple planned to become Wild season ticket holders
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ''Gordie and I are going to purchase four season tickets and we
will rely on the Wild management to distribute them,'' she said.
''We wanted to do something for kids who would not normally have
the opportunity to see a hockey game in such a beautiful setting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-20-00 1926 </TRAILER>
