<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State recommends more spending for foreign languages, smallerclasses  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY PARELLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Some school districts would get more state
funding to help pay for foreign language instruction and to lower
class sizes in elementary grades, under new school funding
guidelines released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Most districts would also see a jump in their special education
funding in the 2001-2002 school year, under the figures released
Monday by the state Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   The department released the amounts it deems necessary for
districts to deliver the ''thorough and efficient education''
required by the state constitution. The new figures don't kick in
until the 2001-2002 school year.
</P>
<P>
   The state Legislature must approve the amounts, which vary by
grade levels, before they become final.
</P>
<P>
   The figures are one factor in a complicated formula that
determines how much state aid each district receives. Enrollment
and a district's wealth are other major factors used to determine
state aid.
</P>
<P>
   The per-pupil amounts vary from about $3,900 for each
kindergartner to about $8,780 for each high school student.
Currently, those amounts range from $3,541 to $8,500. The
department issues the funding report every two years.
</P>
<P>
   Districts can spend more or less, depending on local need. And,
most districts receive only a portion of their funding from the
state. The rest comes from property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   State Education Commissioner David Hespe is recommending the
biggest increase -- nearly 10 percent -- for elementary schools.
</P>
<P>
   He wants the state to help districts lower class sizes from an
average of 21 to 18 in grades kindergarten through third.
</P>
<P>
   Hespe is also recommending the state begin to fund its mandate
that all elementary schools teach a foreign language by 2001-2002.
Educators have complained that the state is failing to provide any
funding for that requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new figures, districts with increasing elementary
enrollment stand to gain the most, said Mike Azzara, the education
department's assistant commissioner of finance.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will redistribute aid to those districts that have a
greater percentage of elementary students,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Most districts would also enjoy a boost in special education
funding -- another area that educators have long complained the
state underfunds. The guidelines range from $315 per pupil for
children with the mildest disabilities to about $13,000 for
students with severe disabilities. Currently, the amounts range
from $300 to about $12,600.
</P>
<P>
   Middle and high schools would receive increases to keep pace
with inflation, under the new figures.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Belluscio, a spokesman for the New Jersey School Boards
Association, said the increases for elementary schools and special
education are good news.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're recognizing that school districts are going to have
costs associated with the world language standard and that has not
been recognized before,'' said Belluscio.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the state is acknowledging that districts are
incurring legitimate costs to educate children with learning
problems by restoring -- and increasing -- special education funding
that was cut a couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The report also outlines costs for preschools, which the state
Supreme Court has ordered for all 3- and 4-year-olds in 30 of New
Jersey's poorest districts.
</P>
<P>
   The new numbers provide that districts would receive $4,575 per
preschool student, or between about $500 to $800 for each student
in the district, whichever is greater, Azzara said.
</P>
<P>
   The new figures would give more money to districts that have a
growing preschool and elementary enrollment, Azzara said, adding
that about half of the 30 ''special needs'' districts would receive
''significant'' increases in preschool funding.
</P>
<P>
   But David Sciarra, director of the Education Law Center, which
represents poor children in the 30-year-old school funding fight,
said the numbers are, once again, based on models rather than the
needs of children.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no explanation of how they arrived at $4,575 per pupil
for preschool,'' said Sciarra. ''This report needs to be rejected
by the Legislature. They should order (the education department) to
come up with a number that has some basis in the real world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-20-00 1929 </TRAILER>
