<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Chief Hopes For Aid  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Colombian Defense Minister Luis Fernando
Ramirez said Monday night he is hopeful Congress will approve $1.6
billion in assistance for Colombia within the next month, but he
cautioned that the proposal could be delayed until later this year
or scuttled altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez met with reporters at the State Department after a day
of consultations with Clinton administration officials and
congressional leaders.
</P>
<P>
   During his meetings, he reviewed the steps his government is
taking to combat human rights violations -- a major source of
concern among many lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez said the package, aimed primarily at combatting drug
traffickers, should be taken up by the full House next week and by
the Senate shortly thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not clear it will be approved, but all efforts are being
made to see it passed before Holy Week,'' he said. Holy Week begins
on April 16, Palm Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is part of a $9 billion assistance package that
also includes money for Kosovo and other trouble spots. Ramirez
indicated he was concerned that the package could be rejected not
because of opposition to the assistance to Colombia but because of
other aspects of the package.
</P>
<P>
   On March 9, the House Appropriations Committee voted 33-13 to
send the proposal to the full House. It contains $1.7 billion in
assistance to combat drug trafficking in the Andes, the bulk of the
money earmarked for Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez said the costs to Colombia will be high if Congress
decides to handle the aid program through the normal appropriations
process rather than on an emergency basis.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it is not treated as an emergency supplemental, it would
delay the implementation of the process in Colombia,'' he said,
noting that a large part of the request is not cash but rather
equipment, such as helicopters that must be ordered and assembled.
</P>
<P>
   Delays would only assist drug traffickers in southern Colombia
against whom the aid package is primarily directed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his meetings here, Ramirez is using his U.S.
visit to tell private groups that the aid request is worthy of
support. He flew here after a visit to San Francisco and planned to
meet with groups at Harvard University on Tuesday before returning
to Colombia later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   State Department:
http://www.state.gov/www/regions/wha/index.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-20-00 1935 </TRAILER>
