<HEADLINE> DaimlerChrysler Probe Expanded  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The federal government has expanded its
investigation into possible gasoline tank leaks on DaimlerChrysler
minivans during side-impact crashes to include 2000 model-year
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The gas tank of a 2000 Dodge Caravan leaked during recent
government testing, said officials from the National Highway
Traffic Safety Administration. Two earlier NHTSA crash tests on
1999 minivans also exposed gas leaks that could spark fires.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler spokesman Mike Aberlich said the company is
conducting its own tests, but has not seen similar results. He also
said the company had no complaints of fuel leakage or fires because
the tank's hose came loose in crashes on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're working to try to figure out what it is they saw and why
because as we look at the real world accidents that have happened
with minivans over the years, we haven't seen this phenomenon,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The NHTSA side-impact tests are designed to gauge how well the
vehicle protects passengers in a crash, not gas-tank performance.
It simulates a vehicle crashing into the side of the minivan at
about 30 mph.
</P>
<P>
   During a test of a 1999 Dodge Caravan minivan on Jan. 5, the
hose that channels gasoline from the gas pump into the minivan's
fuel tank pulled loose from the tank, and half the tank's test fuel
spilled out, an agency report said.
</P>
<P>
   That led to an investigation focused on the Dodge Caravan and
Grand Caravan, Plymouth Voyager and Grand Voyager, and Chrysler
Town and Country from model years 1996 through 1999. The
investigation, begun in June, initially focused on more than 2
million minivans, but expands by about 750,000 with the year-2000
models.
</P>
<P>
   NHTSA opens any safety investigation with a preliminary inquiry
in which the government and manufacturer exchange paperwork
including any complaints. An investigation eventually can lead to a
recall, but many are dropped.
------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.nhtsa.dot.gov.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
