<HEADLINE> Coast Guard Returns Ecuadoreans  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- A U.S. Coast Guard cutter turned 234
Ecuadoreans over to national authorities Monday after intercepting
their boat as they tried made their way for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Ecuadorean-registered boat, the Viviana II, was seized
Saturday morning in the Pacific Ocean 240 miles off the Andean
nation's shore by the Thetis, a U.S. Coast Guard cutter based out
of Key West, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Ecuador's navy said the 40 women and 194 men found on the
Viviana II were all from the country's central Andes and were
detained because they were traveling through international waters
without documentation.
</P>
<P>
   The passengers, all reportedly in good condition, were handed
over to Ecuadorean officials Monday, the navy said, and were being
held in the port of Esmeraldas, 112 miles northwest of the capital,
Quito.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear what charges, if any, would be
lodged against them.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Steve Matthews, spokesman for the Coast Guard in Miami, said
the U.S. government received permission from Ecuador to stop the
vessel.
</P>
<P>
   Their intended destination was Nicaragua, U.S. Coast Guard and
Ecuador authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Knight, a spokeswoman for the U.S. Coast Guard's 11th
District in San Francisco, said a growing number of Ecuadoreans are
using high seas routes to Central America and Mexico to illegally
reach the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''The last one that we intercepted was in January and that was
the fourth or fifth in the last 12 months,'' she told The
Associated Press. ''We've noticed a rapidly growing trend of
Ecuadoreans boarding these vessels and heading for other ports with
the ultimate destination being the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Ecuador's 12 million people are struggling through their worst
economic crisis in decades. Last year, some 320,000 citizens
legally emigrated from the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
