<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Court To Hear Burma Case  </HEADLINE>
By JEAN McMILLAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- A Massachusetts law against doing business with
Myanmar because of its poor human rights record has confronted the
U.S. Supreme Court with a fundamental constitutional question: Can
state and local governments make their own foreign policy?
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge and an appeals court have said no, and
Massachusetts has appealed to the nation's highest court. As the
justices hear the case Wednesday, cities and states with similar
laws and activist groups will be watching closely.
</P>
<P>
   ''More and more people who are becoming interested in grassroots
influence on international affairs and human rights issues see this
may be a turning point in the techniques they will be able to
use,'' said state Rep. Byron Rushing, who sponsored Massachusetts'
law.
</P>
<P>
   Myanmar, the Southeast Asian nation formerly known as Burma, is
one of the world's poorest countries and is controlled by its
military. The United States and other countries have restricted aid
since thousands of protesters were gunned down in a 1988
pro-democracy uprising.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago -- while U.S. policy still allowed trade with
Burma -- Massachusetts lawmakers barred the state from buying goods
and services from companies that do business with Myanmar -- unless
there is no other comparable bid. Exceptions were made for
purchases of some medical devices, for news-gathering companies and
for telecommunications companies.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the so-called Burma Law said they had a right to
influence foreign policy and decide how to spend taxpayers' money,
calling it a matter of free speech and states' rights.
</P>
<P>
   Several months after the law was approved, the federal
government imposed similar but less restrictive trade sanctions on
Myanmar. So the Supreme Court, which is expected to rule by late
June, could decide that the Massachusetts law is essentially moot
because of the federal action.
</P>
<P>
   But the state's opponents, including the National Foreign Trade
Council, which represents 580 major U.S. corporations and sued
Massachusetts over the law, hope the court goes much further -- and
restricts state and local governments' rights to enact such laws.
</P>
<P>
   The trade group and the U.S. government say foreign policy
matters ought to be left to Washington, so as not to weaken the
United States' position as a business partner. They cite the
constitutional provision granting foreign policy powers to the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ''The country has to be able to speak with one voice,'' said
Frank Kittredge, president of the trade council.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Massachusetts law was struck down by a federal
judge in 1998 and the decision was later upheld by an appeals
court, there are about 20 similar laws elsewhere in the country,
including in New York City, Ann Arbor, Mich., and Chapel Hill, N.C.
Other cities are considering such restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Rushing pointed out that if local governments cannot set such
purchasing rules, activists might turn to such tactics as consumer
boycotts, which he said are potentially more detrimental in the
long-term to U.S. companies.
</P>
<P>
   But Kittredge said competitors in other countries see differing
state and local policies in the United States and use that as a
sales tactic, telling potential customers that an American company
may not be a reliable supplier.
</P>
<P>
   ''For a business perspective, it's a terrible thing,'' said
Robin Conrad, a lawyer for the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, which also
opposes the Burma Law. ''You've got 50 states plus the District of
Columbia, 309,000 sub-federal jurisdictions, able to enact their
policies. It makes an overall mess of things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-20-00 2046 </TRAILER>
