<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wis. Sues Shalala Over Organ Rules  </HEADLINE>
By JENNY PRICE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- Wisconsin and its two major transplant
centers sued U.S. Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala
on Monday over new rules intended to change the way organs are
distributed for transplants.
</P>
<P>
   The rules order the United Network for Organ Sharing to send
more organs to the sickest patients, regardless of where they live.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, organs are distributed locally first. Wisconsin
stands to lose under the new system because its organ donation
rates are high and its patients generally get organs faster than
those in other states.
</P>
<P>
   In its lawsuit, the state claims Shalala's agency stripped the
United Network for Organ Sharing, the private agency running the
nation's transplant program, of the power to decide how organs
should be allocated.
</P>
<P>
   It also claims Shalala's actions unlawfully substitute her
personal judgment for that of medical professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin officials are seeking an injunction to prevent Shalala
from enforcing the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Health and Human Services officials disputed the lawsuit's
claims.
</P>
<P>
   ''The regulation is entirely grounded in the law as Congress
intended,'' said Jon Nelson, who oversees the department's
transplant division.
</P>
<P>
   Policy experts in Congress and others believe it would be
unconstitutional for Shalala to lose her authority to set policy.
Legislation pending in Congress would clarify who has authority to
set the transplant policy.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Louisiana has also tried to stop the new rules in
court in a case now on hold. South Carolina has threatened a
lawsuit as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
