<HEADLINE> Monday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
<TEXT>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Funeral For Preschoolers Held in Quebec
</P>
<P>
   NICOLET, Quebec (AP) -- The signs of lives ended much too soon
were everywhere Monday at the funeral for two of the seven
pre-schoolers killed in a minivan collision last week on a day-care
outing.
</P>
<P>
   A blue teddy bear holding a child's flannel blanket sat on a
table overlooking the somber mourners who crowded the local Roman
Catholic cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   Two small, white coffins lay side by side. Placed behind them
were lovingly crafted, colorful posters of sunshine and doves.
</P>
<P>
   The simple service was attended by about 500 family, friends and
others who just wanted to say a quiet goodbye to five-year-old Karl
Tailly-Duval and his playmate Viviane Cloutier, four.
</P>
<P>
   Funerals also were held in other communities on Monday for
two-year-old Stacy Roy and Frederic Isabel-Fournier, five.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Safety Advocates Urge Proper Use of Seat-Belts After Quebec
Accident
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- The tragic crash of a day-care minivan that
killed seven pre-schoolers in Quebec has parents and safety
advocates taking a second look at how children are secured in
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary inquest shows each of the 10 children traveling to
a maple sugar shack was probably wearing a seat belt when the
deadly collision occurred. However, the same belt might have been
used to secure as many as three children.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian Automobile Association said Monday it has anecdotal
evidence to suggest many parents, unaware of the risk at which they
are putting their children, are not following safety
recommendations for buckling up their kids.
</P>
<P>
   ''Absolutely never strap more than one child to a seat-belt,''
Rosalinda Fischer, manager of public and government affairs for the
CAA, warned emphatically.
</P>
<P>
   ''That shouldn't happen. A seat-belt was designed to hold one
person. The reason for that is if two people are strapped together,
on impact, their heads and bodies are going to crash together.''
</P>
<P>
   ---
Liberals Makes no Apologies For Export Loans
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- The Liberals made no apologies Monday for giving
loans to foreign governments, agencies and companies to buy
Canadian, while the Economic Development Corporation called reports
of bad loans ''a complete fabrication.''
</P>
<P>
   EDC spokesman Rod Giles said it's not true that the
taxpayer-backed EDC rang up $22 billion in outstanding loans -- of
which $2.8 billion had been written off.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are probably confusing that with the amount of money we
have set aside in the event we need to cover lost loans.''
</P>
<P>
   Giles confirmed that $1 billion was given to the U.S. railroad
Amtrak to support Canadian companies that make equipment and
supplies. He refused to disclose details.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Amtrak loans are already being repaid.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Conference Board To Study Soaring Gas Prices For Feds
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- A study commissioned by the federal government on
soaring gas prices will do nothing to help consumers grappling with
the problem now, critics say.
</P>
<P>
   Industry Minister John Manley announced in the Commons on Monday
the study will examine why gas prices have ballooned in the past
year and report back by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Conference Board of Canada, a public policy think-tank, will
study the relationship between prices at the pump and the price of
crude oil, consumer demand and gasoline supply.
</P>
<P>
   It will also look into the conduct, structure and performance of
the gasoline industry.
</P>
<P>
   While many agreed a broader study is probably a good idea,
critics said the issue has already been studied to death and the
government is simply ducking responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really have to wonder how credible and sincere the desire to
help is here,'' said David Bradley of the Canadian Trucking
Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ---
British Columbia Farmer on Combine Ends Protest Journey in Ottawa
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- After harvesting bushels of public attention with
his protest trek from British Columbia, grain farmer Nick Parsons
parked his big red combine on Parliament Hill on Monday to make
some political hay.
</P>
<P>
   The producer, who lumbered his way to Ottawa at speeds of about
20 kilometers hour, took his concerns about the future of farm
families to Agriculture Minister Lyle Vanclief.
</P>
<P>
   But Parsons, 52, was shut out of Prime Minister Jean Chretien's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Police later forced him to move his Massey Ferguson combine,
festooned with banners and bumper stickers, to a park area several
kilometers away from the Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Vanclief wouldn't promise more farm aid but said the issue will
arise again this week when he meets with provincial agriculture
ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Chretien has refused repeated invitations to visit Prairie farms
hit hard by what many say is the worst income crisis since the
Depression.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
