<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressDon Baker:
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Don Baker, a journalist known as a
defender of laws aimed at keeping government meetings and records
open to the public, died Sunday. He was 52.
</P>
<P>
   Baker had worked at the Deseret News covering Salt Lake and
Davis county suburbs since 1997. He was also the paper's curling
specialist for the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to joining the Deseret News, Baker worked at the
Standard-Examiner in Ogden for 27 years.
</P>
<P>
   Baker received numerous awards for his reporting, including the
1993 Clifford P. Cheney Service to Journalism Award, the top honor
given out each year by the Utah Society of Professional
Journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Baker worked to get the Utah Legislature in 1991 to adopt the
Government Records Access and Management Act, which opened many
government records to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Baker also was an accomplished bluegrass musician who once
played for President Jimmy Carter at a White House picnic.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Andrea, two children and six
stepchildren.
DeAnn Evans:
</P>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- DeAnn Evans, associate professor of
journalism at the University of Utah and the first female managing
editor of a Utah newspaper, died Sunday of a heart attack. She was
59.
</P>
<P>
   A specialist in media criticism and ethics, Evans spent her
career in Salt Lake City, where she built a reputation as a devoted
educator.
</P>
<P>
   Evans joined the Deseret News in 1967 and worked her way up the
ranks before being named managing editor in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   She left in 1989 to pursue her doctorate at the University of
Utah and then became associate professor of communications there.
</P>
<P>
   A former president of the Utah chapter of the Society of
Professional Journalists, Evans received the group's Clifford P.
Cheney Service to Journalism Award for her lifetime contributions
to Utah journalism in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Evans is survived by her brother, Republican state Sen. R. Mont
Evans, and a sister.
John T. Hicks:
</P>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Retired state Sen. John T. Hicks, who
once forced a committee meeting to adjourn for lack of a quorum by
declaring ''I'm not here,'' died Sunday of a heart attack. He was
74.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks was a crafty Democrat who at a 1989 meeting of the Senate
Oversight Committee blocked a vote on the method for selecting
state Supreme Court justices by insisting he was absent, thereby
preventing the committee from meeting its quorum.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks served in the state House from 1965 to 1976 and in the
state Senate from 1977 to 1992.
J. Russell King:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- J. Russell King, a New York Times deputy news
editor often responsible for laying out the front page, died
Saturday of AIDS-related pneumonia. He was 45.
</P>
<P>
   Russell taught high school for a year before becoming a
journalist. He worked briefly at The Wichita Eagle and The Miami
Herald before joining the Times as a copy editor in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   His journalistic skills, language aptitude and knowledge of
national and world affairs propelled him to the Times news desk, a
small group of editors who polish copy as it leaves the newsroom
departments and oversee preparation of the front page.
</P>
<P>
   King spent the last decade on the news desk, refining the
content and style of major stories and their accompanying
headlines. Often, King laid out Page 1 in consultation with the
paper's top editors.
</P>
<P>
   King was a member of the National Lesbian and Gay Journalists
Association and served as a mentor for many new Times staff
members.
</P>
<P>
   Among the small crew that works into the early morning hours
preparing the newspaper, he started a tradition of wearing formal
attire to work on New Year's Eve.
Kermit Anthony Tarleton:
</P>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Kermit Anthony Tarleton, a reporter and
editor whose journalism career in Louisiana spanned four decades,
died Sunday of a brain tumor. He was 70.
</P>
<P>
   During his career at the Times-Picayune and the now-defunct New
Orleans States-Item, Tarleton worked as a reporter, rewrite man and
night city editor. He earned a reputation as a gruff boss who
helped mold a generation of young reporters.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, Tarleton served in the Navy on destroyers.
He was drafted into the Army in 1950 for the Korean War and served
with the 3rd Logistical Command Headquarters Detachment.
</P>
<P>
   Tarleton started working for the Times-Picayune in the 1950s,
then worked for the Stars and Stripes military newspaper in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Upon his return to New Orleans, Tarleton worked for the New
Orleans States, which later became The States-Item. He returned to
The Times-Picayune in 1980 shortly before it merged with The
States-Item.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his wife, Ethel, and three sons and five
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
