<HEADLINE> Bronx woman arrested after confrontation aboard America Westflight  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- Five days after a man attacked an
airline co-pilot over California, an irate Bronx woman was arrested
Monday aboard an America West jetliner after allegedly entering the
cockpit in flight and striking another co-pilot, the FBI said.
</P>
<P>
   Flight 2186, an Airbus A-320 jetliner bound for Phoenix from New
York's John F. Kennedy International Airport with 128 passengers
and five crew members aboard, was diverted to Albuquerque because
of the disturbance, agent Doug Beldon said.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Laverne Brown, 39, of the Bronx, was arrested at about 5
p.m., Beldon said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was charged with committing a crime aboard an aircraft,
namely interfering with a flight crew, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Apparently she refused to return to her seat, failed to obey
the orders of the flight personnel, became angry, went into the
cockpit and struck the co-pilot,'' Beldon said. ''The passenger was
obviously under the influence of alcohol. She threatened a flight
attendant and assaulted the co-pilot.''
</P>
<P>
   She faces an initial appearance Tuesday before a U.S. magistrate
and was spending the night at the Bernalillo County Detention
Center, Beldon said.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, a 39-year-old Missouri man broke into an Alaska
Airlines cockpit and grappled with a co-pilot. The FBI and Federal
Aviation Administration reported that Peter L. Bradley Jr. of Blue
Springs, Mo., apparently tried to seize control of the throttle and
fuel controls near Monterey, Calif. Bradley was arrested when the
plane landed in San Francisco after the flight from Puerto
Vallarta, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Police Officer Joe Reilly said the man displayed
bizarre behavior, spoke nonsense, took off his socks and shirt and
yelled to the other 42 passengers: ''I'm going to kill you all.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately known what Brown was unhappy about
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   America West spokeswoman Patty Nowack said she couldn't release
details and declined to say what triggered the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ''We did have an incident with an unruly passenger. The captain
decided to divert to have this passenger removed due to concern for
flight safety,'' Nowack said in Phoenix.
</P>
</TEXT>
