<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bolivia Flooding Wrecks Crops  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) -- Flooding from torrential rains in recent
weeks has destroyed crops, killed thousands of cattle and left
hundreds of people homeless, the Civil Defense Office said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The rains ended a severe drought that affected a third of
Bolivia earlier this month. Rain-swollen rivers overflowed their
banks, covering fields of soy bean, cotton, corn and grapes.
</P>
<P>
   The rains have also flooded parts of the cities of Santa Cruz,
with a population one million, and Cochabamba, with a population of
450,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Civil Defense Office said the crops of 22,000 families had
been destroyed and at least 10,000 cattle killed, as well as
hundreds of people left homeless. The affected families have not
only lost their crops but are also facing severe food and potable
water shortages, the office said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States Agency for International Development and CARE
began providing emergency food supplies Monday that will reach 39
farming communities in the Bolivian lowlands.
</P>
<P>
   The Bolivian Government also began a campaign to install
emergency potable water systems in flood areas. The government is
also seeking donations of medicine and food supplies to assist
flood victims.
</P>
<P>
   The town of Bermejo, a major producer of sugar cane, and the
region of Villamontes, a natural gas and petroleum producer, were
cut off from the rest of Bolivia due to landslides.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rains have also been falling on the Bolivian highlands,
destroying roads and bridges. The main road connecting the cities
of Cochabamba and Santa Cruz have been interrupted several times
this month by landslides caused by rains.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
