<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Warns Afghanistan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The U.N. Security Council warned the
warring parties in Afghanistan on Monday not to launch spring
offensives that they are reportedly preparing.
</P>
<P>
   Council president Amwarul Chowdhury of Bangladesh admitted the
15-member council has repeatedly called for an end to fighting --
which has killed thousands and driven tens of thousands from their
homes -- but to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe the council needs to have some teeth in terms of
what it is pronouncing,'' Chowdhury said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the council was supporting peace talks organized by the
Organization of the Islamic Conference ''and will take appropriate
action ... if any breach of the peace takes place.''
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban religious army rules 90 percent of Afghanistan,
where it has imposed its strict version of Islamic law. It is
battling opposition forces based in the north.
</P>
<P>
   Francesc Vendrell, Secretary-General Kofi Annan's personal
representative to Afghanistan, said after briefing the council that
governments close to each side to urge them ''not to carry out an
offensive -- and also to stop supplying weapons to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Arabia and Pakistan are considered the main supporters of
the Taliban. Iran is believed to support the opposition alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Vendrell, who just returned from the region, said all
information coming from Afghanistan ''suggests there is a buildup --
and that there is an intention to carry out a military offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. envoy will work out of Islamabad, Pakistan, starting in
April, trying to persuade the two sides to negotiate a cease-fire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-20-00 2158 </TRAILER>
