<DOCNO> APW20000320.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leaders: Let's End China-Taiwan Feud  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM FOREMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- In their first public verbal volley,
Taiwan's next president and China's top leader agreed Monday that
they should negotiate an end to five decades of feuding -- but
neither budged on major points that have blocked talks.
</P>
<P>
   The highly anticipated statement from Chinese President Jiang
Zemin said Chen Shui-bian, who won Saturday's election despite
China's intense opposition, was welcome to come to the mainland for
talks. Beijing imposed a condition, however, repeating that Taiwan
must first recognize that it is an inseparable part of China.
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, Chinese officials tried to brand Chen, a
former Taipei mayor and opposition leader, as a radical who would
declare Taiwan independence and spark a conflict with China's
military just 80 miles across the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
   Since the two sides split amid civil war in 1949, Beijing has
given the island a choice: eventual reunification or war. A war
could quickly involve the United States, which has hinted it might
help defend the island.
</P>
<P>
   Pronouncements from Beijing often send Taiwan's stock market
plunging, but share prices climbed Tuesday, with stocks up 5
percent in early trading. Analysts said buying by government funds
and fading fears of war with China inspired the buying.
</P>
<P>
   While making courtesy calls early Tuesday, Chen did not directly
address Jiang's comments but repeated that he would ''seek lasting
peace across the Taiwan Strait.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting two days of meetings in Beijing on Monday, the United
States' U.N. ambassador, Richard Holbrooke, said Taiwan and Chen's
win would be topics of discussion. He declined to say what he would
say to Chinese officials. Stanley Roth, the top East Asian official
at the State Department, was with him.
</P>
<P>
   In a parallel diplomatic mission, former congressman Lee
Hamilton, an expert on Chinese affairs, heads to Taiwan on
Wednesday to urge restraint from the new government there.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang offered to ease tensions with Taiwan in his statement
issued by Xinhua, the official Chinese news agency.
</P>
<P>
   ''We said before and still hold today that whoever comes to
power in Taiwan, he is welcome to the mainland for talks, and we
may also go to Taiwan,'' Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Jiang repeated a long-standing condition for talks:
They can only happen if Taiwan agrees that it is an inseparable
part of China. This is known as the ''one-China principle.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen objects to the principle because he fears that if he
accepts it, he would have to agree that the ruling government of
that one China is in Beijing. This would mean that Taiwan was ruled
by a local government unequal to the undemocratic, communist
regime.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Chen repeated that he was willing to discuss ''one
China'' and anything else with Beijing, but he would not agree to
allow the principle be a condition for talks.
</P>
<P>
   ''As long as we are treated as equals, there is nothing we
cannot discuss,'' Chen told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's insistence on equality at the bargaining table squares
with the current Nationalist government's China policy, and most
Taiwanese have supported that position.
</P>
<P>
   Although the public does not favor immediate independence,
fearing it would spark a war, most Taiwanese also don't want Taiwan
to be bullied into a quick deal with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   During his campaign, Chen worked the hardest to prove to voters
that he was willing to work with Beijing. He softened his position
on independence, saying he would only put the issue to a islandwide
vote if China attacked.
</P>
<P>
   He often said that unlikely leaders -- including President Nixon
-- often produce surprising diplomatic breakthroughs. He likes to
point out that Nixon, a fervent anti-communist politician,
re-established U.S.-China ties.
</P>
<P>
   Although it seemed Taiwan-China relations were mired in a
semantic disputes that would continue during Chen's presidency, all
hope should not be lost, said James Seymour, a political scientist
at Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is possible to play around with language,'' Seymour said.
''If there is goodwill on both sides, they will be able to come up
with language both can agree on.''
</P>
<P>
   While paying courtesy calls to campaign supporters Monday, Chen
reaffirmed that he wanted to improve trade ties with China's huge,
developing market.
</P>
<P>
   Chen also said he would quickly seek a meeting with Taiwan's
respected envoy to China, Koo Chen-fu, who has had good rapport
with Beijing's envoy to Taiwan, Wang Daohan.
</P>
<P>
   Since the election, angry protesters have been surrounding the
Nationalist Party's headquarters in downtown Taipei. The crowd
swelled to 3,000 Sunday, and some broke car windows and scuffled
with police. The demonstrators dwindled to a few hundred by Monday,
but they were joined by reform-minded lawmakers who demanded Lee
resign immediately as party boss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-20-00 2217 </TRAILER>
