<DOCNO> APW20000320.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Starts Mir's Computer  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Russian mission control on Monday switched on the
main computer aboard the long-dormant space station Mir, ahead of
next month's planned return of cosmonauts to the station, the
ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Mir has been orbiting unmanned since August as the cash-strapped
space program searches for funding to keep it aloft.
</P>
<P>
   The government had said it would ditch the station this month
unless private investors came up with funds. But it later agreed to
keep Mir in orbit after Amsterdam-based MirCorp agreed to pay dlrs
10-20 million to lease commercial rights on the station.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmonauts Sergei Zaletin and Alexander Kaleri are to blast off
for the Mir on April 4, for a mission expected to last 45 days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-20-00 2236 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000320.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
