<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UCLA's Watson Expects To Play  </HEADLINE>
By KEN PETERS, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- UCLA guard Earl Watson underwent laser
surgery Monday to repair a small hole in the retina of his left
eye. His vision was fine afterward and he is expected to start the
Bruins' NCAA tournament game Thursday against Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   The retinal problem apparently existed for some time, said Dr.
Steven Schwartz, and was discovered only because Watson sustained a
blow above his eye in last Saturday's 105-70 victory over Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Watson had four stitches to close that wound, but woke up Monday
morning with the eye very sore and almost swollen shut. He had the
eye examined, and the retinal hole was discovered.
</P>
<P>
   ''Otherwise, It probably wouldn't have been found until
physicals before next season,'' Schwartz said.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor then performed the routine, 15-minute laser surgery
to repair the damage.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was stressful,'' Watson said. ''It was scary, somebody
doing something with my eye. But it was cool. Technology is
amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the elbow from Maryland's Jason Blake, Watson's eye
was still swollen half-shut late Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ''So long as he is able to see OK, I don't think it will be any
problem,'' UCLA coach Steve Lavin said of Watson, who had a school
record 16 assists, plus 17 points, including 5-of-6 from 3-point
range, and no turnovers against Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz said the retinal hole could have become a problem if it
were not repaired, thus the quick surgery. He added that Watson's
vision is unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Watson missed the Bruins' practice Monday afternoon, but came to
Pauley Pavilion with Schwartz afterward to answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he felt, the 6-foot-1 junior said, ''Actually, I'm
hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz, who performed the laser procedure at UCLA's Jules
Stein Eye Institute some five hours earlier, quipped: ''That's how
we want him, hungry -- and focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson is expected to work out with the Bruins on Tuesday as
they prepare for the matchup with Iowa State at Auburn Hills, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's ''Iron Man,'' Watson has started all 96 games during his
three-year career at the school.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
