<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Punter Bidwell Says He's Back  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Punter Josh Bidwell says he's ready to
spring a surprise on Packers coaches when he returns to practice
for the first time since being diagnosed with cancer last Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The diagnosis ended Bidwell's rookie season and started his
treatment for testicular cancer.
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday, he estimated his health at about 95 percent
recovered, and he currently is the only punter on the roster for
next season.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the coaches will be surprised about how far along I
am, given the reports that my physicians have been giving them
throughout the year,'' said Bidwell, who will work out Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm a lot further along than I imagined,'' he said. ''I'm
hitting the ball well right now, probably better than they think I
can hit them.
</P>
<P>
   ''Being nearly 100 percent right now will show them they
probably don't have to put quite as much effort into finding
another guy going into (training) camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Punting a football, though, wasn't foremost on Bidwell's mind
after he was diagnosed with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving Green Bay for his home in Eugene, Ore., to begin
the road to recovery, Bidwell said his emotions hit rock bottom.
Just the idea of cancer cells in his body took a toll on him.
</P>
<P>
   Treatment sapped his strength and made him a shell of the
well-conditioned athlete he had been.
</P>
<P>
   He came to realize punting a football isn't such an important
thing, but he wanted to get back to the NFL, and the road back
began with physical rehabilitation in December.
</P>
<P>
   Bidwell said he started lifting weights, but was limited to
5-pounders at first. He did water aerobics to regain his range of
motion, flexibility and endurance.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't sure at that time if he could return to the football
field.
</P>
<P>
   ''Going through this physically, I was in terrible shape,'' said
Bidwell, who averaged 40 yards on 11 punts during three 1999
preseason games.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really couldn't imagine myself getting back into the shape
I'm in now,'' he said. ''It seemed so far off. Once I got fully
recovered from my surgeries, I was beginning to see that I was
going to get back into good shape, maybe better shape.''
</P>
<P>
   During his recovery, Bidwell never asked the question many do
when diagnosed with a serious illness: Why me?
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew where I was going to be March 20 as compared to where I
was going to be when this started,'' said Bidwell, a fourth-round
draft pick from the University of Oregon in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''The process is tough, but I was excited about the man I was
going to be afterward. I knew that once I defeated it, I was going
to have a perspective on life and I was going to be able to see
things at face value for what they're worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, Bidwell's outlook on his life has changed. He wants
to be Green Bay's punter this season and for many more seasons, but
football holds a different place on his list of priorities.
</P>
<P>
   That is why when the Packers showed interest in San Diego punter
Darren Bennett, Bidwell wasn't disappointed. He said when the
Packers didn't sign anybody, it was somewhat a vote of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that says two things to me,'' Bidwell said. ''It says
stay on the ball, work hard, because in this profession you're
always trying to be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   ''Other than that, it shows me this organization is committed to
winning,'' he said. ''They want to get the best people in here, and
I want to prove I'm the best person to be here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
