<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Duke 90, Western Kentucky 70  </HEADLINE>
By ELIZABETH A. DAVIS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. (AP) -- Georgia Schweitzer and freshman Sheana Mosch
each scored 25 points as second-seeded Duke beat Western Kentucky
90-70 Monday in the second round of the women's NCAA East Regional.
</P>
<P>
   Duke (27-5), last year's national runner-up, advanced to its
third straight final 16. Missy West and Krista Gingrich added 11
points apiece and Rochelle Parent pulled down 11 rebounds for the
Blue Devils, who rebounded from a poor offensive showing against
Campbell in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Duke will meet third-seeded LSU, a 57-45 winner over Stephen F.
Austin, in the regional semifinal in Richmond, Va. on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Western Kentucky (22-9), seeded 10th, lost in the second round
for the second straight time and has not advanced beyond the second
round since 1986 when the Lady Toppers went to the Final Four.
ShaRae Mansfield scored 21 points and Jaime Walz and Jamie Britt
added 17 points apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Western Kentucky, with only nine active players, had rallied
from seven points down in the second half to hold on for a 68-65
win over Marquette in the first round, but they could not pull off
a repeat against Duke.
</P>
<P>
   Down by six a halftime, Western Kentucky tied the score after an
8-2 run to open the second half. During the span Britt scored two
baskets and her second made it 40-40 with 17:01 left.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lady Toppers, who had been able to score under the
basket through double-team defense earlier, started to fade despite
rallying throughout the season for wins.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils responded with a 10-1 run the next four minutes
after it was tied, and after West and Schweitzer each hit a 3, Duke
led 50-41 with 13:30 to go.
</P>
<P>
   West made another layup and Schweitzer converted a fast-break
layup to increase Duke's lead to 61-46 with 10:09 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Western Kentucky cut it to seven twice over the next five
minutes, the last at 7:12 left after Natalie Powers made two free
throws to trim the lead to 67-54.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Toppers got no closer than 67-57 at 6:43 the rest of
the way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
