<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Lawmaker Heading To Taiwan  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lee Hamilton, who became an expert on Chinese
affairs during service as an Indiana congressman, will travel to
Taiwan this week to encourage restraint after the election of a new
president whose party supports independence.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, Richard Holbrooke,
and Stanley Roth, the top East Asian official at the State
Department, are delivering the same message in Beijing. They
arrived Sunday on a visit announced two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese leaders are believed to be under pressure from the
military hierarchy to follow through on threats to take military
action against Taiwan now that the island's voters have defied
Beijing by moving closer to the path of independence.
</P>
<P>
   But administration officials have been reassured by the absence
of provocative rhetoric by the two sides since the election.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomatic missions to both Beijing and Taipei are believed
aimed at encouraging the two rivals to renew a dialogue, consistent
with long-standing administration policy. China considers the
island a province in rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   A White House official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Hamilton is leaving Wednesday for Taiwan. The official declined to
say that the former Democratic lawmaker was acting as an emissary
of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The official explanation was that Hamilton, who now heads the
Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars, is making a
private trip to Taiwan but is ''familiar with the president's
thinking and is well acquainted with the views of senior members of
Congress'' on China-Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilson Center declined all comment on Hamilton's travel
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, a political moderate who ended his 34-year
congressional career last year, once served as chairman of the
House International Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton cannot send an administration official to Taiwan. That
would violate the one-China policy that successive presidents have
pursued for years.
</P>
<P>
   National security adviser Sandy Berger, accompanying Clinton to
South Asia this week, plans to visit China at the end of that trip.
</P>
<P>
   Briefing reporters Monday in Bangladesh, Berger said, ''I think
the statements that Mr. Chen has made in the last 24 or 48 hours
have been conciliatory. The statements from the Chinese side have
been, I think, measured. And I think this is a time to now seize
upon an opportunity that exists to resume a dialogue between Taipei
and Beijing.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Senate Foreign Relations Committee chairman Jesse
Helms, R-N.C., sent a letter to Chen promising to support his
efforts to renew a dialogue with China on the basis of ''peace
through strength.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The people of Taiwan made clear this weekend that if there is
still 'one China,' there are without question two Chinese states --
one communist, one free; one whose leaders rule with an iron fist,
the other whose leaders serve at the pleasure of the people,''
Helms said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the time has come when the United States must adopt a
China policy that recognizes that Beijing must not be allowed to
follow through on its threats last week against Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   A March 6 announcement by the U.S. mission to the United Nations
said Holbrooke will remain in China from Sunday through Wednesday.
Like Hamilton, Holbrooke has strong China credentials. As a State
Department official, he was an architect of the Carter
administration's 1979 decision to open diplomatic relations with
China.
</P>
<P>
   The administration watched with unease last week as China warned
Taiwan of possible military action if voters elected as president
Chen Shui-bian, the candidate most sympathetic to independence.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the election results were announced, Clinton urged
the two sides to open a dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   ''The United States strongly supports such dialogue and is
committed to promoting peace, stability and prosperity in the
region,'' the president said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton congratulated Chen on his victory and said the election
''clearly demonstrates the strength and vitality of Taiwan's
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- AP White House Correspondent Terence Hunt
contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   State Department:
http://www.state.gov/www/regions/eap/index.html
</P>
<P>
   Library of Congress on China:
http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/cntoc.html
</P>
<P>
   American Institute in Taiwan: http://www.ait.org.tw
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Embassy in Beijing: http://www.usembassy-china.org.cn/
</P>
