<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Said To Drag Another to Death  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUMA, La. (AP) -- A woman was charged with dragging another
woman to death under her car, refusing to stop even when her
passengers told her she had hit someone.
</P>
<P>
   Lezlie Ann Fields, 20, was booked with drunken driving and
vehicular homicide and freed on $25,000 bond.
</P>
<P>
   Cheyenne Glassford, 25, of Houma, bled to death, her body
scraped raw from chest to thighs, according to Bruce Peters, chief
investigator for the parish coroner's office.
</P>
<P>
   ''Other people in the car told her she had hit someone. She just
didn't stop,'' said Col. Godfrey Buquet, spokesman for the
Terrebonne Parish sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   Glassford was dragged about a fifth of a mile from a nightclub
parking where she had tried to stop Fields early Sunday morning --
supposedly because Fields had run over another woman's foot. ''We
don't know who yet. Nobody's come forward,'' Buquet said.
</P>
<P>
   Glassford was standing next to the car when Fields turned and
drove away, knocking her down, according to a news release; in
spite of her passengers pleas to stop, Fields kept driving both
then and after the body came loose from the car, according to
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   A deputy looking for her car arrested Fields about 20 minutes
later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
