<HEADLINE> Kosovo Fallout Study Released  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The five permanent U.N. Security Council
members should lose their veto power ''in exceptional
circumstances'' to prevent another Holocaust or Rwanda genocide, a
study of political fallout from the Kosovo crisis recommended.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations University study, released Monday, said that
requiring the consent of all five permanent council members for a
humanitarian intervention could lead to paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   Or, it could lead to unilateral action -- such as NATO's air
campaign against Yugoslavia -- which violates international law and
undermines world order.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bottom line question for us is this: Faced with another
Holocaust or Rwanda-type genocide on the one hand, and a Security
Council veto on the other, what would we do?'' said Ramesh Thakur,
the university's vice rector and co-editor of the study.
</P>
<P>
   The study calls on governments to reach ''an international
consensus about the point at which a state forfeits its
sovereignty.''
</P>
<P>
   The study recommends removing the veto power of the five
permanent Security Council members -- the United States, Britain,
France, Russia and China -- in exceptional circumstances ''so that
the support of a majority of the great powers is all that is
required to permit states to engage in humanitarian war.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tokyo-based United Nations University is autonomous within
the U.N. framework and serves as a think-tank for the U.N. system.
It has no students of its own, no faculty or campus. Instead, it
operates through a worldwide network of academic and research
institutions -- including its own research and training centers -- to
address global problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-20-00 2303 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000320.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 23:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela: US OPEC Pressure OK  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- A senior Venezuelan official said
Monday that U.S. pressure on the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries to increase oil production is understandable.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a legitimate position they have,'' Deputy Oil Minister
Bernardo Alvarez said in a radio interview, referring to U.S.
efforts to convince OPEC nations to increase production in order to
reduce prices, which have reached nine-year highs.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez said during his weekly radio
program Sunday that President Clinton had asked Venezuela, an OPEC
member, to ensure that OPEC increased production soon.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez said he told Clinton that he was willing to listen to
concerns over oil prices. In return, he asked Clinton to lend an
ear to Venezuela's concern about poverty and foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
   On March 27, OPEC ministers will meet in Vienna and are widely
expected to agree on some kind of an output hike, although it's not
clear when or by how much.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuelan Oil Minister Ali Rodriguez is currently touring OPEC
countries in a bid to ensure consensus before the meeting.
Rodriguez already visited Iran, Iraq and Kuwait. He is scheduled to
travel to Algeria and Libya before arriving in Vienna March 23.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Venezuelan Vice President Isaias Rodriguez said his
country shares U.S. concern about oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   ''Excessive high oil prices could also hurt producing nations,''
Rodriguez said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
