<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Fall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices fell moderately Tuesday morning
after a three-day weekend on selling of high technology issues. The
dollar was higher against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 109.54 points, or 0.56
percent, to 19,456.78 at the end of the morning session. On Friday,
the average closed up 313.04 points, or 1.63 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 106.67 yen in late morning trading, up 0.73
yen from late Friday in Tokyo and also higher than its late New
York level of 106.36 yen.
</P>
<P>
   Financial markets in Japan were closed Monday for a national
holiday.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, prices started lower Tuesday as players
avoided making significant moves ahead of a key U.S. monetary
policy meeting scheduled later Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Market participants said they will closely monitor the U.S.
Federal Open Market Committee meeting and the impact of any
interest rate decision on volatile U.S. stock markets.
</P>
<P>
   Many Wall Street observers expect the Fed to raise interest
rates by a quarter-percentage point, the fifth increase since last
June. Higher interest rates generally send stocks lower because
they cut into corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   Traders in Tokyo said the FOMC's expected decision has already
been factored in.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the Nasdaq composite index fell 188.13 to 4,610.00
at Monday's close. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 85.01
points to close at 10,680.24.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was down 13.17 points, or 0.79 percent, to 1,661.05.
The TOPIX closed up 28.65 points, or 1.74 percent, on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, the dollar gained some ground against the
yen as foreign and domestic players sold the Japanese currency in
the absence of major market-moving news.
</P>
<P>
   But many investors were retreating to the sidelines ahead of the
Fed meeting.
</P>
<P>
   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 103.62 yen, up from
102.60 yen late Friday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose
to 1.8600 percent from Friday's finish of 1.8300. Its price fell
0.25 point to 99.49.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
