<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 23:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> D.C. Voting Right Suit Rejected  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A three-judge panel on Monday ruled against
District of Columbia citizens who filed two lawsuits seeking voting
rights in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The majority said in its 2-1 decision that while the denial of
voting representation was an inequity, the Constitution and
numerous courts have allowed the exemption.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Anthony A. Williams said he was deeply disappointed by the
U.S. District Court panel's ruling. The city intends to petition
the Supreme Court, he said, and would urge the Clinton
administration not to oppose it.
</P>
<P>
   The city has one delegate to Congress, Eleanor Holmes Norton,
but she is not allowed to vote on the House floor, nor are
representatives from other U.S. territories.
</P>
<P>
   Voting to dismiss the lawsuits were Judge Merrick Garland of the
federal Court of Appeals and District Judge Colleen Kollar-Kotelly.
Senior District Judge Lewis Oberdorfer dissented.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
