<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lithuania Ruling Party Trounced  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   VILNIUS, Lithuania (AP) -- The ruling Conservatives suffered a
major defeat in municipal elections over the weekend -- indicating
the right-wing party faces an uphill struggle to win general
elections scheduled for later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives won just 199 out of 1,667 seats on different city
and country councils contested across Lithuania, down from the 493
seats they won in the last local election in 1997, according to
preliminary results released on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the result of the Sunday poll seemed to confirm
widespread expectations that the Conservatives, in power since
1996, are headed for a crushing defeat in upcoming parliamentary
elections.
</P>
<P>
   With unemployment rising to a post-Soviet high of 11 percent and
the government implementing harsh austerity measures to rein in a
yawning budget deficit, the ruling party has seen its popularity
plummet over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest winner Sunday was the New Union, which took 270
seats. The newly formed center-left party, headed by a former
Soviet prosecutor, Arturas Paulauskas, argued during the campaign
that Lithuania was selling out to foreigners by privatizing key
state industries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
