<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tennessee 75, Arizona 60  </HEADLINE>
By DUNCAN MANSFIELD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- All-American Tamika Catchings scored 21
points, including 16 in the first half, to lead Tennessee to a
75-60 victory Monday over Arizona in the NCAA Mideast second round.
</P>
<P>
   The victory moved the six-time national champion Lady Volunteers
(30-3) into the round of 16 for the 19th consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona (25-7) exited in the second round for the second year in
a row, but with the best record in Wildcats history.
</P>
<P>
   Catchings gave the Southeastern Conference champions and
regional top seed a 4-3 lead on a driving layup through traffic
with less than two minutes gone. Arizona played catchup from then
on.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats didn't score a single fast-break point and were
outscored 18-12 by the Lady Vols on second-chance points.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona, averaging 72 percent from the free throw line, was
12-of-21 (57 percent) for the game. Tennessee was 17-of-24 (71
percent).
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee broke to a 33-21 halftime lead as Arizona struggled on
the boards, going the first 11 minutes without a rebound, and
missing eight of 10 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   Three 3-pointers by Lisa Griffith kept Arizona close in the
first half, but the Lady Vols came out running in the second
period.
</P>
<P>
   A 10-4 Tennessee run, keyed by a 3-pointer by Kara Lawson and
another by Semeka Randall, pushed the Tennessee lead to 50-31 with
11:31 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Catchings added eight rebounds to her 9-for-16 shooting. Randall
added 15 points and Lawson had 14.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Lackey led Arizona with 13 points. Griffith and Tatum
Brown had 11 each.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
