<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-20 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York Power Authority delays sale of nuclear plants  </HEADLINE>
By KATHERINE ROTH, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- After more than 10 hours of closed-door
deliberations and meetings with would-be buyers, the New York Power
Authority put off a decision late Monday to sell its two nuclear
plants, citing unresolved tax liability issues with a bid.
</P>
<P>
   The move by NYPA's board of trustees to delay continuation of
the talks until its next regular meeting, March 28 in Albany,
prolonged a bidding war for the assets between Dominion Resources
Inc., of Richmond, Va., and Entergy Nuclear LLC, of Jackson, Miss.,
the only prospective buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Entergy Nuclear is a unit of New Orleans-based Entergy Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a tax liability issue revolving around the
decommissioning fund and its transfer that leaves the Power
Authority with a potential exposure of anywhere between around $100
million to $400 million,'' NYPA spokesman Mike Petralia said.
''Entergy has resolved it. Dominion has not.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominion's Mark Lazenby gave no comment late Monday on the
status of Dominion's offer, which was slated to expire at 11:59
p.m. EST Monday, according to the terms of its proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ''We would very much like Dominion to stay in the bidding
process,'' NYPA spokesman Steve Shoenholz said, adding that he
wasn't aware of any contractual restrictions that would prevent
Dominion from continuing to participate in the auction.
</P>
<P>
   A sale of the stations would represent the largest nuclear plant
sale in the country. Assets include the 980-megawatt Indian Point 3
nuclear unit in Buchanan, N.Y., the 825-megawatt James A.
Fitzpatrick nuclear plant in Oswego, N.Y., nuclear fuel for the
stations and 1,700 staff members at the plants and at a
headquarters in White Plains.
</P>
<P>
   The money will be paid over seven years in equal annual
installments following an initial payment of $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Dominion, a latecomer to the bargaining table with an
unsolicited bid in February, had upped the stakes in a recent
bidding war for the assets with an offer made public late Friday
that it said was worth $1.52 billion, topping rival Entergy's
claimed value of $1.42 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co., which advised NYPA on the sale, set the
nominal price of Dominion's offer for the plants at $945.7 million
including fuel, or $774.8 million without fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Entergy's offer was nominally priced at $898 million, which
includes its offer for the plants and their fuel as well as
proposed decommissioning payments. The Entergy offer was nominally
priced at $636 million not including fuel.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan's evaluations were substantially lower than the
figures put forth by the two bidders because J.P. Morgan set the
value of contingent aspects of the deals at much lower levels, the
NYPA's Shoenholz said.
</P>
<P>
   Contingencies included offers to share in savings gained through
economies of scale in plant operation and decommissioning expenses,
seen through future projects and purchases, and in proposed
profit-sharing plans, he said.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan fixed the net present value of Dominion's offer for
the assets at $727 million and calculated additional speculative
economic benefits would bring the total to $786 million.
</P>
<P>
   Entergy's offer was given a net present value of $647 million,
and the company priced additional economic benefits associated with
decommissioning funds and power sales agreements at $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan vice president Harris Kretzge added that there was
only a $40 million to $50 million maximum potential difference in
the offers by the two companies.
</P>
<P>
   Dominion said last week its offer included a direct payment of
$946 million, 10 percent above Dominion's original unsolicited
offer and 17 percent above Entergy's proposed direct payment of
$806 million.
</P>
<P>
   In defending its proposal, Dominion cited a profit-sharing
agreement with the NYPA it said was worth $169 million in
speculative value if power prices top current projections, compared
with a $35 million profit-sharing pledge by Entergy.
</P>
<P>
   Dominion also touted the operating record of its two nuclear
stations in Virginia and said it was giving the transaction its
full corporate backing, whereas Entergy is a limited-liability
corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Dominion charged that the Entergy proposal had been inflated by
$100 million in phantom value related to decommissioning costs, as
well as power sales agreements.
</P>
<P>
   The original Entergy offer committed 46 percent of Fitzpatrick's
power to NYPA in 2000, decreasing to 31 percent in 2004 at $32 a
megawatt hour, the expected price in the emerging competitive power
market.
</P>
<P>
   In its increased bid, Entergy had said it offered to sell the
remaining output of the plant at $29 per megawatt hour through
2004. But Dominion said that Entergy's official offer that was due
March 10 only extended that offer through 2003.
</P>
<P>
   A winning bid would increase Dominion's nuclear holdings to six
units at four plants, including the two-unit North Anna and Surry
plants it owns and operates in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of the units to Dominion would give the company a
foothold in the U.S. northeast power market, where Entergy has
already been a successful buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Entergy approached NYPA more than two years ago about a possible
purchase of the plants. A successful bid would enlarge its
ownership portfolio to seven stations, making it the second-largest
owner of nuclear plants, behind Chicago-based Unicom Corp. and
Philadelphia-based PECO Energy Co., which have agreed to merge.
</P>
<P>
   Entergy Nuclear bought the 670-megawatt Pilgrim nuclear unit
from BEC Energy's Boston Edison Co. in July for $80 million. The
one-unit station is located in eastern Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Entergy Nuclear is also managing decommissioning activities at
the Maine Yankee plant near Wicasset, Maine, and at Northeast
Utilities' Millstone unit 1 station near Waterford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Entergy said recently it is interested in Consolidated Edison
Co. of New York's planned auction of the 980-megawatt Indian Point
2 nuclear unit.
</P>
<P>
   Entergy said its strategy of buying plants close to each other
helps the facilities share maintenance costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
